{"title_page": "Club Penguin", "text_new": "{{about||the franchise it spawned|Club Penguin (franchise)|its successor released in 2017|Club Penguin Island}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{short description|Massively multiplayer online game}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game online service\n|name                         = Club Penguin\n|title                        = ''Club Penguin''\n|image                        = Club Penguin logo.png\n|developer                    = New Horizon Interactive<br />RocketSnail Games<br />[[Disney Interactive Studios]]\n|type                         = [[Massively multiplayer online game]]\n|launched                     = {{Start date|2005|10|24}}\n|discontinued                 = {{End date|2017|3|30}}\n|platform                     = [[Online]] ([[Adobe Flash]])\n|status                       = Discontinued in favor of ''[[Club Penguin Island]]'' ({{End date|2017|03|30}})\n|members                      = \n|website                      =  [http://clubpenguin.com Club Penguin Website]\n}} (\n'''''Club Penguin''''' was a [[massively multiplayer online game]] (MMO), involving a [[virtual world]] that contained a range of online games and activities. It was created by New Horizon Interactive (now known as Disney Canada Inc.). Players used cartoon penguin-[[avatar (virtual reality)|avatars]] and played in a winter-set virtual world. After [[beta-testing]], ''Club Penguin'' was made available to the general public on October 24, 2005,<ref name=\"BillyBob2005a\">{{cite web |url=http://community.clubpenguin.com/blog/2005/10/Its-Launched.php |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429202042/http://community.clubpenguin.com/blog/2005/10/Its-Launched.php |archivedate=April 29, 2008 |title=Club Penguin&nbsp;\u2014 It's Launched! |accessdate=June 16, 2008 |author=Billybob |date=October 24, 2005 |work=Club Penguin Developer Blog |quote=}}</ref> and expanded into a large [[online community]], such that by late 2007, it was claimed ''Club Penguin'' had over 30 million user accounts.<ref name=\"Walmsley\">{{cite news|title=Kids' virtual worlds are maturing nicely|last=Walmsley|first=Andrew|date=October 24, 2007|work=Marketing}}</ref> In July 2013, ''Club Penguin'' had over 200 million registered user accounts.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |title='Star Wars' Takes Over Disney's Club Penguin |author=Graser, Marc |url=https://variety.com/2013/digital/news/star-wars-takes-over-disneys-club-penguin-1200561084/ |newspaper=Variety |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=August 15, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814113840/http://variety.com/2013/digital/news/star-wars-takes-over-disneys-club-penguin-1200561084/ |archive-date=August 14, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile free memberships were available, revenue was predominantly raised through paid memberships, which allowed players to access a range of additional features, such as the ability to purchase virtual clothing, furniture, and in-game pets called \"puffles\" for their penguins through the usage of in-game [[currency]]. The success of ''Club Penguin'' led to New Horizon being purchased by [[The Walt Disney Company]] in August 2007 for the sum of 350 million dollars, with an additional 350 million dollars in bonuses should specific targets be met by 2009.<ref name= WSJAcquire>{{cite news | title=Disney Buys Kids' Social-Network Site \u2013 WSJ.com | work=Wall Street Journal | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118599768804085026?mod=hpp_us_whats_news | accessdate=December 26, 2010 | first1=Merissa | last1=Marr | first2=Peter | last2=Sanders | date=August 2, 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307214255/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118599768804085026?mod=hpp_us_whats_news | archive-date=March 7, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe game was specifically designed for children aged 6 to 14 (however, users of any age were allowed to play ''Club Penguin'').<ref name=\"kudos\">{{cite web|date=December 11, 2006 |title=Kudos continue as Club Penguin marks one-year anniversary (Media Release) |work=Club Penguin |url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/news/061211-one-year-anniversary.htm |accessdate=June 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080420210109/http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/news/061211-one-year-anniversary.htm |archivedate=April 20, 2008 }}</ref> Thus, a major focus of the developers was on child safety,<ref name=\"Kiely\" /> with a number of features having been introduced to the game to facilitate this. These features included offering an \"Ultimate Safe Chat\" mode, whereby users selected their comments from a menu; [[Wordfilter|filtering]] that prevented swearing and the revelation of personal information;<ref name=\"Kiely\" /> and [[Forum moderator|moderators]] who patrolled the game.<ref name=\"Flanagan\" />\n\nOn January 30, 2017, it was announced that the game would be discontinued on March 29, 2017. ''Club Penguin'' later shut down its servers on March 30, 2017 at 12:01 AM [[Pacific Time|PDT]]. The game was replaced by a successor, titled ''[[Club Penguin Island]]'' (which itself was discontinued the following year).<ref name=\"CPBlog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/important-announcement-regarding-club-penguin-desktop-and-mobile-devices|title=Important Announcement Regarding Club Penguin on Desktop and Mobile Devices|first=|date=January 30, 2017|website=|publisher=Club Penguin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328202618/http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/important-announcement-regarding-club-penguin-desktop-and-mobile-devices|archive-date=March 28, 2017|url-status= |access-date=January 31, 2017|author=Megg}}</ref> Since being shut down, the original game has been hosted and recreated on a number of [[Server emulator|private servers]] using [[SWF]] files from the game's old website.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Predecessors (2000\u20132004) ===\nThe first seeds of what would become ''Club Penguin'' began as a [[Adobe Flash|Flash 4]] [[web-based]] game called ''Snow Blasters'' that developer Lance Priebe had been developing in his spare time in July 2000.<ref name=\"BDODunwoody\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bizactions.com/index.cfm/ba/e105/fa/68240602G627J357168P0P10056056T0/|title=BDO Dunwoody Announcement|work=BDO Dunwoody|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016214213/http://bizactions.com/index.cfm/ba/e105/fa/68240602G627J357168P0P10056056T0/|archivedate=October 16, 2007|accessdate=May 19, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/rocketsnail/status/289216023683547138|title=RocketSnail on Twitter|newspaper=Twitter|language=en|access-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209080023/https://twitter.com/rocketsnail/status/289216023683547138|archive-date=February 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/rocketsnail/status/350638923585843200|title=RocketSnail on Twitter|newspaper=Twitter|language=en|access-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210140826/https://twitter.com/rocketsnail/status/350638923585843200|archive-date=February 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Priebe's attention was brought to penguins after he \"happened to glance at a ''[[The Far Side|Far Side]]'' cartoon featuring penguins that was sitting on his desk\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/10/business/media/10adco.html|title=A Procession of Penguins Arrives on Madison Ave.|last=Elliott|first=Stuart|date=January 10, 2007|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201234856/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/10/business/media/10adco.html|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The project was never finished, and instead morphed into ''Experimental Penguins. Experimental Penguins'' was released through Priebe's company of employment, the [[Kelowna]], British Columbia, Canada-based online game and comic developer Rocketsnail Games, in July 2000, though it ultimately went offline the following year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rocketsnail.com/experimental-penguins|title=Experimental Penguins|website=RocketSnail|language=en-US|access-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203163749/http://rocketsnail.com/experimental-penguins|archive-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It was used as the inspiration for ''Penguin Chat'' (also known as ''Penguin Chat 1''), a similar game which was released shortly after ''Experimental Penguins''<nowiki>'</nowiki> removal. Released January 2003, ''Penguin Football Chat'' (also known as ''Penguin Chat 2)'' was the second attempt at a penguin-themed MMORPG, and was created on FLASH 5 and used the same interface as ''Experimental Penguins.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rocketsnail.com/penguin-chat/|title=Penguin Chat|website=RocketSnail|language=en-US|access-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203162414/http://rocketsnail.com/penguin-chat/|archive-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The game contained various minigames; the premiere title of RocketSnail Games was ''Ballistic Biscuit'', a game that would be placed into ''Experimental Penguins'' and eventually be adapted into ''Club Penguin''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s ''Hydro Hopper''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rocketsnail.com/games/|title=Games|website=RocketSnail|language=en-US|access-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201035125/http://rocketsnail.com/games|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> RocketSnails Games' ''Mancala Classic'' would also be placed into the game as ''Mancala''.\n\nLance Priebe, as well as co-workers Lane Merrifield and Dave Krysko, started to formulate the ''Club Penguin'' concept when the trio were unsuccessful in finding \"something that had some social components but was safe, and not just marketed as safe\" for their own children.<ref name=\"Mlynek\">{{cite news|url=http://www.canadianbusiness.com/managing/ceo_interviews/article.jsp?content=20080428_198723_198723 |title=Q&A: Club Penguin's Lane Merrifield |last=Mlynek |first=Alex |date=April 28, 2008 |work=[[Canadian Business]] |accessdate=May 16, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219060236/http://www.canadianbusiness.com/managing/ceo_interviews/article.jsp?content=20080428_198723_198723 |archivedate=December 19, 2008 |df= }}</ref> Dave Krysko in particular wanted to build a safe social-networking site their kids could enjoy free of advertising.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/about|title=About Club Penguin|newspaper=Club Penguin|language=en|access-date=January 19, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131182951/http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/about|archivedate=January 31, 2017}}</ref> In 2003, Merrifield and Priebe approached their boss, with the idea of creating a spinoff company to develop the new product.<ref name=\"McKenna\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/children-and-penguins-turn-trio-into-kingpins/article18176636/|title=Children and penguins turn trio into kingpins|last=McKenna|first=Barrie|date=November 13, 2006|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|location=Toronto|accessdate=May 16, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160218111840/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/children-and-penguins-turn-trio-into-kingpins/article18176636/|archive-date=February 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The spin-off company would be known as New Horizon Interactive.\n\n=== Early history (2004\u20132007) ===\nWork commenced on the project in 2004, and the team settled on a name in the summer of 2005.<ref name=\":2\" /> The developers used the previous project ''Penguin Chat 2''&nbsp;\u2013 which was still online&nbsp;\u2013 as a jumping-off point in the design process, while incorporating concepts and ideas from Experimental Penguins. Penguin Chat's third version was released in April 2005, and was used to test the client and servers of ''Penguin Chat 4'' (renamed ''Club Penguin'').<ref name=\"Priebe\">{{cite web|url=http://rocketsnail.com/blog/2011/02/21/experimenting-with-penguins/|title=Experimenting with Penguins|last=Priebe|first=Lance|work=Rocketsnail Games|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429222843/http://rocketsnail.com/blog/2011/02/21/experimenting-with-penguins/|archive-date=April 29, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Variants of ''Penguin Chat 3'' included ''Crab Chat, Chibi Friends Chat, Goat Chat, Ultra-Chat, and TV Chat.'' Users from Penguin Chat were invited to beta test ''Club Penguin''. The original plan was to release ''Club Penguin'' in 2010, but since the team had decided to fast-track the project, the first version of ''Club Penguin'' went live on October 24, 2005,<ref name=\"Priebe\" /> just after Penguin Chat servers were shut down in August 2005. While Penguin Chat used ElectroServer, ''Club Penguin'' would use SmartFoxServer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/rocketsnail/status/223980934335180800|title=RocketSnail on Twitter|newspaper=Twitter|language=en|access-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211041756/https://twitter.com/rocketsnail/status/223980934335180800|archive-date=February 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The developers financed their start-up entirely with their own credit cards and personal lines of credit, and maintained 100 percent ownership.<ref name=\"Jordan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bcbusiness.ca/people/lane-merrifield-club-penguin|title=Lane Merrifield: Club Penguin|last=Jordan|first=David|date=April 1, 2008|work=[[BCBusiness Online]]|location=Toronto|accessdate=November 28, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203033854/http://www.bcbusiness.ca/people/lane-merrifield-club-penguin|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Club Penguin'' started with 15,000 users, and by March that number had reached 1.4 million\u2014a figure which almost doubled by September, when it hit 2.6 million.<ref name=\"McKenna\" /> By the time ''Club Penguin'' was two years old, it had reached 3.9 million users, despite lacking a marketing budget.<ref name=\"Shields\">{{cite journal|last=Shields|first=Mike|year=2007|title=Avatar Nation|journal=MediaWeek|volume=17|issue=44}}</ref> The first mention of the game in The New York Times was in October 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/27/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/29Rparenting.html|title=Halloween, Unmasked|last=Winerip|first=Michael|date=October 27, 2006|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201235545/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/27/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/29Rparenting.html|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The following year, ''Club Penguin'' spokesperson Karen Mason explained: \"We offer children the training wheels for the kinds of activities they might pursue as they get older.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/03/fashion/03Online.html|title=Online sites-online sites for children|last=Slatalla|first=Michelle|date=May 3, 2007|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201234946/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/03/fashion/03Online.html|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Acquisition by Disney (2007) ===\nAlthough the three ''Club Penguin'' co-creators had turned down lucrative advertising offers and venture capital investments in the past,<ref name=\"McKenna\" /> in August 2007, they agreed to sell both ''Club Penguin'' and its parent company to [[Disney]] for the sum of $350.93 million.<ref name=\"Walmsley\" /> In addition, the owners were promised bonuses of up to $350 million if they were able to meet growth targets by 2009.<ref name=\"Brooks\">{{cite news | last = Brooks | first = Barnes | date = August 2, 2007 | title = Wary of Losing Out Online, Disney Buys Site for Children up to ages from 6 to 16 | work = [[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Disney ultimately didn't pay the extra $350 million, as ''Club Penguin'' missed both profit goals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/119491/Disney_Skips_350M_Payment_As_Club_Penguin_Misses_Profit_Targets.php|title=Disney Skips $350M Payment As  Club Penguin  Misses Profit Targets|last=Caoili|first=Eric|language=en|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202000835/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/119491/Disney_Skips_350M_Payment_As_Club_Penguin_Misses_Profit_Targets.php|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/13/business/media/13penguin.html|title=Disney Gets a Half-Price Deal for Club Penguin|last=Barnes|first=Brooks|date=May 12, 2010|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201234646/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/13/business/media/13penguin.html|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> At the point when it was purchased by Disney, ''Club Penguin'' had 11\u201312 million accounts, of which 700,000 were paid subscribers, and was generating $40 million in annual revenue.<ref name=\"Walmsley\" /><ref name=\"Jordan\" /> In making the sale, Merrifield has stated that their main focus during negotiations was philosophical,<ref name=\"Mlynek\" /> and that the intent was to provide themselves with the needed infrastructure in order to continue to grow.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}} By late 2007, it was claimed that ''Club Penguin'' had over 30 million user accounts.<ref name=\"Walmsley\" /> In December of that year, The New York Times asserted that the game \"attracts seven times more traffic than [[Second Life]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/31/business/31virtual.html|title=Web Playgrounds of the Very Young|last=Barnes|first=Brooks|date=December 31, 2007|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201234438/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/31/business/31virtual.html|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Club Penguin'' was the 8th top social networking site in April 2008, according to Nielsen.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/nielsen-myspace-club-penguin-growth-static-linkedin-soaring/|title=Nielsen: MySpace, Club Penguin growth static, LinkedIn soaring|newspaper=CNET|language=en|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201235853/https://www.cnet.com/news/nielsen-myspace-club-penguin-growth-static-linkedin-soaring/|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter Disney's acquisition, Disney Interactive had four MMOs to simultaneously juggle: ''[[Toontown Online|ToonTown]]'', ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean Online]]'', ''[[Pixie Hollow (video game)|Pixie Hollow]]'', and ''Club Penguin'', with ''[[The World of Cars Online|World of Cars]]'' set to follow soon. Lane Merrifield assured GlobalToyNews at the time that \"it's a lot of worlds to manage, but we have really strong teams.\" Merrifield's role changed from taking a backseat in daily game design to focusing on overall branding and quality control of the virtual gaming properties. One of his roles was to merge the ''Club Penguin'' studio New Horizon Interactive in Kelowna (renamed to Disneyland Studios Canada) with Disneyland Studios LA. Disneyland Studios Canada focused its efforts on one product (with such features as multilingual versions), while Disneyland Studios LA focused on customer products and franchises of a wide selection of games. Merrifield was responsible for cross-pollinating both cultures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaltoynews.com/2010/08/an-interview-with-lane-merrifield-creator-of-club-penguin-.html|title=An Interview with Lane Merrifield; creator of Club Penguin \u2013 Global Toy News|website=www.globaltoynews.com|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201234723/http://www.globaltoynews.com/2010/08/an-interview-with-lane-merrifield-creator-of-club-penguin-.html|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Franchising and growth (2007\u20132015) ===\nSince the Disney purchase, ''Club Penguin'' continued to grow, becoming part of a larger franchise including video games, books, a television special, an anniversary song, and an app MMO. Disney has often used the game as a cross-promotion opportunity when releasing new films such as ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]],'' ''[[Zootopia]],'' and ''[[Star Wars]],'' having special themed events and parties to celebrate their releases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kidscreen.com/2014/08/19/club-penguin-gets-frozen/|title=Club Penguin gets Frozen|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131192413/http://kidscreen.com/2014/08/19/club-penguin-gets-frozen/|archive-date=January 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/zootopia-party-announcement|title=Zootopia Party Announcement|date=April 28, 2016|newspaper=Club Penguin|language=en|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201110014/http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/zootopia-party-announcement|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2013/digital/news/star-wars-takes-over-disneys-club-penguin-1200561084/|title='Star Wars' Takes Over Disney's Club Penguin|last=Graser|first=Marc|date=July 11, 2013|newspaper=Variety|language=en-US|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131200312/http://variety.com/2013/digital/news/star-wars-takes-over-disneys-club-penguin-1200561084/|archive-date=January 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The game forged an ever-growing mythology of characters and plot elements, including: a pirate, a journalist, and a secret agent.\n\nIn 2008, the first international office opened in Brighton, England, to personalise the level of moderation and player support. Later international office locations included S\u00e3o Paulo and Buenos Aires.<ref name=\":0\" /> On March 11, 2008, ''Club Penguin'' released the ''Club Penguin'' Improvement Project.<ref name=\"BillyBob2008a\">{{cite web | last = BillyBob | date = March 10, 2008 | title = Welcome!! | work = Club Penguin Improvement Project: Blog | url = http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/03/welcome-to-the-club-penguin-im.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080421205905/http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/03/welcome-to-the-club-penguin-im.html | archivedate = April 21, 2008 | accessdate = May 19, 2007}}</ref> This project allowed players to be part of the testing of new servers, which were put into use in ''Club Penguin'' on April 14, 2008.<ref name=\"BillyBob2008d\">{{cite web | last = BillyBob | date = April 14, 2008 | title = New website and new servers | work = Club Penguin Improvement Project: Blog | url = http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/04/new-website-and-new-servers.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080420170611/http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/04/new-website-and-new-servers.html | archivedate = April 20, 2008 | accessdate = May 19, 2007}}</ref> Players had a \"clone\" of their penguin made, to test these new servers for bugs and glitches.<ref name=\"BillyBob2008b\">{{cite web | last = BillyBob | date = March 10, 2008 | title = Account Questions | work = Club Penguin Improvement Project: Blog | url = http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/03/account-questions.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080421205844/http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/03/account-questions.html | archivedate = April 21, 2008 | accessdate = May 19, 2007}}</ref> The testing was ended on April 4, 2008.<ref name=\"BillyBob2008c\">{{cite web | last = BillyBob | date = April 4, 2008 | title = Server Test Success!! | work = Club Penguin Improvement Project: Blog | url = http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/04/server-test-success.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080421041844/http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/04/server-test-success.html | archivedate = April 21, 2008 | accessdate = May 19, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn June 20, 2011, the game's website temporarily crashed after the company let the ''Club Penguin'' domain name expire.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2011/06/club-penguin-downtime-is-only-disneys-latest-internet-misstep/240752/|title=Club Penguin Downtime Is Only Disney's Latest Internet Misstep|last=Jackson|first=Nicholas|newspaper=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131195315/http://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2011/06/club-penguin-downtime-is-only-disneys-latest-internet-misstep/240752/|archive-date=January 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2011, one of Club Penguin's minigames, Puffle Launch, was released on iOS as an app. Merrifield commented: \"Kids are going mobile and have been asking for Club Penguin to go there with them.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/technology-science/technology/disneys-club-penguin-celebrates-150-186884|title=Disney's Club Penguin Celebrates 150 million users by launching new app|last=Mirror.co.uk|date=September 15, 2011|newspaper=mirror|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202113740/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/technology-science/technology/disneys-club-penguin-celebrates-150-186884|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2012, Merrifield left Disney Interactive to focus on his family and a new educational product, Freshgrade. Chris Heatherly took Merrifield's former position.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/oct/17/entertainment/la-et-ct-disney-interactive-club-penguin-20121017 | title=Disney Interactive loses Club Penguin founder Lane Merrifield | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | first1=Dawn C. | last1=Chmielewski | first2=Ben | last2=Fritz | date=October 17, 2012 | accessdate=January 17, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170331143426/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/oct/17/entertainment/la-et-ct-disney-interactive-club-penguin-20121017 | archive-date=March 31, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> The company dropped the words \"Online Studios\" from its name<ref>{{cite web |title=Club Penguin Trademark Details |url=http://trademarks.justia.com/850/69/club-penguin-85069142.html |date=November 20, 2013 |accessdate=December 27, 2013 |publisher=Justia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228072829/http://trademarks.justia.com/850/69/club-penguin-85069142.html |archive-date=December 28, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/privacy-policy/en |title=Privacy Policy |publisher=Club Penguin |accessdate=December 27, 2013 |date=November 1, 2013 |quote=Disney Club Penguin (\"Club Penguin\") is operated and presented to users in all locations by Disney Canada Inc. (formerly known as Disney Online Studios Canada Inc.)... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226133601/http://www.clubpenguin.com/privacy-policy/en |archive-date=December 26, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> in 2013. As of July 2013, ''Club Penguin'' had over 200 million registered user accounts.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2013, ''Club Penguin'' hired singer and former ''Club Penguin'' player [[Jordan Fisher]] to record a song entitled ''It's Your Birthday'', to commemorate Club Penguin's 8th anniversary.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/blog/2013/10/exclusive-interview-jordan-fisher|title=Exclusive Interview with Jordan Fisher!|date=October 23, 2013|newspaper=Club Penguin|language=en|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202034242/http://www.clubpenguin.com/blog/2013/10/exclusive-interview-jordan-fisher|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Decline and discontinuation (2015\u20132017) ===\n[[File:The Penguin Times.jpg|thumb|400x400px|This message was provided by Aunt Arctic (a proxy for Club Penguin developers) in the last issue of the in-universe newspaper The Penguin Times. It nostalgically looks back on the game's 12-year history, comments on how far the community has grown, and has an optimistic view on the future for its members.]]\n\nIn April 2015, it was revealed that Disney Interactive had [[Layoff|laid off]] 28 members of ''Club Penguin''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Kelowna headquarters due to the game's declining popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techvibes.com/2016/03/05/layoffs-club-penguin-2016-03-05|title=Disney Canada Hit by Layoffs \u2013 More to Come?|date=March 5, 2016|website=Techvibes|access-date=September 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921020905/https://techvibes.com/2016/03/05/layoffs-club-penguin-2016-03-05|archive-date=September 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The company's UK office in Brighton was shut down around April 17, 2015. Some employees in the [[Los Angeles]] office were also let go. Disney Interactive replied to Castanet on the layoffs: \"Disney Interactive continually looks to find ways to create efficiencies and streamline our operations. As part of this ongoing process, we are consolidating a small number of teams and are undergoing a targeted reduction in workforce.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.castanet.net/news/Kelowna/137843/Club-Penguin-cuts-jobs|title=Club Penguin cuts jobs \u2013 Kelowna News|website=www.castanet.net|access-date=April 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429223753/http://www.castanet.net/news/Kelowna/137843/Club-Penguin-cuts-jobs|archive-date=April 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn September 2, 2015, ''Club Penguin'' closed down the [[German language|German]] and [[Russian language|Russian]] versions of the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/blog/2015/06/important-news-about-club-penguin-russian-and-german-languages|title=Important News About Club Penguin in the Russian and German Languages|website=Club Penguin|access-date=April 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420234558/http://www.clubpenguin.com/blog/2015/06/important-news-about-club-penguin-russian-and-german-languages|archive-date=April 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> A spin-off mobile app, Puffle Wild, was removed from the [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] and [[Google Play]] the same day in order to allow Disney Interactive to focus on Club Penguin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://help.disney.com/articles/en_US/FAQ/About-Puffle-Wild?section=clubpenguin|title=Disney Interactive Support \u2013 Puffle Wild Closure|date=September 5, 2015|access-date=April 9, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905223247/https://help.disney.com/articles/en_US/FAQ/About-Puffle-Wild?section=clubpenguin|archivedate=September 5, 2015}}</ref> On January 11, 2016, the Sled Racer and SoundStudio apps (the former being an original game and the latter being a [[Porting|port]] of a game on the website) followed suit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/important-information-regarding-sled-racer-soundstudio-apps|title=Important Information Regarding Sled Racer & SoundStudio Apps|website=Club Penguin|access-date=April 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405071902/http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/important-information-regarding-sled-racer-soundstudio-apps|archive-date=April 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> With the closure of Disney Interactive in 2015, ''Club Penguin'' side-projects wound down to allow a streamlined effort to focus on the core ''Club Penguin'' experience; this involved the layoffs of 30 Disney Studios Canada staff.<ref name=\"Wawro\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/241587/Report_Layoffs_strike_Disneys_Club_Penguin.php|title=Report: Layoffs strike Disney's  Club Penguin|last=Wawro|first=Alex|language=en|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131194538/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/241587/Report_Layoffs_strike_Disneys_Club_Penguin.php|archive-date=January 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 30, 2017, ''Club Penguin'' announced that the current game would be discontinued on March 29, 2017, to make way for its successor, ''[[Club Penguin Island]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/01/31/club-penguin-is-shutting-down/|title=Club Penguin is shutting down|last=Perez|first=Sarah|date=January 31, 2017|website=TechCrunch|access-date=February 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206184552/https://techcrunch.com/2017/01/31/club-penguin-is-shutting-down/|archive-date=February 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2017/1/31/14458168/club-penguin-closing|title=Club Penguin set to close, breaking millennial hearts worldwide|last=Frank|first=Allegra|date=January 31, 2017|website=Polygon|access-date=February 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203191158/http://www.polygon.com/2017/1/31/14458168/club-penguin-closing|archive-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2017/01/31/club-penguin-shutting-down-and-everyone-sad/97277620/|title=Club Penguin is shutting down and everyone is sad|last=Molina|first=Brett|date=January 31, 2017|newspaper=USA Today|access-date=February 5, 2017|work=|language=en|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202204217/http://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2017/01/31/club-penguin-shutting-down-and-everyone-sad/97277620/|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Membership payments for the original game were no longer accepted as of January 31, 2017, with paid members slated to receive emails about membership and refunds.<ref name=\"CPBlog\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.idigitaltimes.com/club-penguin-shutting-down-mobile-only-club-penguin-island-take-its-place-582155|title='Club Penguin' Shutting Down; Mobile-Only 'Club Penguin Island' To Take Its Place|last=Medina|first=Nathalie|date=February 2, 2017|newspaper=iDigitalTimes.com|access-date=February 5, 2017|work=|language=en|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205055603/http://www.idigitaltimes.com/club-penguin-shutting-down-mobile-only-club-penguin-island-take-its-place-582155|archive-date=February 5, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIt became popular in the final weeks of Club Penguin to attempt [[speedrun]]s to see how fast users could get banned from the site; the fastest records were [[tool-assisted speedrun]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2017/2/22/14698354/club-penguin-ban-speedruns|title=Getting banned from Club Penguin is now a competitive sport|date=February 22, 2017|website=Polygon|access-date=March 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317233507/http://www.polygon.com/2017/2/22/14698354/club-penguin-ban-speedruns|archive-date=March 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDays before the shut down, ''Club Penguin'' announced that on the final day of the game's operation, all users would be given a free membership until the servers were disconnected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/waddle-party-finale-meet-times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326053454/http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/waddle-party-finale-meet-times|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 26, 2017|title=Waddle On Party: Finale Meet-Up Times {{!}} Club Penguin|date=March 26, 2017|access-date=September 23, 2018}}</ref>\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Club Penguin Final Seconds.jpeg|thumb|250px|Penguins gathered around town in the server Blizzard seconds before the shut down of the ''Club Penguin'' servers.]] -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Club Penguin Lost Connection.jpg|thumb|250px|The message that displayed on users' webpages when the ''Club Penguin'' servers disconnected.]] -->\n\nOn March 30, 2017, at 12:01:39 AM [[Pacific Time|PDT]] (7:01:39 AM {{Abbr|UTC|Universal Coordinated Time}}), ''Club Penguin''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s servers were officially shut down.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://thespartanstandard.com/2017/04/farewell-club-penguin/ |title=Farewell, Club Penguin |date=April 18, 2017 |access-date=October 3, 2018 |newspaper=The Spartan Standard |publisher=[[Bainbridge High School (Washington)|Bainbridge High School]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003014208/https://thespartanstandard.com/2017/04/farewell-club-penguin/ |archive-date=October 3, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\n\n=== Business model ===\nPrior to being purchased by Disney, ''Club Penguin'' was almost entirely dependent on membership fees to produce a revenue stream.<ref name=\"Kiely\">{{cite news | last = Kiely | first = Lynsey | date = January 14, 2007 | title = C-c-c-click on clubpenguin | work = [[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]] | url = http://www.independent.ie/national-news/cccclick-on-clubpenguin-120865.html | accessdate = May 25, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080516060149/http://www.independent.ie/national-news/cccclick-on-clubpenguin-120865.html | archive-date = May 16, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref> The vast majority of users (90% according to [[The Washington Post]]) chose not to pay, instead taking advantage of the free play on offer.<ref name=\"Reid\">{{cite news | last = Reid | first = Alice | date = October 18, 2007 | title = Breaking the Ice&nbsp;&nbsp;\u2014 Club Penguin Allows Kids to Safely Explore the World of Online Gaming and Chatting | work = [[The Washington Post]] | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/10/17/AR2007101702198.html | accessdate = May 25, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110628204724/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/10/17/AR2007101702198.html | archive-date = June 28, 2011 | url-status = live }}</ref> Those who chose to pay did so because full (paid) membership was required to access all of the services, such as the ability to purchase virtual clothes for the penguins and buy decorations for igloos,<ref name=\"Navarro\">{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/28/fashion/28virtual.html | last = Navarro | first = Mireya | date = October 28, 2007 | title = Pay Up, Kid, or Your Igloo Melts | work = [[The New York Times]] | access-date = February 21, 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170201235627/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/28/fashion/28virtual.html | archive-date = February 1, 2017 | url-status = live }}</ref> and because peer pressure created a \"[[caste system]],\" separating paid from unpaid members.<ref name=\"Robertson\">{{cite journal | last = Robertson | first = Heather-Jane | year = 2007 | title = Postman Does Penguins | journal = [[Phi Delta Kappan]] | volume = 88 | issue = 5}}</ref> Advertising, both [[In-game advertising|in-game]] and on-site, was not incorporated into the system, although some competitors chose to employ it, including: [[Whyville]], which used corporate sponsorship,<ref name=\"Diaz\">{{cite news | last = Diaz | first = Sam | author2 = Yang, Xiyun | date = August 3, 2007 | title = Playground Networking, Now Online&nbsp;\u2014 Social Sites Aim at Users Too Young for MySpace | work = [[The Washington Post]] | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/02/AR2007080202351.html | accessdate = May 25, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110628204818/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/02/AR2007080202351.html | archive-date = June 28, 2011 | url-status = live }}</ref> and [[Neopets]], which incorporated product placements.<ref name=\"Rushe\">{{cite news | last = Rushe | first = Dominic | date = November 18, 2007 | title = Hooking the kids with the internet | work = [[The Sunday Times]] | url = http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/technology/article2889446.ece | accessdate = May 25, 2008 | location = London | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090508151627/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/technology/article2889446.ece | archive-date = May 8, 2009 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nAn alternative revenue stream came through the development of an online merchandise shop, which opened on the ''Club Penguin'' website in August 2006,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://community.clubpenguin.com/blog/2006/08/NOW-OPEN.php | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080429194151/http://community.clubpenguin.com/blog/2006/08/NOW-OPEN.php | archivedate = April 29, 2008 | title = NOW OPEN!!! | accessdate = June 17, 2008 |author=Billybob | date= August 31, 2006 | work = Club Penguin Developer Blog}}</ref> selling stuffed [[#Puffles|Puffles]] and T-shirts. Key chains, gift cards, and more shirts were added on November 7, 2006.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://community.clubpenguin.com/blog/2006/12/Lots-of-New-Stuff.php | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080421162623/http://community.clubpenguin.com/blog/2006/12/Lots-of-New-Stuff.php | archivedate = April 21, 2008 | title = Lots of New Stuff!! | accessdate = June 17, 2008 | author = Billybob | date = November 7, 2006 |work = Club Penguin Developer Blog}}</ref> In October 2008, a series of [[plush toys]] based on characters from ''Club Penguin,'' were made available online (both through the ''Club Penguin'' store and Disney's online store), and in retail outlets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/news/102408-new-consumer-products.htm |title=New Consumer Products Extend Club Penguin Offline (Press release) |accessdate=December 4, 2008 |date=October 24, 2008 |work=Club Penguin |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113192817/http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/news/102408-new-consumer-products.htm |archivedate=November 13, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAs with one of its major rivals, ''[[Webkinz]]'', ''Club Penguin'' traditionally relied almost entirely on [[word-of-mouth]] advertising to increase its membership base.<ref name=\"Garofoli\">{{cite news | last = Garofoli | first = Joe | date = May 27, 2007 | title = I'm 8, I'm late for an online date with a cuddly penguin | work = [[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Child safety ===\n''Club Penguin'' was designed for the ages of 6\u201314.<ref name=\"kudos\" /> Thus, one of the major concerns when designing ''Club Penguin'' was how to improve both the safety of participants and the suitability of the game to children. As Lane Merrifield stated, \"the decision to build Club Penguin grew out of a desire to create a fun, virtual world that I and the site's other two founders would feel safe letting our own children visit.\"<ref name=\"Merrifield\">{{cite journal|last=Merrifield|first=Lane|year=2007|title=Safety First?|journal=[[The Atlantic Monthly]]|volume=300|issue=3|page=17|author2=Males, Mike|author3=Flanagan, Caitlin}}</ref> As a result, ''Club Penguin'' maintained a strong focus on child safety,<ref name=\"Jesdanun\">{{cite news|title=Safety questioned as younger kids flock to Internet&nbsp;\u2014 Parents need to set guidelines, limits|last=Jesdanun|first=Anick|date=July 23, 2007|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> to the point where the security features were described as almost \"fastidious\" and \"reminiscent of an [[Orwellian]] [[dystopia]]\",<ref name=\"Williamson\">{{cite news|title=Why Many Children Are Now Picking a Penguin as Their Favourite Online Friend|last=Williamson|first=David|date=January 5, 2008|work=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]}}</ref> although it was also argued that this focus might \"reassure more parents than it alienate[d].\"<ref name=\"Williamson\" />\n\nThe system employed a number of different approaches in an attempt to improve child safety. The key approaches included preventing the use of inappropriate [[usernames]];<ref name=\"Reidb\">{{cite news|title=Safe surfing: Club Penguin is a G-rated MySpace-type site that gives kids a safer way to mingle online|last=Reid|first=Alice|date=October 18, 2007|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> providing an \"Ultimate Safe Chat\" mode, which limited players to selecting phrases from a list;<ref name=\"Jesdanun\" /> using an automatic [[Wordfilter|filter]] during \"Standard Safe Chat\" (which allowed users to generate their own messages)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/parents/club_penguin_guide.htm#safe|title=Is It Safe?|accessdate=June 17, 2008|work=Club Penguin Q&A for Parents|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705192151/http://www.clubpenguin.com/parents/club_penguin_guide.htm#safe|archive-date=July 5, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> and blocked [[profanity]] even when users employed \"creative\" methods to insert it into sentences;<ref name=\"Reidb\" /> filtering seemingly innocuous terms, such as \"mom\"; and blocking both telephone numbers and email addresses.<ref name=\"Jesdanun\" /> It also included employing paid [[Forum moderator|moderators]]; out of 100 staff employed in the company in May 2007, Merrifield estimated that approximately 70 staff were dedicated to policing the game.<ref name=\"Garofoli\" /> It also included promoting users to \"EPF (Elite Penguin Force) Agent\" status, and encouraging them to report inappropriate behavior.<ref name=\"Jesdanun\" />\n\nEach game server offered a particular type of chat\u2014the majority allowing either chat mode, but some servers allowed only the \"Ultimate Safe Chat\" mode. When using \"Standard Safe Chat\", all comments made by users were filtered. When a comment was blocked, the user who made the comment saw it, but other users were unaware that it was made\u2014suggesting to the \"speaker\" that they were being ignored, rather than encouraging them to try to find a way around the restriction.<ref name=\"Jesdanun\" />\n\nBeyond these primary measures, systems were in place to limit the amount of time spent online, and the site did not feature any advertisements, because, as described by Merrifield, \"within two or three clicks, a kid could be on a gambling site or an adult dating site.\"<ref name=\"Garofoli\" /> Nevertheless, after ''Club Penguin'' was purchased by Disney, concerns were raised that this state of affairs might change, especially in regard to potential spin-off products<ref name=\"Dwyer\">{{cite news|title=Virtual kids|last=Dwyer|first=Michael|date=November 29, 2007|work=[[The Age]]}}</ref>\u2014although Disney continued to insist that it believed advertising to be \"inappropriate\" for a young audience.<ref name=\"Rushe\" />\n\nPlayers who used profanity were often punished by an automatic 24-hour ban, although not all vulgar language resulted in an immediate ban. Players found by moderators to have broken ''Club Penguin'' rules were punished by a ban lasting \"from 24 hours to forever depending on the offense.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.clubpenguin.com/help/help/safety.htm|title=\"Breaking the Rules\" and \"How a Penguin is Banned\"|quote=|accessdate=June 17, 2008|work=Club Penguin Communicating|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723123728/http://support.clubpenguin.com/help/help/safety.htm|archivedate=July 23, 2008|df=}}</ref>\n\n=== Education and charity ===\nCoins for Change was an in-game charity fund-raising event which first appeared in 2007. The fund-raising lasted for approximately two weeks each December during the game's annual \"Holiday Party\". Players could \"donate\" their virtual coins to vote for three charitable issues: Kids who were sick, the environment, and kids in developing countries.<ref name=\"coins for change 2007 whattheyplay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.whattheyplay.com/blog/2008/12/10/coins-for-change-kicks-off-this-friday/|title=What They Play \u2013 Coins for Change kicks off this Friday|work=What They Play|accessdate=February 15, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231212056/http://www.whattheyplay.com/blog/2008/12/10/coins-for-change-kicks-off-this-friday/|archivedate=December 31, 2009}}</ref> Players were able to donate in increments of 100, 250, 500, 1,000, 5,000, or 10,000 virtual coins. At the end of the campaign, a set amount of real-world money was divided among each of the causes based on the amount of in-game currency each cause received. At the end of the first campaign, the New Horizon Foundation donated a total of $1 million to the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]], the [[Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS Foundation]], and [[Free The Children]].<ref name=\"coins for change 2007 whattheyplay\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/12/29/AR2007122901848_pf.html|title=For Modern Kids, 'Philanthropy' Is No Grown-Up Word|last=Rucker|first=Philip|date=December 30, 2007|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 22, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927172236/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/12/29/AR2007122901848_pf.html|archive-date=September 27, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In both the 2007 and 2008 campaigns, two-and-a-half million players participated.<ref name=\"coins for change 2007 whattheyplay\" /><ref name=\"coins for change 2008 whattheyplay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.whattheyplay.com/blog/2008/12/25/club-penguin-kids-donate-3-billion-in-game-coins-t/|title=What They Play \u2013 Club Penguin kids donate 3 billion in-game coins to charity|work=What They Play|accessdate=February 15, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231212005/http://www.whattheyplay.com/blog/2008/12/25/club-penguin-kids-donate-3-billion-in-game-coins-t/|archivedate=December 31, 2009}}</ref> In 2009, ''Club Penguin'' donated $1,000,000 Canadian dollars to charitable projects around the world. In 2010, ''Club Penguin'' donated $300,000 towards building safe places, $360,000 towards protecting the Earth, and $340,000 towards providing medical help. Lane Merrifield said: \"Our players are always looking for ways to make a difference and help others, and over the past five years they've embraced the opportunity to give through Coins For Change, it was exciting to see kids from 191 countries participate together.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/news/01-01-12-coins-for-change.htm|title=Virtual world celebrates fifth year of Coins For Change|work=celebrates fifth year|accessdate=February 15, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125092513/http://www.clubpenguin.com//company/news/01-01-12-coins-for-change.htm|archivedate=January 25, 2012}}</ref> In 2011, the amount of money donated was doubled to $2 million, ostensibly in response to an unexpected increase in participation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/global-citizenship/coins-for-change-2011|title=Coins For Change 2011|last=|first=|authorlink=|year=2011|publisher=Club Penguin|format=|doi=|work=|access-date=September 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920025046/http://www.clubpenguin.com/global-citizenship/coins-for-change-2011|archive-date=September 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Plot and gameplay ==\n''Club Penguin'' was divided into various rooms and distinct areas. Illustrator Chris Hendricks designed many of the first environments. Each player was provided with an igloo for a home. Members had the option of opening their igloo so other penguins could access it via the map, under \"Member Igloos.\"{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}} Members could also purchase larger igloos and decorate their igloos with items bought with virtual coins earned by playing mini-games.<ref name=\"Reid\" /> At least one party per month was held on Club Penguin. In most cases, a free clothing item was available, both for paid members and free users. Some parties also provided member-only rooms which only paid members could access. Some major ''Club Penguin'' parties were its annual [[Halloween]] and Holiday parties. Other large parties included the Music Jam, the Adventure Party, the Puffle Party, and the Medieval Party.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n== Franchise ==\n{{Main|Club Penguin (franchise)}}\nDisney's franchising of the brand began with its acquisition of ''Club Penguin'' in 2007. In addition to the ''Club Penguin Island'' web-based video game,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://kotaku.com/club-penguin-island-to-shut-down-marking-final-end-of-1829370171 |title=Club Penguin Island To Shut Down, Marking Final End Of The Beloved Children's MMO |date=September 27, 2018 |last=D'Anastasio |first=Cecilia |website=Kotaku |access-date=November 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205185831/https://kotaku.com/club-penguin-island-to-shut-down-marking-final-end-of-1829370171 |archive-date=December 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> the franchise has also included console video games for [[Nintendo DS]] and [[Wii]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/tech/columnist/jinnygudmundsen/2008-12-11-club-penguin_N.htm |title=Join 'Elite Penguin Force' on Nintendo DS |first=Jinny |last=Gudmundsen |date=December 11, 2008 |accessdate=November 30, 2018 |newspaper=USA Today |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231000423/http://www.usatoday.com/tech/columnist/jinnygudmundsen/2008-12-11-club-penguin_N.htm |archive-date=December 31, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://worthplaying.com/article/2010/6/10/news/74812/ |title='Club Penguin Game Day!' (Wii) Announced |date=June 10, 2010 |website=Worthplaying |access-date=November 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201005131/https://worthplaying.com/article/2010/6/10/news/74812/ |archive-date=December 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> television specials in the UK,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.factorycreate.com/factory-produces-new-show-disney/ |title=Factory Produces New Disney Show |date=November 24, 2014 |website=Factory |access-date=November 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714170733/http://www.factorycreate.com/factory-produces-new-show-disney/ |archive-date=July 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a series of books.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whattheyplay.com/blog/2008/10/22/club-penguin-books/ |title=What They Play \u2013 Club Penguin books|work=What They Play |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718040129/http://www.whattheyplay.com/blog/2008/10/22/club-penguin-books/ |archive-date=July 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |access-date=November 30, 2018 |first=John |last=Davison |date=October 22, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n''Club Penguin'' received mixed reviews throughout its journey. The site was awarded a \"kids' privacy seal of approval\" from the [[Better Business Bureau]].<ref name=\"Green\">{{cite journal | last = Green | first = Elizabeth Weiss | date = March 19, 2007 | title = Clique on to Penguin | journal = [[U.S. News & World Report]] | volume = 142 | issue = 10}}</ref> Similarly, Brian Ward, a [[Detective Inspector]] at the Child Abuse Investigation Command in the United Kingdom, stated that it was good for children to experience a restricted system such as ''Club Penguin'' before moving into [[social networking]] sites, which provide less protection.<ref name=\"TheAustralian\">{{cite news | date = October 9, 2007 | title = Kids' online community growing fast | work = [[The Australian]]}}</ref> In terms of simple popularity, the rapid growth of ''Club Penguin'' suggested considerable success, although there were signs that this was leveling out. [[Nielsen Company|Nielsen]] figures released in April 2008 indicated that in the previous 12 months, ''Club Penguin'' traffic had shrunk by 7%.<ref name=\"McCarthy\">{{cite web | last = McCarthy | first = Caroline | date = May 20, 2008 | title = Nielsen: MySpace, Club Penguin growth static, LinkedIn soaring | work = CNet | url = http://news.cnet.com/8301-13577_3-9948219-36.html | accessdate = May 25, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080719165638/http://news.cnet.com/8301-13577_3-9948219-36.html | archive-date = July 19, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nA criticism expressed by commentators was that the game encouraged [[consumerism]]<ref name=\"Navarro\" /> and allowed players to [[cheating in online games|cheat]].<ref name=\"Benderoff\" /> While ''Club Penguin'' did not require members to purchase in-game products with real money (instead relying on a set monthly fee), players were encouraged to earn coins within the game with which to buy virtual products. In addition, the \"competitive culture\" that this could create led to concerns about [[cheating in online games|cheating]], as children looked for \"shortcuts\" to improve their standing. It was suggested that this might influence their real-world behavior.<ref name=\"Benderoff\">{{cite news | url = http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/chi-0703080167mar08,0,7203137.story | last = Benderoff | first = Eric | date = March 7, 2007 | title = Young gamers may be learning the art of cheating | work = [[Chicago Tribune]] | access-date = March 16, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091129074025/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/chi-0703080167mar08,0,7203137.story | archive-date = November 29, 2009 | url-status = live }}</ref> To counter this, ''Club Penguin'' added guidelines to prevent cheating, and banned players who were caught cheating or who encouraged cheating.<ref name=\"Benderoff\" /> The use of in-game money was commented on as possibly helping teach children how to save money, select what to spend it on, improve their abilities at math,<ref name=\"Navarro\" /><ref name=\"Reid\" /> and encourage them to \"practice safe money-management skills\".<ref name=\"Bishop\">{{cite news | last = Bishop | first = Tricia | date = April 8, 2007 | title = Sites aimed at preteens gaining in popularity&nbsp;\u2014 Marketers courting children ages 6\u201312 as their spending soars | work = [[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\nIn spite of the attempts to create a safe space for children in ''Club Penguin'', concerns about safety and behavior still arose within the media. While the language in-game was filtered, discussions outside of ''Club Penguin'' were beyond the owner's control, and thus it was stated that third-party ''Club Penguin'' [[Internet forum|forums]] could become \"as bawdy as any other chat\".<ref name=\"Robertson\" /> Even within the game, some people noted that [[cyberbullying]] could still occur,<ref name=\"Charkes\">{{cite news | last = Charkes | first = Juli S. | date = March 30, 2008 | title = Cracking Down on the Cyberbully | work = [[The New York Times]]}}</ref> with [[flame war]]s potentially occurring within the game.<ref name=\"Flanagan\">{{cite news | last = Flanagan | first = Caitlin | date = July\u2013August 2007 | title = Babes in the Woods | work = [[The Atlantic Monthly]] | url = https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2007/07/babes-in-the-woods/5974/ | accessdate = May 24, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100914180133/http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2007/07/babes-in-the-woods/5974/ | archive-date = September 14, 2010 | url-status = live }}</ref> Also, the \"Caste system\" between those who had membership and exclusive items and those who lacked full membership (and therefore were unable to own the \"coolest\" items) could lead to players having a difficult time attracting friends.<ref name=\"Robertson\" />\n\nOne criticism came from Caitlin Flanagan in ''[[The Atlantic Monthly]]'': in relation to the safety procedures, she noted that ''Club Penguin'' was \"certainly the safest way for unsupervised children to talk to potentially malevolent strangers\u2014but why would you want them to do that in the first place?\"<ref name=\"Flanagan\" /> While views of the strength of this criticism might vary, the concern was mirrored by Lynsey Kiely in the ''[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]'', who quoted Karen Mason, Communications Director for ''Club Penguin'', as saying \"we cannot guarantee that every person who visits the site is a child.\"<ref name=\"Kiely\" />\n\nOn August 20, 2013, Disney announced that ''[[Toontown Online]]'', ''[[Pixie Hollow (video game)|Pixie Hollow]]'', and ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean Online]]'' were closing directly because of ''Club Penguin'' and Disney's mobile games. This caused major controversy between ''Club Penguin'' and fans of the three games, especially ''Toontown'', where some users had played for more than 12 years (''Toontown''<nowiki/>'s [[Alpha-test|alpha test]] started in August 2001).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/23/tech/gaming-gadgets/closing-toontown/ | work=CNN | title=Coping with the loss of an online world \u2013 CNN.com | date=August 24, 2013 | access-date=August 24, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823225043/http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/23/tech/gaming-gadgets/closing-toontown | archive-date=August 23, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Private servers ==\nA Club Penguin Private Server (commonly abbreviated and known as a CPPS) is an online multiplayer game that is not part of ''Club Penguin'', but uses [[SWF]] files from ''Club Penguin'', a database, and a server emulator in order to create a similar environment for the game. Many now use these environments in order to play the original game after its discontinuation. CPPSs often contain features that did not exist in the original game such as custom items and rooms, free membership, etc.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nThroughout the official game's existence, various players created private servers of ''Club Penguin'', and in response to the its closure, more private servers were created. ''Club Penguin Rewritten'', launched February 12, 2017&nbsp;\u2013 had reached a million players as of October 12, 2017,<ref name=Cooley>{{cite magazine |url=http://culture.affinitymagazine.us/save-club-penguin-the-game-we-know-and-love/ |magazine=Affinity |title=Save Club Penguin: The Game We Know and Love |first=Marcus |last=Cooley |access-date=November 4, 2017 |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102064051/http://culture.affinitymagazine.us/save-club-penguin-the-game-we-know-and-love/ |archive-date=November 2, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> though discontinued \"permanently\" on March 4, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://community.cprewritten.net/announcement.php |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226202443/https://community.cprewritten.net/announcement.php |archive-date=February 26, 2018 |date=February 26, 2018 |title=Announcement Regarding the future of Club Penguin Rewritten |publisher=Club Penguin Rewritten }}</ref> Citing community support and funding, it returned in April 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://community.cprewritten.net/2018/04/27/the-island-has-returned/ |title=The Island Has Returned! |author=Stu |website=Club Penguin Rewritten |date=April 27, 2018 |access-date=April 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430182212/https://community.cprewritten.net/2018/04/27/the-island-has-returned/ |archive-date=April 30, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The private server had at least four million player accounts in July 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nakedsecurity.sophos.com/2019/08/02/4-million-club-penguin-rewritten-accounts-exposed-in-breach/ |title=4 million Club Penguin Rewritten accounts exposed in breach |date=August 2, 2019 |website=Naked Security |publisher=[[Sophos]] |first=John E. |last=Dunn |access-date=April 9, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic|2020 COVID-19 pandemic]], the ''Club Penguin Online'' private server game passed six million players.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-gb/2020/04/9647031/club-penguin-back-play-online-2020 |title=Disney's Club Penguin Is Back |last=Cort\u00e9s |first=Michelle Santiago |website=Refinery29 |language=en-GB |access-date=April 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Legal status ===\nSince private servers essentially copy materials copyrighted by Disney, there has been much controversy as to whether or not creating and hosting them is legal. Disney and ''Club Penguin'' have pursued numerous CPPSs and attempted to have them taken down with [[DMCA]] notices.<ref>{{cite web|title=Notice by Club Penguin Rewritten that they are switching domains due to Disney's legal action|url=https://clubpenguinrewritten.pw/|accessdate=October 22, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022113002/https://clubpenguinrewritten.pw/|archivedate=October 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Vulnerabilities ===\nMany private servers have become vulnerable to DDOS attacks and database leaks due to insufficient security measures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.speedycppshq.com/breaking-news-cpps-me-breach/|title=CPPS.me Database Breach|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712162751/http://www.speedycppshq.com/breaking-news-cpps-me-breach/|archivedate=July 12, 2018|accessdate=June 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.speedycppshq.com/breaking-news-supercpps-database-breach-10000-accounts/|title=SuperCPPS Database Breach|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712162738/http://www.speedycppshq.com/breaking-news-supercpps-database-breach-10000-accounts/|archivedate=July 12, 2018|accessdate=June 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2019, the login data of over 4 million ''Club Penguin Rewritten'' users was stolen after a data breach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/logins-stolen-from-admin-backdoored-club-penguin-rewritten-site/|title=Logins Stolen From Admin-Backdoored Club Penguin Rewritten Site|website=BleepingComputer|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821084353/https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/logins-stolen-from-admin-backdoored-club-penguin-rewritten-site/|archive-date=August 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{expand list|date=June 2013}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|+\n!Year !! Award !! Title !! Recipient !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2008\n|Web Marketing Association Entertainment Standard of Excellence\n|\n| rowspan=\"8\" |Club Penguin\n|{{won}}\n| <ref name=\"Web Marketing Association\">{{cite web|title=Walt Disney Internet Group wins 2008 WebAward for Club Penguin|url=http://www.webaward.org/winner.asp?eid=10249#.Uyjl1_38_B0|publisher=Web Marketing Association|accessdate=March 18, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319033556/http://www.webaward.org/winner.asp?eid=10249#.Uyjl1_38_B0|archive-date=March 19, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Web Marketing Association Game Site Standard of Excellence\n|\n|{{won}}\n| <ref name=\"Web Marketing Association\" />\n|-\n|2008 [[Webby Award]]s, Youth Category\n|\n|{{nominated}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Youth The Webby Awards Gallery|url=http://winners.webbyawards.com/2008/web/general-website/youth/club-penguin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313081053/http://winners.webbyawards.com/2008/web/general-website/youth/club-penguin|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 13, 2014|accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\n|2009 [[Webby Award]]s, Games Category\n|\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Games The Webby Awards Gallery|url=http://winners.webbyawards.com/2009/web/general-website-categories/games/club-penguin|publisher=The Webby Awards|accessdate=March 13, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313070520/http://winners.webbyawards.com/2009/web/general-website-categories/games/club-penguin|archivedate=March 13, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010\n|Children's [[BAFTA Award]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Kids Vote\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=2010 Children's BAFTA Kids' Vote|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2010/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-websites|publisher=BAFTA|accessdate=February 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302010843/http://awards.bafta.org/award/2010/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-websites|archive-date=March 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011\n|Children's [[BAFTA Award]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 Children's BAFTA Kids Vote Powered By Yahoo!|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2011/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-powered-by-yahoo-top-10s-websites|publisher=BAFTA|accessdate=February 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317212659/http://awards.bafta.org/award/2011/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-powered-by-yahoo-top-10s-websites|archive-date=March 17, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012\n|Children's [[BAFTA Award]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=2012 Children's BAFTA Kids' Vote|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2012/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-websites|publisher=BAFTA|accessdate=February 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305073547/http://awards.bafta.org/award/2012/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-websites|archive-date=March 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013\n|Children's [[BAFTA Award]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Children's BAFTA Kids' Vote|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2013/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-websites|publisher=BAFTA|accessdate=February 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408090200/http://awards.bafta.org/award/2013/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-websites|archive-date=April 8, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|En-club-penguin.ogg|2019-11-06}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/ |title=Club Penguin Website |accessdate=December 30, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330010044/http://www.clubpenguin.com/ |archivedate=March 30, 2017 |df= }}\n* [https://www.clubpenguinisland.com/ Official ''Club Penguin'' Island website]\n* [http://www.zdnet.com/article/the-technology-behind-disneys-club-penguin/ The technology behind Disney's Club Penguin]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2005 video games]]\n[[Category:Browser games]]\n[[Category:Children's websites]]\n[[Category:Club Penguin| ]]\n[[Category:Disney video games]]\n[[Category:Disney acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Fictional penguins]]\n[[Category:Inactive massively multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Internet properties disestablished in 2017]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Massively multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Miniclip games]]\n[[Category:Persistent worlds]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Canada]]\n[[Category:Webby Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the franchise it spawned|Club Penguin (franchise)|its successor released in 2017|Club Penguin Island}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{short description|Massively multiplayer online game}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game online service\n|name                         = Club Penguin\n|title                        = ''Club Penguin''\n|image                        = Club Penguin logo.png\n|developer                    = New Horizon Interactive<br />RocketSnail Games<br />[[Disney Interactive Studios]]\n|type                         = [[Massively multiplayer online game]]\n|launched                     = {{Start date|2005|10|24}}\n|discontinued                 = {{End date|2017|3|30}}\n|platform                     = [[Online]] ([[Adobe Flash]])\n|status                       = Discontinued in favor of ''[[Club Penguin Island]]'' ({{End date|2017|03|30}})\n|members                      = \n|website                      =  [http://clubpenguinn.com Club Penguin Website]\n}} (\n'''''Club Penguin''''' was a [[massively multiplayer online game]] (MMO), involving a [[virtual world]] that contained a range of online games and activities. It was created by New Horizon Interactive (now known as Disney Canada Inc.). Players used cartoon penguin-[[avatar (virtual reality)|avatars]] and played in a winter-set virtual world. After [[beta-testing]], ''Club Penguin'' was made available to the general public on October 24, 2005,<ref name=\"BillyBob2005a\">{{cite web |url=http://community.clubpenguin.com/blog/2005/10/Its-Launched.php |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429202042/http://community.clubpenguin.com/blog/2005/10/Its-Launched.php |archivedate=April 29, 2008 |title=Club Penguin&nbsp;\u2014 It's Launched! |accessdate=June 16, 2008 |author=Billybob |date=October 24, 2005 |work=Club Penguin Developer Blog |quote=}}</ref> and expanded into a large [[online community]], such that by late 2007, it was claimed ''Club Penguin'' had over 30 million user accounts.<ref name=\"Walmsley\">{{cite news|title=Kids' virtual worlds are maturing nicely|last=Walmsley|first=Andrew|date=October 24, 2007|work=Marketing}}</ref> In July 2013, ''Club Penguin'' had over 200 million registered user accounts.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |title='Star Wars' Takes Over Disney's Club Penguin |author=Graser, Marc |url=https://variety.com/2013/digital/news/star-wars-takes-over-disneys-club-penguin-1200561084/ |newspaper=Variety |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=August 15, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814113840/http://variety.com/2013/digital/news/star-wars-takes-over-disneys-club-penguin-1200561084/ |archive-date=August 14, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile free memberships were available, revenue was predominantly raised through paid memberships, which allowed players to access a range of additional features, such as the ability to purchase virtual clothing, furniture, and in-game pets called \"puffles\" for their penguins through the usage of in-game [[currency]]. The success of ''Club Penguin'' led to New Horizon being purchased by [[The Walt Disney Company]] in August 2007 for the sum of 350 million dollars, with an additional 350 million dollars in bonuses should specific targets be met by 2009.<ref name= WSJAcquire>{{cite news | title=Disney Buys Kids' Social-Network Site \u2013 WSJ.com | work=Wall Street Journal | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118599768804085026?mod=hpp_us_whats_news | accessdate=December 26, 2010 | first1=Merissa | last1=Marr | first2=Peter | last2=Sanders | date=August 2, 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307214255/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118599768804085026?mod=hpp_us_whats_news | archive-date=March 7, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe game was specifically designed for children aged 6 to 14 (however, users of any age were allowed to play ''Club Penguin'').<ref name=\"kudos\">{{cite web|date=December 11, 2006 |title=Kudos continue as Club Penguin marks one-year anniversary (Media Release) |work=Club Penguin |url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/news/061211-one-year-anniversary.htm |accessdate=June 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080420210109/http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/news/061211-one-year-anniversary.htm |archivedate=April 20, 2008 }}</ref> Thus, a major focus of the developers was on child safety,<ref name=\"Kiely\" /> with a number of features having been introduced to the game to facilitate this. These features included offering an \"Ultimate Safe Chat\" mode, whereby users selected their comments from a menu; [[Wordfilter|filtering]] that prevented swearing and the revelation of personal information;<ref name=\"Kiely\" /> and [[Forum moderator|moderators]] who patrolled the game.<ref name=\"Flanagan\" />\n\nOn January 30, 2017, it was announced that the game would be discontinued on March 29, 2017. ''Club Penguin'' later shut down its servers on March 30, 2017 at 12:01 AM [[Pacific Time|PDT]]. The game was replaced by a successor, titled ''[[Club Penguin Island]]'' (which itself was discontinued the following year).<ref name=\"CPBlog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/important-announcement-regarding-club-penguin-desktop-and-mobile-devices|title=Important Announcement Regarding Club Penguin on Desktop and Mobile Devices|first=|date=January 30, 2017|website=|publisher=Club Penguin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328202618/http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/important-announcement-regarding-club-penguin-desktop-and-mobile-devices|archive-date=March 28, 2017|url-status= |access-date=January 31, 2017|author=Megg}}</ref> Since being shut down, the original game has been hosted and recreated on a number of [[Server emulator|private servers]] using [[SWF]] files from the game's old website.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Predecessors (2000\u20132004) ===\nThe first seeds of what would become ''Club Penguin'' began as a [[Adobe Flash|Flash 4]] [[web-based]] game called ''Snow Blasters'' that developer Lance Priebe had been developing in his spare time in July 2000.<ref name=\"BDODunwoody\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bizactions.com/index.cfm/ba/e105/fa/68240602G627J357168P0P10056056T0/|title=BDO Dunwoody Announcement|work=BDO Dunwoody|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016214213/http://bizactions.com/index.cfm/ba/e105/fa/68240602G627J357168P0P10056056T0/|archivedate=October 16, 2007|accessdate=May 19, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/rocketsnail/status/289216023683547138|title=RocketSnail on Twitter|newspaper=Twitter|language=en|access-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209080023/https://twitter.com/rocketsnail/status/289216023683547138|archive-date=February 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/rocketsnail/status/350638923585843200|title=RocketSnail on Twitter|newspaper=Twitter|language=en|access-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210140826/https://twitter.com/rocketsnail/status/350638923585843200|archive-date=February 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Priebe's attention was brought to penguins after he \"happened to glance at a ''[[The Far Side|Far Side]]'' cartoon featuring penguins that was sitting on his desk\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/10/business/media/10adco.html|title=A Procession of Penguins Arrives on Madison Ave.|last=Elliott|first=Stuart|date=January 10, 2007|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201234856/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/10/business/media/10adco.html|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The project was never finished, and instead morphed into ''Experimental Penguins. Experimental Penguins'' was released through Priebe's company of employment, the [[Kelowna]], British Columbia, Canada-based online game and comic developer Rocketsnail Games, in July 2000, though it ultimately went offline the following year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rocketsnail.com/experimental-penguins|title=Experimental Penguins|website=RocketSnail|language=en-US|access-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203163749/http://rocketsnail.com/experimental-penguins|archive-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It was used as the inspiration for ''Penguin Chat'' (also known as ''Penguin Chat 1''), a similar game which was released shortly after ''Experimental Penguins''<nowiki>'</nowiki> removal. Released January 2003, ''Penguin Football Chat'' (also known as ''Penguin Chat 2)'' was the second attempt at a penguin-themed MMORPG, and was created on FLASH 5 and used the same interface as ''Experimental Penguins.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rocketsnail.com/penguin-chat/|title=Penguin Chat|website=RocketSnail|language=en-US|access-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203162414/http://rocketsnail.com/penguin-chat/|archive-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The game contained various minigames; the premiere title of RocketSnail Games was ''Ballistic Biscuit'', a game that would be placed into ''Experimental Penguins'' and eventually be adapted into ''Club Penguin''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s ''Hydro Hopper''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rocketsnail.com/games/|title=Games|website=RocketSnail|language=en-US|access-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201035125/http://rocketsnail.com/games|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> RocketSnails Games' ''Mancala Classic'' would also be placed into the game as ''Mancala''.\n\nLance Priebe, as well as co-workers Lane Merrifield and Dave Krysko, started to formulate the ''Club Penguin'' concept when the trio were unsuccessful in finding \"something that had some social components but was safe, and not just marketed as safe\" for their own children.<ref name=\"Mlynek\">{{cite news|url=http://www.canadianbusiness.com/managing/ceo_interviews/article.jsp?content=20080428_198723_198723 |title=Q&A: Club Penguin's Lane Merrifield |last=Mlynek |first=Alex |date=April 28, 2008 |work=[[Canadian Business]] |accessdate=May 16, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219060236/http://www.canadianbusiness.com/managing/ceo_interviews/article.jsp?content=20080428_198723_198723 |archivedate=December 19, 2008 |df= }}</ref> Dave Krysko in particular wanted to build a safe social-networking site their kids could enjoy free of advertising.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/about|title=About Club Penguin|newspaper=Club Penguin|language=en|access-date=January 19, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131182951/http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/about|archivedate=January 31, 2017}}</ref> In 2003, Merrifield and Priebe approached their boss, with the idea of creating a spinoff company to develop the new product.<ref name=\"McKenna\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/children-and-penguins-turn-trio-into-kingpins/article18176636/|title=Children and penguins turn trio into kingpins|last=McKenna|first=Barrie|date=November 13, 2006|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|location=Toronto|accessdate=May 16, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160218111840/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/children-and-penguins-turn-trio-into-kingpins/article18176636/|archive-date=February 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The spin-off company would be known as New Horizon Interactive.\n\n=== Early history (2004\u20132007) ===\nWork commenced on the project in 2004, and the team settled on a name in the summer of 2005.<ref name=\":2\" /> The developers used the previous project ''Penguin Chat 2''&nbsp;\u2013 which was still online&nbsp;\u2013 as a jumping-off point in the design process, while incorporating concepts and ideas from Experimental Penguins. Penguin Chat's third version was released in April 2005, and was used to test the client and servers of ''Penguin Chat 4'' (renamed ''Club Penguin'').<ref name=\"Priebe\">{{cite web|url=http://rocketsnail.com/blog/2011/02/21/experimenting-with-penguins/|title=Experimenting with Penguins|last=Priebe|first=Lance|work=Rocketsnail Games|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429222843/http://rocketsnail.com/blog/2011/02/21/experimenting-with-penguins/|archive-date=April 29, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Variants of ''Penguin Chat 3'' included ''Crab Chat, Chibi Friends Chat, Goat Chat, Ultra-Chat, and TV Chat.'' Users from Penguin Chat were invited to beta test ''Club Penguin''. The original plan was to release ''Club Penguin'' in 2010, but since the team had decided to fast-track the project, the first version of ''Club Penguin'' went live on October 24, 2005,<ref name=\"Priebe\" /> just after Penguin Chat servers were shut down in August 2005. While Penguin Chat used ElectroServer, ''Club Penguin'' would use SmartFoxServer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/rocketsnail/status/223980934335180800|title=RocketSnail on Twitter|newspaper=Twitter|language=en|access-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211041756/https://twitter.com/rocketsnail/status/223980934335180800|archive-date=February 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The developers financed their start-up entirely with their own credit cards and personal lines of credit, and maintained 100 percent ownership.<ref name=\"Jordan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bcbusiness.ca/people/lane-merrifield-club-penguin|title=Lane Merrifield: Club Penguin|last=Jordan|first=David|date=April 1, 2008|work=[[BCBusiness Online]]|location=Toronto|accessdate=November 28, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203033854/http://www.bcbusiness.ca/people/lane-merrifield-club-penguin|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Club Penguin'' started with 15,000 users, and by March that number had reached 1.4 million\u2014a figure which almost doubled by September, when it hit 2.6 million.<ref name=\"McKenna\" /> By the time ''Club Penguin'' was two years old, it had reached 3.9 million users, despite lacking a marketing budget.<ref name=\"Shields\">{{cite journal|last=Shields|first=Mike|year=2007|title=Avatar Nation|journal=MediaWeek|volume=17|issue=44}}</ref> The first mention of the game in The New York Times was in October 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/27/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/29Rparenting.html|title=Halloween, Unmasked|last=Winerip|first=Michael|date=October 27, 2006|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201235545/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/27/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/29Rparenting.html|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The following year, ''Club Penguin'' spokesperson Karen Mason explained: \"We offer children the training wheels for the kinds of activities they might pursue as they get older.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/03/fashion/03Online.html|title=Online sites-online sites for children|last=Slatalla|first=Michelle|date=May 3, 2007|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201234946/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/03/fashion/03Online.html|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Acquisition by Disney (2007) ===\nAlthough the three ''Club Penguin'' co-creators had turned down lucrative advertising offers and venture capital investments in the past,<ref name=\"McKenna\" /> in August 2007, they agreed to sell both ''Club Penguin'' and its parent company to [[Disney]] for the sum of $350.93 million.<ref name=\"Walmsley\" /> In addition, the owners were promised bonuses of up to $350 million if they were able to meet growth targets by 2009.<ref name=\"Brooks\">{{cite news | last = Brooks | first = Barnes | date = August 2, 2007 | title = Wary of Losing Out Online, Disney Buys Site for Children up to ages from 6 to 16 | work = [[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Disney ultimately didn't pay the extra $350 million, as ''Club Penguin'' missed both profit goals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/119491/Disney_Skips_350M_Payment_As_Club_Penguin_Misses_Profit_Targets.php|title=Disney Skips $350M Payment As  Club Penguin  Misses Profit Targets|last=Caoili|first=Eric|language=en|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202000835/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/119491/Disney_Skips_350M_Payment_As_Club_Penguin_Misses_Profit_Targets.php|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/13/business/media/13penguin.html|title=Disney Gets a Half-Price Deal for Club Penguin|last=Barnes|first=Brooks|date=May 12, 2010|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201234646/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/13/business/media/13penguin.html|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> At the point when it was purchased by Disney, ''Club Penguin'' had 11\u201312 million accounts, of which 700,000 were paid subscribers, and was generating $40 million in annual revenue.<ref name=\"Walmsley\" /><ref name=\"Jordan\" /> In making the sale, Merrifield has stated that their main focus during negotiations was philosophical,<ref name=\"Mlynek\" /> and that the intent was to provide themselves with the needed infrastructure in order to continue to grow.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}} By late 2007, it was claimed that ''Club Penguin'' had over 30 million user accounts.<ref name=\"Walmsley\" /> In December of that year, The New York Times asserted that the game \"attracts seven times more traffic than [[Second Life]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/31/business/31virtual.html|title=Web Playgrounds of the Very Young|last=Barnes|first=Brooks|date=December 31, 2007|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201234438/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/31/business/31virtual.html|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Club Penguin'' was the 8th top social networking site in April 2008, according to Nielsen.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/nielsen-myspace-club-penguin-growth-static-linkedin-soaring/|title=Nielsen: MySpace, Club Penguin growth static, LinkedIn soaring|newspaper=CNET|language=en|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201235853/https://www.cnet.com/news/nielsen-myspace-club-penguin-growth-static-linkedin-soaring/|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter Disney's acquisition, Disney Interactive had four MMOs to simultaneously juggle: ''[[Toontown Online|ToonTown]]'', ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean Online]]'', ''[[Pixie Hollow (video game)|Pixie Hollow]]'', and ''Club Penguin'', with ''[[The World of Cars Online|World of Cars]]'' set to follow soon. Lane Merrifield assured GlobalToyNews at the time that \"it's a lot of worlds to manage, but we have really strong teams.\" Merrifield's role changed from taking a backseat in daily game design to focusing on overall branding and quality control of the virtual gaming properties. One of his roles was to merge the ''Club Penguin'' studio New Horizon Interactive in Kelowna (renamed to Disneyland Studios Canada) with Disneyland Studios LA. Disneyland Studios Canada focused its efforts on one product (with such features as multilingual versions), while Disneyland Studios LA focused on customer products and franchises of a wide selection of games. Merrifield was responsible for cross-pollinating both cultures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaltoynews.com/2010/08/an-interview-with-lane-merrifield-creator-of-club-penguin-.html|title=An Interview with Lane Merrifield; creator of Club Penguin \u2013 Global Toy News|website=www.globaltoynews.com|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201234723/http://www.globaltoynews.com/2010/08/an-interview-with-lane-merrifield-creator-of-club-penguin-.html|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Franchising and growth (2007\u20132015) ===\nSince the Disney purchase, ''Club Penguin'' continued to grow, becoming part of a larger franchise including video games, books, a television special, an anniversary song, and an app MMO. Disney has often used the game as a cross-promotion opportunity when releasing new films such as ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]],'' ''[[Zootopia]],'' and ''[[Star Wars]],'' having special themed events and parties to celebrate their releases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kidscreen.com/2014/08/19/club-penguin-gets-frozen/|title=Club Penguin gets Frozen|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131192413/http://kidscreen.com/2014/08/19/club-penguin-gets-frozen/|archive-date=January 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/zootopia-party-announcement|title=Zootopia Party Announcement|date=April 28, 2016|newspaper=Club Penguin|language=en|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201110014/http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/zootopia-party-announcement|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2013/digital/news/star-wars-takes-over-disneys-club-penguin-1200561084/|title='Star Wars' Takes Over Disney's Club Penguin|last=Graser|first=Marc|date=July 11, 2013|newspaper=Variety|language=en-US|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131200312/http://variety.com/2013/digital/news/star-wars-takes-over-disneys-club-penguin-1200561084/|archive-date=January 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The game forged an ever-growing mythology of characters and plot elements, including: a pirate, a journalist, and a secret agent.\n\nIn 2008, the first international office opened in Brighton, England, to personalise the level of moderation and player support. Later international office locations included S\u00e3o Paulo and Buenos Aires.<ref name=\":0\" /> On March 11, 2008, ''Club Penguin'' released the ''Club Penguin'' Improvement Project.<ref name=\"BillyBob2008a\">{{cite web | last = BillyBob | date = March 10, 2008 | title = Welcome!! | work = Club Penguin Improvement Project: Blog | url = http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/03/welcome-to-the-club-penguin-im.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080421205905/http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/03/welcome-to-the-club-penguin-im.html | archivedate = April 21, 2008 | accessdate = May 19, 2007}}</ref> This project allowed players to be part of the testing of new servers, which were put into use in ''Club Penguin'' on April 14, 2008.<ref name=\"BillyBob2008d\">{{cite web | last = BillyBob | date = April 14, 2008 | title = New website and new servers | work = Club Penguin Improvement Project: Blog | url = http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/04/new-website-and-new-servers.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080420170611/http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/04/new-website-and-new-servers.html | archivedate = April 20, 2008 | accessdate = May 19, 2007}}</ref> Players had a \"clone\" of their penguin made, to test these new servers for bugs and glitches.<ref name=\"BillyBob2008b\">{{cite web | last = BillyBob | date = March 10, 2008 | title = Account Questions | work = Club Penguin Improvement Project: Blog | url = http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/03/account-questions.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080421205844/http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/03/account-questions.html | archivedate = April 21, 2008 | accessdate = May 19, 2007}}</ref> The testing was ended on April 4, 2008.<ref name=\"BillyBob2008c\">{{cite web | last = BillyBob | date = April 4, 2008 | title = Server Test Success!! | work = Club Penguin Improvement Project: Blog | url = http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/04/server-test-success.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080421041844/http://community.clubpenguin.com/cpip/2008/04/server-test-success.html | archivedate = April 21, 2008 | accessdate = May 19, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn June 20, 2011, the game's website temporarily crashed after the company let the ''Club Penguin'' domain name expire.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2011/06/club-penguin-downtime-is-only-disneys-latest-internet-misstep/240752/|title=Club Penguin Downtime Is Only Disney's Latest Internet Misstep|last=Jackson|first=Nicholas|newspaper=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131195315/http://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2011/06/club-penguin-downtime-is-only-disneys-latest-internet-misstep/240752/|archive-date=January 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2011, one of Club Penguin's minigames, Puffle Launch, was released on iOS as an app. Merrifield commented: \"Kids are going mobile and have been asking for Club Penguin to go there with them.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/technology-science/technology/disneys-club-penguin-celebrates-150-186884|title=Disney's Club Penguin Celebrates 150 million users by launching new app|last=Mirror.co.uk|date=September 15, 2011|newspaper=mirror|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202113740/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/technology-science/technology/disneys-club-penguin-celebrates-150-186884|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2012, Merrifield left Disney Interactive to focus on his family and a new educational product, Freshgrade. Chris Heatherly took Merrifield's former position.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/oct/17/entertainment/la-et-ct-disney-interactive-club-penguin-20121017 | title=Disney Interactive loses Club Penguin founder Lane Merrifield | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | first1=Dawn C. | last1=Chmielewski | first2=Ben | last2=Fritz | date=October 17, 2012 | accessdate=January 17, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170331143426/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/oct/17/entertainment/la-et-ct-disney-interactive-club-penguin-20121017 | archive-date=March 31, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> The company dropped the words \"Online Studios\" from its name<ref>{{cite web |title=Club Penguin Trademark Details |url=http://trademarks.justia.com/850/69/club-penguin-85069142.html |date=November 20, 2013 |accessdate=December 27, 2013 |publisher=Justia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228072829/http://trademarks.justia.com/850/69/club-penguin-85069142.html |archive-date=December 28, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/privacy-policy/en |title=Privacy Policy |publisher=Club Penguin |accessdate=December 27, 2013 |date=November 1, 2013 |quote=Disney Club Penguin (\"Club Penguin\") is operated and presented to users in all locations by Disney Canada Inc. (formerly known as Disney Online Studios Canada Inc.)... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226133601/http://www.clubpenguin.com/privacy-policy/en |archive-date=December 26, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> in 2013. As of July 2013, ''Club Penguin'' had over 200 million registered user accounts.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2013, ''Club Penguin'' hired singer and former ''Club Penguin'' player [[Jordan Fisher]] to record a song entitled ''It's Your Birthday'', to commemorate Club Penguin's 8th anniversary.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/blog/2013/10/exclusive-interview-jordan-fisher|title=Exclusive Interview with Jordan Fisher!|date=October 23, 2013|newspaper=Club Penguin|language=en|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202034242/http://www.clubpenguin.com/blog/2013/10/exclusive-interview-jordan-fisher|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Decline and discontinuation (2015\u20132017) ===\n[[File:The Penguin Times.jpg|thumb|400x400px|This message was provided by Aunt Arctic (a proxy for Club Penguin developers) in the last issue of the in-universe newspaper The Penguin Times. It nostalgically looks back on the game's 12-year history, comments on how far the community has grown, and has an optimistic view on the future for its members.]]\n\nIn April 2015, it was revealed that Disney Interactive had [[Layoff|laid off]] 28 members of ''Club Penguin''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Kelowna headquarters due to the game's declining popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techvibes.com/2016/03/05/layoffs-club-penguin-2016-03-05|title=Disney Canada Hit by Layoffs \u2013 More to Come?|date=March 5, 2016|website=Techvibes|access-date=September 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921020905/https://techvibes.com/2016/03/05/layoffs-club-penguin-2016-03-05|archive-date=September 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The company's UK office in Brighton was shut down around April 17, 2015. Some employees in the [[Los Angeles]] office were also let go. Disney Interactive replied to Castanet on the layoffs: \"Disney Interactive continually looks to find ways to create efficiencies and streamline our operations. As part of this ongoing process, we are consolidating a small number of teams and are undergoing a targeted reduction in workforce.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.castanet.net/news/Kelowna/137843/Club-Penguin-cuts-jobs|title=Club Penguin cuts jobs \u2013 Kelowna News|website=www.castanet.net|access-date=April 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429223753/http://www.castanet.net/news/Kelowna/137843/Club-Penguin-cuts-jobs|archive-date=April 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn September 2, 2015, ''Club Penguin'' closed down the [[German language|German]] and [[Russian language|Russian]] versions of the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/blog/2015/06/important-news-about-club-penguin-russian-and-german-languages|title=Important News About Club Penguin in the Russian and German Languages|website=Club Penguin|access-date=April 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420234558/http://www.clubpenguin.com/blog/2015/06/important-news-about-club-penguin-russian-and-german-languages|archive-date=April 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> A spin-off mobile app, Puffle Wild, was removed from the [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] and [[Google Play]] the same day in order to allow Disney Interactive to focus on Club Penguin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://help.disney.com/articles/en_US/FAQ/About-Puffle-Wild?section=clubpenguin|title=Disney Interactive Support \u2013 Puffle Wild Closure|date=September 5, 2015|access-date=April 9, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905223247/https://help.disney.com/articles/en_US/FAQ/About-Puffle-Wild?section=clubpenguin|archivedate=September 5, 2015}}</ref> On January 11, 2016, the Sled Racer and SoundStudio apps (the former being an original game and the latter being a [[Porting|port]] of a game on the website) followed suit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/important-information-regarding-sled-racer-soundstudio-apps|title=Important Information Regarding Sled Racer & SoundStudio Apps|website=Club Penguin|access-date=April 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405071902/http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/important-information-regarding-sled-racer-soundstudio-apps|archive-date=April 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> With the closure of Disney Interactive in 2015, ''Club Penguin'' side-projects wound down to allow a streamlined effort to focus on the core ''Club Penguin'' experience; this involved the layoffs of 30 Disney Studios Canada staff.<ref name=\"Wawro\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/241587/Report_Layoffs_strike_Disneys_Club_Penguin.php|title=Report: Layoffs strike Disney's  Club Penguin|last=Wawro|first=Alex|language=en|access-date=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131194538/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/241587/Report_Layoffs_strike_Disneys_Club_Penguin.php|archive-date=January 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 30, 2017, ''Club Penguin'' announced that the current game would be discontinued on March 29, 2017, to make way for its successor, ''[[Club Penguin Island]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/01/31/club-penguin-is-shutting-down/|title=Club Penguin is shutting down|last=Perez|first=Sarah|date=January 31, 2017|website=TechCrunch|access-date=February 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206184552/https://techcrunch.com/2017/01/31/club-penguin-is-shutting-down/|archive-date=February 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2017/1/31/14458168/club-penguin-closing|title=Club Penguin set to close, breaking millennial hearts worldwide|last=Frank|first=Allegra|date=January 31, 2017|website=Polygon|access-date=February 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203191158/http://www.polygon.com/2017/1/31/14458168/club-penguin-closing|archive-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2017/01/31/club-penguin-shutting-down-and-everyone-sad/97277620/|title=Club Penguin is shutting down and everyone is sad|last=Molina|first=Brett|date=January 31, 2017|newspaper=USA Today|access-date=February 5, 2017|work=|language=en|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202204217/http://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2017/01/31/club-penguin-shutting-down-and-everyone-sad/97277620/|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Membership payments for the original game were no longer accepted as of January 31, 2017, with paid members slated to receive emails about membership and refunds.<ref name=\"CPBlog\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.idigitaltimes.com/club-penguin-shutting-down-mobile-only-club-penguin-island-take-its-place-582155|title='Club Penguin' Shutting Down; Mobile-Only 'Club Penguin Island' To Take Its Place|last=Medina|first=Nathalie|date=February 2, 2017|newspaper=iDigitalTimes.com|access-date=February 5, 2017|work=|language=en|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205055603/http://www.idigitaltimes.com/club-penguin-shutting-down-mobile-only-club-penguin-island-take-its-place-582155|archive-date=February 5, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIt became popular in the final weeks of Club Penguin to attempt [[speedrun]]s to see how fast users could get banned from the site; the fastest records were [[tool-assisted speedrun]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2017/2/22/14698354/club-penguin-ban-speedruns|title=Getting banned from Club Penguin is now a competitive sport|date=February 22, 2017|website=Polygon|access-date=March 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317233507/http://www.polygon.com/2017/2/22/14698354/club-penguin-ban-speedruns|archive-date=March 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDays before the shut down, ''Club Penguin'' announced that on the final day of the game's operation, all users would be given a free membership until the servers were disconnected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/waddle-party-finale-meet-times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326053454/http://www.clubpenguin.com/whats-new/waddle-party-finale-meet-times|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 26, 2017|title=Waddle On Party: Finale Meet-Up Times {{!}} Club Penguin|date=March 26, 2017|access-date=September 23, 2018}}</ref>\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Club Penguin Final Seconds.jpeg|thumb|250px|Penguins gathered around town in the server Blizzard seconds before the shut down of the ''Club Penguin'' servers.]] -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Club Penguin Lost Connection.jpg|thumb|250px|The message that displayed on users' webpages when the ''Club Penguin'' servers disconnected.]] -->\n\nOn March 30, 2017, at 12:01:39 AM [[Pacific Time|PDT]] (7:01:39 AM {{Abbr|UTC|Universal Coordinated Time}}), ''Club Penguin''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s servers were officially shut down.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://thespartanstandard.com/2017/04/farewell-club-penguin/ |title=Farewell, Club Penguin |date=April 18, 2017 |access-date=October 3, 2018 |newspaper=The Spartan Standard |publisher=[[Bainbridge High School (Washington)|Bainbridge High School]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003014208/https://thespartanstandard.com/2017/04/farewell-club-penguin/ |archive-date=October 3, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\n\n=== Business model ===\nPrior to being purchased by Disney, ''Club Penguin'' was almost entirely dependent on membership fees to produce a revenue stream.<ref name=\"Kiely\">{{cite news | last = Kiely | first = Lynsey | date = January 14, 2007 | title = C-c-c-click on clubpenguin | work = [[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]] | url = http://www.independent.ie/national-news/cccclick-on-clubpenguin-120865.html | accessdate = May 25, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080516060149/http://www.independent.ie/national-news/cccclick-on-clubpenguin-120865.html | archive-date = May 16, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref> The vast majority of users (90% according to [[The Washington Post]]) chose not to pay, instead taking advantage of the free play on offer.<ref name=\"Reid\">{{cite news | last = Reid | first = Alice | date = October 18, 2007 | title = Breaking the Ice&nbsp;&nbsp;\u2014 Club Penguin Allows Kids to Safely Explore the World of Online Gaming and Chatting | work = [[The Washington Post]] | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/10/17/AR2007101702198.html | accessdate = May 25, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110628204724/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/10/17/AR2007101702198.html | archive-date = June 28, 2011 | url-status = live }}</ref> Those who chose to pay did so because full (paid) membership was required to access all of the services, such as the ability to purchase virtual clothes for the penguins and buy decorations for igloos,<ref name=\"Navarro\">{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/28/fashion/28virtual.html | last = Navarro | first = Mireya | date = October 28, 2007 | title = Pay Up, Kid, or Your Igloo Melts | work = [[The New York Times]] | access-date = February 21, 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170201235627/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/28/fashion/28virtual.html | archive-date = February 1, 2017 | url-status = live }}</ref> and because peer pressure created a \"[[caste system]],\" separating paid from unpaid members.<ref name=\"Robertson\">{{cite journal | last = Robertson | first = Heather-Jane | year = 2007 | title = Postman Does Penguins | journal = [[Phi Delta Kappan]] | volume = 88 | issue = 5}}</ref> Advertising, both [[In-game advertising|in-game]] and on-site, was not incorporated into the system, although some competitors chose to employ it, including: [[Whyville]], which used corporate sponsorship,<ref name=\"Diaz\">{{cite news | last = Diaz | first = Sam | author2 = Yang, Xiyun | date = August 3, 2007 | title = Playground Networking, Now Online&nbsp;\u2014 Social Sites Aim at Users Too Young for MySpace | work = [[The Washington Post]] | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/02/AR2007080202351.html | accessdate = May 25, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110628204818/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/02/AR2007080202351.html | archive-date = June 28, 2011 | url-status = live }}</ref> and [[Neopets]], which incorporated product placements.<ref name=\"Rushe\">{{cite news | last = Rushe | first = Dominic | date = November 18, 2007 | title = Hooking the kids with the internet | work = [[The Sunday Times]] | url = http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/technology/article2889446.ece | accessdate = May 25, 2008 | location = London | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090508151627/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/technology/article2889446.ece | archive-date = May 8, 2009 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nAn alternative revenue stream came through the development of an online merchandise shop, which opened on the ''Club Penguin'' website in August 2006,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://community.clubpenguin.com/blog/2006/08/NOW-OPEN.php | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080429194151/http://community.clubpenguin.com/blog/2006/08/NOW-OPEN.php | archivedate = April 29, 2008 | title = NOW OPEN!!! | accessdate = June 17, 2008 |author=Billybob | date= August 31, 2006 | work = Club Penguin Developer Blog}}</ref> selling stuffed [[#Puffles|Puffles]] and T-shirts. Key chains, gift cards, and more shirts were added on November 7, 2006.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://community.clubpenguin.com/blog/2006/12/Lots-of-New-Stuff.php | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080421162623/http://community.clubpenguin.com/blog/2006/12/Lots-of-New-Stuff.php | archivedate = April 21, 2008 | title = Lots of New Stuff!! | accessdate = June 17, 2008 | author = Billybob | date = November 7, 2006 |work = Club Penguin Developer Blog}}</ref> In October 2008, a series of [[plush toys]] based on characters from ''Club Penguin,'' were made available online (both through the ''Club Penguin'' store and Disney's online store), and in retail outlets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/news/102408-new-consumer-products.htm |title=New Consumer Products Extend Club Penguin Offline (Press release) |accessdate=December 4, 2008 |date=October 24, 2008 |work=Club Penguin |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113192817/http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/news/102408-new-consumer-products.htm |archivedate=November 13, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAs with one of its major rivals, ''[[Webkinz]]'', ''Club Penguin'' traditionally relied almost entirely on [[word-of-mouth]] advertising to increase its membership base.<ref name=\"Garofoli\">{{cite news | last = Garofoli | first = Joe | date = May 27, 2007 | title = I'm 8, I'm late for an online date with a cuddly penguin | work = [[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Child safety ===\n''Club Penguin'' was designed for the ages of 6\u201314.<ref name=\"kudos\" /> Thus, one of the major concerns when designing ''Club Penguin'' was how to improve both the safety of participants and the suitability of the game to children. As Lane Merrifield stated, \"the decision to build Club Penguin grew out of a desire to create a fun, virtual world that I and the site's other two founders would feel safe letting our own children visit.\"<ref name=\"Merrifield\">{{cite journal|last=Merrifield|first=Lane|year=2007|title=Safety First?|journal=[[The Atlantic Monthly]]|volume=300|issue=3|page=17|author2=Males, Mike|author3=Flanagan, Caitlin}}</ref> As a result, ''Club Penguin'' maintained a strong focus on child safety,<ref name=\"Jesdanun\">{{cite news|title=Safety questioned as younger kids flock to Internet&nbsp;\u2014 Parents need to set guidelines, limits|last=Jesdanun|first=Anick|date=July 23, 2007|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> to the point where the security features were described as almost \"fastidious\" and \"reminiscent of an [[Orwellian]] [[dystopia]]\",<ref name=\"Williamson\">{{cite news|title=Why Many Children Are Now Picking a Penguin as Their Favourite Online Friend|last=Williamson|first=David|date=January 5, 2008|work=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]}}</ref> although it was also argued that this focus might \"reassure more parents than it alienate[d].\"<ref name=\"Williamson\" />\n\nThe system employed a number of different approaches in an attempt to improve child safety. The key approaches included preventing the use of inappropriate [[usernames]];<ref name=\"Reidb\">{{cite news|title=Safe surfing: Club Penguin is a G-rated MySpace-type site that gives kids a safer way to mingle online|last=Reid|first=Alice|date=October 18, 2007|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> providing an \"Ultimate Safe Chat\" mode, which limited players to selecting phrases from a list;<ref name=\"Jesdanun\" /> using an automatic [[Wordfilter|filter]] during \"Standard Safe Chat\" (which allowed users to generate their own messages)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/parents/club_penguin_guide.htm#safe|title=Is It Safe?|accessdate=June 17, 2008|work=Club Penguin Q&A for Parents|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705192151/http://www.clubpenguin.com/parents/club_penguin_guide.htm#safe|archive-date=July 5, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> and blocked [[profanity]] even when users employed \"creative\" methods to insert it into sentences;<ref name=\"Reidb\" /> filtering seemingly innocuous terms, such as \"mom\"; and blocking both telephone numbers and email addresses.<ref name=\"Jesdanun\" /> It also included employing paid [[Forum moderator|moderators]]; out of 100 staff employed in the company in May 2007, Merrifield estimated that approximately 70 staff were dedicated to policing the game.<ref name=\"Garofoli\" /> It also included promoting users to \"EPF (Elite Penguin Force) Agent\" status, and encouraging them to report inappropriate behavior.<ref name=\"Jesdanun\" />\n\nEach game server offered a particular type of chat\u2014the majority allowing either chat mode, but some servers allowed only the \"Ultimate Safe Chat\" mode. When using \"Standard Safe Chat\", all comments made by users were filtered. When a comment was blocked, the user who made the comment saw it, but other users were unaware that it was made\u2014suggesting to the \"speaker\" that they were being ignored, rather than encouraging them to try to find a way around the restriction.<ref name=\"Jesdanun\" />\n\nBeyond these primary measures, systems were in place to limit the amount of time spent online, and the site did not feature any advertisements, because, as described by Merrifield, \"within two or three clicks, a kid could be on a gambling site or an adult dating site.\"<ref name=\"Garofoli\" /> Nevertheless, after ''Club Penguin'' was purchased by Disney, concerns were raised that this state of affairs might change, especially in regard to potential spin-off products<ref name=\"Dwyer\">{{cite news|title=Virtual kids|last=Dwyer|first=Michael|date=November 29, 2007|work=[[The Age]]}}</ref>\u2014although Disney continued to insist that it believed advertising to be \"inappropriate\" for a young audience.<ref name=\"Rushe\" />\n\nPlayers who used profanity were often punished by an automatic 24-hour ban, although not all vulgar language resulted in an immediate ban. Players found by moderators to have broken ''Club Penguin'' rules were punished by a ban lasting \"from 24 hours to forever depending on the offense.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.clubpenguin.com/help/help/safety.htm|title=\"Breaking the Rules\" and \"How a Penguin is Banned\"|quote=|accessdate=June 17, 2008|work=Club Penguin Communicating|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723123728/http://support.clubpenguin.com/help/help/safety.htm|archivedate=July 23, 2008|df=}}</ref>\n\n=== Education and charity ===\nCoins for Change was an in-game charity fund-raising event which first appeared in 2007. The fund-raising lasted for approximately two weeks each December during the game's annual \"Holiday Party\". Players could \"donate\" their virtual coins to vote for three charitable issues: Kids who were sick, the environment, and kids in developing countries.<ref name=\"coins for change 2007 whattheyplay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.whattheyplay.com/blog/2008/12/10/coins-for-change-kicks-off-this-friday/|title=What They Play \u2013 Coins for Change kicks off this Friday|work=What They Play|accessdate=February 15, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231212056/http://www.whattheyplay.com/blog/2008/12/10/coins-for-change-kicks-off-this-friday/|archivedate=December 31, 2009}}</ref> Players were able to donate in increments of 100, 250, 500, 1,000, 5,000, or 10,000 virtual coins. At the end of the campaign, a set amount of real-world money was divided among each of the causes based on the amount of in-game currency each cause received. At the end of the first campaign, the New Horizon Foundation donated a total of $1 million to the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]], the [[Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS Foundation]], and [[Free The Children]].<ref name=\"coins for change 2007 whattheyplay\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/12/29/AR2007122901848_pf.html|title=For Modern Kids, 'Philanthropy' Is No Grown-Up Word|last=Rucker|first=Philip|date=December 30, 2007|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 22, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927172236/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/12/29/AR2007122901848_pf.html|archive-date=September 27, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In both the 2007 and 2008 campaigns, two-and-a-half million players participated.<ref name=\"coins for change 2007 whattheyplay\" /><ref name=\"coins for change 2008 whattheyplay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.whattheyplay.com/blog/2008/12/25/club-penguin-kids-donate-3-billion-in-game-coins-t/|title=What They Play \u2013 Club Penguin kids donate 3 billion in-game coins to charity|work=What They Play|accessdate=February 15, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231212005/http://www.whattheyplay.com/blog/2008/12/25/club-penguin-kids-donate-3-billion-in-game-coins-t/|archivedate=December 31, 2009}}</ref> In 2009, ''Club Penguin'' donated $1,000,000 Canadian dollars to charitable projects around the world. In 2010, ''Club Penguin'' donated $300,000 towards building safe places, $360,000 towards protecting the Earth, and $340,000 towards providing medical help. Lane Merrifield said: \"Our players are always looking for ways to make a difference and help others, and over the past five years they've embraced the opportunity to give through Coins For Change, it was exciting to see kids from 191 countries participate together.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/company/news/01-01-12-coins-for-change.htm|title=Virtual world celebrates fifth year of Coins For Change|work=celebrates fifth year|accessdate=February 15, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125092513/http://www.clubpenguin.com//company/news/01-01-12-coins-for-change.htm|archivedate=January 25, 2012}}</ref> In 2011, the amount of money donated was doubled to $2 million, ostensibly in response to an unexpected increase in participation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubpenguin.com/global-citizenship/coins-for-change-2011|title=Coins For Change 2011|last=|first=|authorlink=|year=2011|publisher=Club Penguin|format=|doi=|work=|access-date=September 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920025046/http://www.clubpenguin.com/global-citizenship/coins-for-change-2011|archive-date=September 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Plot and gameplay ==\n''Club Penguin'' was divided into various rooms and distinct areas. Illustrator Chris Hendricks designed many of the first environments. Each player was provided with an igloo for a home. Members had the option of opening their igloo so other penguins could access it via the map, under \"Member Igloos.\"{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}} Members could also purchase larger igloos and decorate their igloos with items bought with virtual coins earned by playing mini-games.<ref name=\"Reid\" /> At least one party per month was held on Club Penguin. In most cases, a free clothing item was available, both for paid members and free users. Some parties also provided member-only rooms which only paid members could access. Some major ''Club Penguin'' parties were its annual [[Halloween]] and Holiday parties. Other large parties included the Music Jam, the Adventure Party, the Puffle Party, and the Medieval Party.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n== Franchise ==\n{{Main|Club Penguin (franchise)}}\nDisney's franchising of the brand began with its acquisition of ''Club Penguin'' in 2007. In addition to the ''Club Penguin Island'' web-based video game,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://kotaku.com/club-penguin-island-to-shut-down-marking-final-end-of-1829370171 |title=Club Penguin Island To Shut Down, Marking Final End Of The Beloved Children's MMO |date=September 27, 2018 |last=D'Anastasio |first=Cecilia |website=Kotaku |access-date=November 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205185831/https://kotaku.com/club-penguin-island-to-shut-down-marking-final-end-of-1829370171 |archive-date=December 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> the franchise has also included console video games for [[Nintendo DS]] and [[Wii]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/tech/columnist/jinnygudmundsen/2008-12-11-club-penguin_N.htm |title=Join 'Elite Penguin Force' on Nintendo DS |first=Jinny |last=Gudmundsen |date=December 11, 2008 |accessdate=November 30, 2018 |newspaper=USA Today |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231000423/http://www.usatoday.com/tech/columnist/jinnygudmundsen/2008-12-11-club-penguin_N.htm |archive-date=December 31, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://worthplaying.com/article/2010/6/10/news/74812/ |title='Club Penguin Game Day!' (Wii) Announced |date=June 10, 2010 |website=Worthplaying |access-date=November 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201005131/https://worthplaying.com/article/2010/6/10/news/74812/ |archive-date=December 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> television specials in the UK,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.factorycreate.com/factory-produces-new-show-disney/ |title=Factory Produces New Disney Show |date=November 24, 2014 |website=Factory |access-date=November 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714170733/http://www.factorycreate.com/factory-produces-new-show-disney/ |archive-date=July 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a series of books.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whattheyplay.com/blog/2008/10/22/club-penguin-books/ |title=What They Play \u2013 Club Penguin books|work=What They Play |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718040129/http://www.whattheyplay.com/blog/2008/10/22/club-penguin-books/ |archive-date=July 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |access-date=November 30, 2018 |first=John |last=Davison |date=October 22, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n''Club Penguin'' received mixed reviews throughout its journey. The site was awarded a \"kids' privacy seal of approval\" from the [[Better Business Bureau]].<ref name=\"Green\">{{cite journal | last = Green | first = Elizabeth Weiss | date = March 19, 2007 | title = Clique on to Penguin | journal = [[U.S. News & World Report]] | volume = 142 | issue = 10}}</ref> Similarly, Brian Ward, a [[Detective Inspector]] at the Child Abuse Investigation Command in the United Kingdom, stated that it was good for children to experience a restricted system such as ''Club Penguin'' before moving into [[social networking]] sites, which provide less protection.<ref name=\"TheAustralian\">{{cite news | date = October 9, 2007 | title = Kids' online community growing fast | work = [[The Australian]]}}</ref> In terms of simple popularity, the rapid growth of ''Club Penguin'' suggested considerable success, although there were signs that this was leveling out. [[Nielsen Company|Nielsen]] figures released in April 2008 indicated that in the previous 12 months, ''Club Penguin'' traffic had shrunk by 7%.<ref name=\"McCarthy\">{{cite web | last = McCarthy | first = Caroline | date = May 20, 2008 | title = Nielsen: MySpace, Club Penguin growth static, LinkedIn soaring | work = CNet | url = http://news.cnet.com/8301-13577_3-9948219-36.html | accessdate = May 25, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080719165638/http://news.cnet.com/8301-13577_3-9948219-36.html | archive-date = July 19, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nA criticism expressed by commentators was that the game encouraged [[consumerism]]<ref name=\"Navarro\" /> and allowed players to [[cheating in online games|cheat]].<ref name=\"Benderoff\" /> While ''Club Penguin'' did not require members to purchase in-game products with real money (instead relying on a set monthly fee), players were encouraged to earn coins within the game with which to buy virtual products. In addition, the \"competitive culture\" that this could create led to concerns about [[cheating in online games|cheating]], as children looked for \"shortcuts\" to improve their standing. It was suggested that this might influence their real-world behavior.<ref name=\"Benderoff\">{{cite news | url = http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/chi-0703080167mar08,0,7203137.story | last = Benderoff | first = Eric | date = March 7, 2007 | title = Young gamers may be learning the art of cheating | work = [[Chicago Tribune]] | access-date = March 16, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091129074025/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/chi-0703080167mar08,0,7203137.story | archive-date = November 29, 2009 | url-status = live }}</ref> To counter this, ''Club Penguin'' added guidelines to prevent cheating, and banned players who were caught cheating or who encouraged cheating.<ref name=\"Benderoff\" /> The use of in-game money was commented on as possibly helping teach children how to save money, select what to spend it on, improve their abilities at math,<ref name=\"Navarro\" /><ref name=\"Reid\" /> and encourage them to \"practice safe money-management skills\".<ref name=\"Bishop\">{{cite news | last = Bishop | first = Tricia | date = April 8, 2007 | title = Sites aimed at preteens gaining in popularity&nbsp;\u2014 Marketers courting children ages 6\u201312 as their spending soars | work = [[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\nIn spite of the attempts to create a safe space for children in ''Club Penguin'', concerns about safety and behavior still arose within the media. While the language in-game was filtered, discussions outside of ''Club Penguin'' were beyond the owner's control, and thus it was stated that third-party ''Club Penguin'' [[Internet forum|forums]] could become \"as bawdy as any other chat\".<ref name=\"Robertson\" /> Even within the game, some people noted that [[cyberbullying]] could still occur,<ref name=\"Charkes\">{{cite news | last = Charkes | first = Juli S. | date = March 30, 2008 | title = Cracking Down on the Cyberbully | work = [[The New York Times]]}}</ref> with [[flame war]]s potentially occurring within the game.<ref name=\"Flanagan\">{{cite news | last = Flanagan | first = Caitlin | date = July\u2013August 2007 | title = Babes in the Woods | work = [[The Atlantic Monthly]] | url = https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2007/07/babes-in-the-woods/5974/ | accessdate = May 24, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100914180133/http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2007/07/babes-in-the-woods/5974/ | archive-date = September 14, 2010 | url-status = live }}</ref> Also, the \"Caste system\" between those who had membership and exclusive items and those who lacked full membership (and therefore were unable to own the \"coolest\" items) could lead to players having a difficult time attracting friends.<ref name=\"Robertson\" />\n\nOne criticism came from Caitlin Flanagan in ''[[The Atlantic Monthly]]'': in relation to the safety procedures, she noted that ''Club Penguin'' was \"certainly the safest way for unsupervised children to talk to potentially malevolent strangers\u2014but why would you want them to do that in the first place?\"<ref name=\"Flanagan\" /> While views of the strength of this criticism might vary, the concern was mirrored by Lynsey Kiely in the ''[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]'', who quoted Karen Mason, Communications Director for ''Club Penguin'', as saying \"we cannot guarantee that every person who visits the site is a child.\"<ref name=\"Kiely\" />\n\nOn August 20, 2013, Disney announced that ''[[Toontown Online]]'', ''[[Pixie Hollow (video game)|Pixie Hollow]]'', and ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean Online]]'' were closing directly because of ''Club Penguin'' and Disney's mobile games. This caused major controversy between ''Club Penguin'' and fans of the three games, especially ''Toontown'', where some users had played for more than 12 years (''Toontown''<nowiki/>'s [[Alpha-test|alpha test]] started in August 2001).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/23/tech/gaming-gadgets/closing-toontown/ | work=CNN | title=Coping with the loss of an online world \u2013 CNN.com | date=August 24, 2013 | access-date=August 24, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823225043/http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/23/tech/gaming-gadgets/closing-toontown | archive-date=August 23, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Private servers ==\nA Club Penguin Private Server (commonly abbreviated and known as a CPPS) is an online multiplayer game that is not part of ''Club Penguin'', but uses [[SWF]] files from ''Club Penguin'', a database, and a server emulator in order to create a similar environment for the game. Many now use these environments in order to play the original game after its discontinuation. CPPSs often contain features that did not exist in the original game such as custom items and rooms, free membership, etc.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nThroughout the official game's existence, various players created private servers of ''Club Penguin'', and in response to the its closure, more private servers were created. ''Club Penguin Rewritten'', launched February 12, 2017&nbsp;\u2013 had reached a million players as of October 12, 2017,<ref name=Cooley>{{cite magazine |url=http://culture.affinitymagazine.us/save-club-penguin-the-game-we-know-and-love/ |magazine=Affinity |title=Save Club Penguin: The Game We Know and Love |first=Marcus |last=Cooley |access-date=November 4, 2017 |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102064051/http://culture.affinitymagazine.us/save-club-penguin-the-game-we-know-and-love/ |archive-date=November 2, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> though discontinued \"permanently\" on March 4, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://community.cprewritten.net/announcement.php |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226202443/https://community.cprewritten.net/announcement.php |archive-date=February 26, 2018 |date=February 26, 2018 |title=Announcement Regarding the future of Club Penguin Rewritten |publisher=Club Penguin Rewritten }}</ref> Citing community support and funding, it returned in April 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://community.cprewritten.net/2018/04/27/the-island-has-returned/ |title=The Island Has Returned! |author=Stu |website=Club Penguin Rewritten |date=April 27, 2018 |access-date=April 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430182212/https://community.cprewritten.net/2018/04/27/the-island-has-returned/ |archive-date=April 30, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The private server had at least four million player accounts in July 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nakedsecurity.sophos.com/2019/08/02/4-million-club-penguin-rewritten-accounts-exposed-in-breach/ |title=4 million Club Penguin Rewritten accounts exposed in breach |date=August 2, 2019 |website=Naked Security |publisher=[[Sophos]] |first=John E. |last=Dunn |access-date=April 9, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic|2020 COVID-19 pandemic]], the ''Club Penguin Online'' private server game passed six million players.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-gb/2020/04/9647031/club-penguin-back-play-online-2020 |title=Disney's Club Penguin Is Back |last=Cort\u00e9s |first=Michelle Santiago |website=Refinery29 |language=en-GB |access-date=April 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Legal status ===\nSince private servers essentially copy materials copyrighted by Disney, there has been much controversy as to whether or not creating and hosting them is legal. Disney and ''Club Penguin'' have pursued numerous CPPSs and attempted to have them taken down with [[DMCA]] notices.<ref>{{cite web|title=Notice by Club Penguin Rewritten that they are switching domains due to Disney's legal action|url=https://clubpenguinrewritten.pw/|accessdate=October 22, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022113002/https://clubpenguinrewritten.pw/|archivedate=October 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Vulnerabilities ===\nMany private servers have become vulnerable to DDOS attacks and database leaks due to insufficient security measures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.speedycppshq.com/breaking-news-cpps-me-breach/|title=CPPS.me Database Breach|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712162751/http://www.speedycppshq.com/breaking-news-cpps-me-breach/|archivedate=July 12, 2018|accessdate=June 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.speedycppshq.com/breaking-news-supercpps-database-breach-10000-accounts/|title=SuperCPPS Database Breach|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712162738/http://www.speedycppshq.com/breaking-news-supercpps-database-breach-10000-accounts/|archivedate=July 12, 2018|accessdate=June 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2019, the login data of over 4 million ''Club Penguin Rewritten'' users was stolen after a data breach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/logins-stolen-from-admin-backdoored-club-penguin-rewritten-site/|title=Logins Stolen From Admin-Backdoored Club Penguin Rewritten Site|website=BleepingComputer|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821084353/https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/logins-stolen-from-admin-backdoored-club-penguin-rewritten-site/|archive-date=August 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{expand list|date=June 2013}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|+\n!Year !! Award !! Title !! Recipient !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2008\n|Web Marketing Association Entertainment Standard of Excellence\n|\n| rowspan=\"8\" |Club Penguin\n|{{won}}\n| <ref name=\"Web Marketing Association\">{{cite web|title=Walt Disney Internet Group wins 2008 WebAward for Club Penguin|url=http://www.webaward.org/winner.asp?eid=10249#.Uyjl1_38_B0|publisher=Web Marketing Association|accessdate=March 18, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319033556/http://www.webaward.org/winner.asp?eid=10249#.Uyjl1_38_B0|archive-date=March 19, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Web Marketing Association Game Site Standard of Excellence\n|\n|{{won}}\n| <ref name=\"Web Marketing Association\" />\n|-\n|2008 [[Webby Award]]s, Youth Category\n|\n|{{nominated}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Youth The Webby Awards Gallery|url=http://winners.webbyawards.com/2008/web/general-website/youth/club-penguin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313081053/http://winners.webbyawards.com/2008/web/general-website/youth/club-penguin|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 13, 2014|accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\n|2009 [[Webby Award]]s, Games Category\n|\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Games The Webby Awards Gallery|url=http://winners.webbyawards.com/2009/web/general-website-categories/games/club-penguin|publisher=The Webby Awards|accessdate=March 13, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313070520/http://winners.webbyawards.com/2009/web/general-website-categories/games/club-penguin|archivedate=March 13, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010\n|Children's [[BAFTA Award]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Kids Vote\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=2010 Children's BAFTA Kids' Vote|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2010/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-websites|publisher=BAFTA|accessdate=February 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302010843/http://awards.bafta.org/award/2010/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-websites|archive-date=March 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011\n|Children's [[BAFTA Award]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 Children's BAFTA Kids Vote Powered By Yahoo!|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2011/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-powered-by-yahoo-top-10s-websites|publisher=BAFTA|accessdate=February 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317212659/http://awards.bafta.org/award/2011/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-powered-by-yahoo-top-10s-websites|archive-date=March 17, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012\n|Children's [[BAFTA Award]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=2012 Children's BAFTA Kids' Vote|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2012/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-websites|publisher=BAFTA|accessdate=February 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305073547/http://awards.bafta.org/award/2012/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-websites|archive-date=March 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013\n|Children's [[BAFTA Award]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Children's BAFTA Kids' Vote|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2013/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-websites|publisher=BAFTA|accessdate=February 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408090200/http://awards.bafta.org/award/2013/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-websites|archive-date=April 8, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|En-club-penguin.ogg|2019-11-06}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.superclubpenguin.com/ |title=Club Penguin Website |accessdate=December 30, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330010044/http://www.clubpenguin.com/ |archivedate=March 30, 2017 |df= }}\n* [https://www.clubpenguinisland.com/ Official ''Club Penguin'' Island website]\n* [http://www.zdnet.com/article/the-technology-behind-disneys-club-penguin/ The technology behind Disney's Club Penguin]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2005 video games]]\n[[Category:Browser games]]\n[[Category:Children's websites]]\n[[Category:Club Penguin| ]]\n[[Category:Disney video games]]\n[[Category:Disney acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Fictional penguins]]\n[[Category:Inactive massively multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Internet properties disestablished in 2017]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Massively multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Miniclip games]]\n[[Category:Persistent worlds]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Canada]]\n[[Category:Webby Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "Adavidb", "label": "safe", "comment": "just \"clubpenguin.com\", not two N's and not super", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Club_Penguin"}
{"title_page": "Project Longshot", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n[[File:Project Longshot configurations.png|right|thumb|{{ordered list |Initial configuration |Configuration at 33 years |Configuration at 67 years |Configuration at 100 years}}]]\n'''Project Longshot''' was a conceptual [[interstellar spacecraft]] design. It would have been an [[Unmanned spacecraft|unmanned]] [[space probe|probe]], intended to fly to and enter orbit around [[Alpha Centauri|Alpha Centauri B]] powered by [[nuclear pulse propulsion]].<ref name=\"long1\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Project Longshot |url=http://www.realclearscience.com/lists/3_canceled_nasa_projects/ |newspaper=Real Clear Science |location=United States |date 22 april 2014= |access-date=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDeveloped by the [[US Naval Academy]] and [[NASA]], from 1987 to 1988, Longshot was designed to be built at [[Space Station Freedom|Space Station ''Freedom'']], the precursor to the existing [[International Space Station]]. Similar to [[Project Daedalus]], Longshot was designed with existing technology in mind, although some development would have been required; for example, the Project Longshot concept assumes \"a three-order-of-magnitude leap over current propulsion technology.\" <ref name=\"long1\"/>\n\n==Mission==\nUnlike Daedalus, which used an open-cycle [[fusion power|fusion engine]], Longshot would use a long-lived [[nuclear fission]] reactor for power. Initially generating 300 kilowatts, the reactor would power several [[laser]]s in the engine that would be used to ignite [[inertial confinement fusion]] similar to that in Daedalus. The main design difference is that Daedalus also relied on the [[fusion reaction]] to power the ship, whereas in the Longshot design the internal reactor would provide this power.<ref name=\"long1\"/>\n\nThe reactor would also be used to power a laser for communications back to Earth, with a maximum power of 250&nbsp;kW. For most of the journey, this would be used at much lower power for sending data about the [[interstellar medium]]. Still, during the flyby, the main engine section would be discarded and the entire power capacity dedicated to communications at about 1 kilobit per second.\n\nLongshot would have a mass of {{convert|396|t|lb}} at the start of the mission including 264 tonnes of [[helium-3]]/[[deuterium]] pellet fuel/propellant. The active mission payload, which includes the [[fission reactor]] but not the discarded main propulsion section, would have a mass of around 30 tonnes.\n\nA difference in the [[mission architecture]] between Longshot and the Daedalus study is that Longshot would go into orbit about the target star. At the same time, the higher speed Daedalus would do a one-shot [[Planetary flyby|fly-by]] lasting a comparatively short time.\n\nThe journey to [[Alpha Centauri|Alpha Centauri B]] orbit would take about 100 years, at an average velocity of approximately 13,411&nbsp;km/s (about 4.5% the speed of light) and another 4.39&nbsp;years would be necessary for the data to reach [[Earth]].\n\nAccording to the Journal article \"Alpha Centauri: Our First target for Interstellar Probes,\" after the completion of the New Horizons primary mission of Pluto Fly-By, we should set our sights at other star systems like Alpha Centauri. This would be a good target because of its proximity to Earth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Alpha_Centauri_Our_First_Target_for_Interstellar_Probes_999.html|title=Alpha Centauri: Our First Target for Interstellar Probes|work=spacedaily.com|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight|Space}}\n* [[Alpha Centauri Bb]]\n* [[Breakthrough Starshot]]\n* [[Interstellar travel]]\n* [[Nuclear pulse propulsion]]\n* [[Project Daedalus]]\n* [[Project Orion (nuclear propulsion)]]\n* [[Project Icarus (interstellar)|Project Icarus]]\n* [[Spacecraft propulsion]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\nBeals, K. A., M. Beaulieu, F. J. Dembia, J. Kerstiens, D. L. Kramer, J. R. West, and J. A. Zito. [http://large.stanford.edu/courses/2012/ph241/klein2/docs/19890007533_1989007533.pdf ''Project Longshot: An Unmanned Probe To Alpha Centauri.''] U S Naval Academy. NASA-CR-184718. 1988.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Project Longshot}}\n{{Wikisource-inline|links=''[[s:en:Project Longshot|Project Longshot: An Unmanned Probe To Alpha Centauri]]''|single=true}} (Please note that the article cited here refers to an Alpha and Beta Centauri as the orbital target of the mission, but the correct nomenclature for these two components of the Alpha Centauri binary star system is Alpha Centauri A and B. [[Beta Centauri]] is an entirely different, unassociated star.)\n\n{{Nuclear propulsion}}\n\n[[Category:Hypothetical spacecraft]]\n[[Category:Nuclear spacecraft propulsion|Longshot]]\n[[Category:Interstellar travel]]\n[[Category:NASA programs]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy]]\n[[Category:Alpha Centauri]]\n[[Category:1987 in science]]\n[[Category:1988 in science]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n[[File:Project Longshot configurations.png|right|thumb|{{ordered list |Initial configuration |Configuration at 33 years |Configuration at 67 years |Configuration at 100 years}}]]\n'''Project Longshot''' was a conceptual [[interstellar spacecraft]] design. It would have been an [[Unmanned spacecraft|unmanned]] [[space probe|probe]], intended to fly to and enter orbit around [[Alpha Centauri|Alpha Centauri B]] powered by [[nuclear pulse propulsion]].<ref name=\"long1\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Project Longshot |url=http://www.realclearscience.com/lists/3_canceled_nasa_projects/ |newspaper=Real Clear Science |location=United States |date 22 april 2014= |access-date=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDeveloped by the [[US Naval Academy]] and [[NASA]], from 1987 to 1988, Longshot was designed to be built at [[Space Station Freedom|Space Station ''Freedom'']], the precursor to the existing [[International Space Station]]. Similar to [[Project Daedalus]], Longshot was designed with existing technology in mind, although some development would have been required; for example, the Project Longshot concept assumes \"a three-order-of-magnitude leap over current propulsion technology\".<ref name=\"long1\"/>\n\n==Mission==\nUnlike Daedalus, which used an open-cycle [[fusion power|fusion engine]], Longshot would use a long-lived [[nuclear fission]] reactor for power. Initially generating 300 kilowatts, the reactor would power a number of [[laser]]s in the engine that would be used to ignite [[inertial confinement fusion]] similar to that in Daedalus. The main design difference is that Daedalus also relied on the [[fusion reaction]] to power the ship, whereas in the Longshot design the internal reactor would provide this power.<ref name=\"long1\"/>\n\nThe reactor would also be used to power a laser for communications back to Earth, with a maximum power of 250&nbsp;kW. For most of the journey, this would be used at a much lower power for sending data about the [[interstellar medium]]; but during the flyby, the main engine section would be discarded and the entire power capacity dedicated to communications at about 1 kilobit per second.\n\nLongshot would have a mass of {{convert|396|t|lb}} at the start of the mission including 264 tonnes of [[helium-3]]/[[deuterium]] pellet fuel/propellant. The active mission payload, which includes the [[fission reactor]] but not the discarded main propulsion section, would have a mass of around 30 tonnes.\n\nA difference in the [[mission architecture]] between Longshot and the Daedalus study is that Longshot would go into orbit about the target star while the higher speed Daedalus would do a one shot [[Planetary flyby|fly-by]] lasting a comparatively short time.\n\nThe journey to [[Alpha Centauri|Alpha Centauri B]] orbit would take about 100 years, at an average velocity of approximately 13,411&nbsp;km/s (about 4.5% the speed of light) and another 4.39&nbsp;years would be necessary for the data to reach [[Earth]].\n\nAccording to the Journal article \"Alpha Centauri: Our First target for Interstellar Probes,\" after the completion of the New Horizons primary mission of Pluto Fly-By, we should set our sights at other star systems like Alpha Centauri. This would be a good target because of its proximity to Earth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Alpha_Centauri_Our_First_Target_for_Interstellar_Probes_999.html|title=Alpha Centauri: Our First Target for Interstellar Probes|work=spacedaily.com|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight|Space}}\n* [[Alpha Centauri Bb]]\n* [[Breakthrough Starshot]]\n* [[Interstellar travel]]\n* [[Nuclear pulse propulsion]]\n* [[Project Daedalus]]\n* [[Project Orion (nuclear propulsion)]]\n* [[Project Icarus (interstellar)|Project Icarus]]\n* [[Spacecraft propulsion]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\nBeals, K. A., M. Beaulieu, F. J. Dembia, J. Kerstiens, D. L. Kramer, J. R. West and J. A. Zito. [http://large.stanford.edu/courses/2012/ph241/klein2/docs/19890007533_1989007533.pdf ''Project Longshot: An Unmanned Probe To Alpha Centauri.''] U S Naval Academy. NASA-CR-184718. 1988.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Project Longshot}}\n{{Wikisource-inline|links=''[[s:en:Project Longshot|Project Longshot: An Unmanned Probe To Alpha Centauri]]''|single=true}} (Please note that the article cited here refers to an Alpha and Beta Centauri as the orbital target of the mission, but the correct nomenclature for these two components of the Alpha Centauri binary star system is Alpha Centauri A and B. [[Beta Centauri]] is an entirely different, unassociated star.)\n\n{{Nuclear propulsion}}\n\n[[Category:Hypothetical spacecraft]]\n[[Category:Nuclear spacecraft propulsion|Longshot]]\n[[Category:Interstellar travel]]\n[[Category:NASA programs]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy]]\n[[Category:Alpha Centauri]]\n[[Category:1987 in science]]\n[[Category:1988 in science]]\n", "name_user": "Broadwood-park", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling, punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Project_Longshot"}
{"title_page": "The Masked Singer (American TV series)", "text_new": "{{About||the current season|The Masked Singer (American season 3)}}\n{{short description|American reality singing competition television show}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name      = The Masked Singer\n| image          = File:Masked Singer USA Logo.png\n| image_alt      = Title card of ''The Masked Singer''\n| caption        = \n| genre          = [[Reality competition]]<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\">{{cite web|last=Piester|first=Lauren|title= The Secrets of ''The Masked Singer'': Everything We've Learned About TV's Most Mysterious Show |url=https://www.eonline.com/ca/news/1019279/the-secrets-of-the-masked-singer-everything-we-ve-learned-about-tv-s-most-mysterious-show|date=February 27, 2019|website=[[E!#E! Online|E!]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703044452/https://www.eonline.com/ca/news/1019279/the-secrets-of-the-masked-singer-everything-we-ve-learned-about-tv-s-most-mysterious-show|archive-date=July 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| creator        = \n| based_on       = {{based_on|''[[King of Mask Singer]]''|[[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation]]}}\n| developer      = [[Craig Plestis]]\n| director       = {{unbulleted list|Alex Rudzinski|Brad Duns}}\n| presenter      = [[Nick Cannon]]\n| starring       = {{unbulleted list|[[Ken Jeong]]|[[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]|[[Nicole Scherzinger]]|[[Robin Thicke]]}}\n| narrated       = \n| composer       = \n| executive_producer = {{unbulleted list|Craig Plestis ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1\u2013)|Izzie Pick Ibarra ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1\u2013)|Rosie Seitchik ({{abbr|s.|season}} 2\u2013)|Nick Cannon ({{abbr|s.|season}} 3\u2013)}}\n| producer       = \n| company        = {{unbulleted list|[[Endemol Shine North America]] ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1)|Fox Alternative Entertainment ({{abbr|s.|season}} 2\u2013)}}\n| distributor    = {{unbulleted list|[[Fox Corporation]]|Propagate Content}}\n| location       = \n| camera         = \n| runtime        = 42\u201385 minutes\n| opentheme      = {{theme_song|\"[[Who Are You (The Who song)|Who Are You]]\"|[[The Who]]}}\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| network        = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| channel        = \n| picture_format = \n| audio_format   = \n| first_run      = \n| released       = \n| first_aired    = {{Start date|2019|1|2}}\n| last_aired     = present\n| num_seasons    = 3\n| num_episodes   = 36<!-- as of April 15, 2020 -->\n| list_episodes  = List of The Masked Singer (American TV series) episodes\n| preceded_by    = \n| related        = {{unbulletedlist|''The Masked Singer: After the Mask''|''The Masked Dancer''}}\n| website        = https://www.fox.com/the-masked-singer/\n| production_website = https://www.smartdogmedia.com/the-masked-singer\n}}\n\n'''''The Masked Singer''''' is an American [[Reality competition|reality singing competition]] television series, part of the ''[[Masked Singer]]'' franchise, featuring celebrities in head-to-toe costumes and face masks which conceal their identities from other contestants, panelists, and an audience. The series premiered on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] on January 2, 2019, and is hosted by [[Nick Cannon]].\n\nThe series is currently in its [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|third season]] which premiered [[List of Super Bowl lead-out programs|after]] [[Super Bowl LIV]] on February 2, 2020. In an interview prior to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Rob Wade, President of Alternative Entertainment and Specials at Fox, confirmed that future seasons of the show are planned.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 6\">{{cite web|last=Daswani|first=Mansha|title=Fox Entertainment's Rob Wade|url=https://worldscreen.com/tvformats/fox-entertainments-rob-wade/|website=TV Formats|date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416012653/https://worldscreen.com/tvformats/fox-entertainments-rob-wade/|archive-date=April 15, 2020|url-status=live|quote=And then ''The Masked Dancer'' is coming up soon. And future cycles of ''The Masked Singer.''}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n{{Listen|pos=left|filename=Masked Singer US Monster Voiceover.ogg|title=Monster voiceover|description=A sample of a typical voiceover in a clue package showing how modulation is used to disguise the actual identity of the performers on the show while they give hints about their backgrounds.|format=[[Ogg]]}}\nA group of [[Celebrity|celebrities]] compete on the show anonymously in costumes over a series of episodes. The specific format of the competition varies by season and episode, depending on how many celebrities remain, but generally, each episode features four to six celebrities performing a cover of a famous song, with the audience voting for their favorite. The celebrity with the fewest votes in that episode is eliminated from the competition and must take off their mask and reveal their identity.<ref name=\"PeopleS3\">{{cite web|last=Stone|first=Natalie|title=The Masked Singer Renewed for Season 3, to Premiere After 2020 Super Bowl|url=https://people.com/tv/the-masked-singer-renewed-for-season-3/|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220055111/https://people.com/tv/the-masked-singer-renewed-for-season-3/|archive-date=February 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the singing competition, hints to each masked singer's identity are offered during the show, referred to as the \"clue package\" by the panelists. Such clues may feature cryptic allusions to what the celebrity is known for, or may be more direct references. Pre-taped interviews are given as hints and feature celebrities' electronically masked voices. The panelists are given time to speculate the identity of the singer after the performance, including the opportunity to ask questions or gain additional clues offered by the host.<ref name=\"PeopleS3\"/>\n\n==Panelists and host==\n{{multiple image\n| total_width = 450\n| total_height\n| align = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1   = Ken Jeong March 2015.jpg\n| alt1     = Ken Jeong\n| caption1 = [[Ken Jeong]]\n| image2   = Jenny McCarthy at E3 2006.jpg\n| alt2     = Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg\n| caption2 = [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]\n| image3   = Nicole Scherzinger 2012.jpg\n| alt3     = Nicole Scherzinger\n| caption3 = [[Nicole Scherzinger]]\n| image4   = Robin Thicke 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg\n| alt4     = Robin Thicke\n| caption4 = [[Robin Thicke]]\n| image5   = Nick Cannon by David Shankbone.jpg\n| alt5     = Nick Cannon\n| caption5 = [[Nick Cannon]] \n}}\n\nSince the first season, the permanent panel has consisted of actor and comedian [[Ken Jeong]], television personality [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]], recording artist [[Nicole Scherzinger]], and singer-songwriter [[Robin Thicke]], with [[Nick Cannon]] hosting the show.<ref name=\"VAR Aug 2\">{{cite web|last=Birnbaum|first=Debra|title=Fox Orders ''Masked Singer'' Reality Series; Nick Cannon to Host|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/fox-masked-singer-reality-series-nick-cannon-1202893337/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102132907/https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/fox-masked-singer-reality-series-nick-cannon-1202893337/|archive-date=November 2, 2019|date=August 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThere are often guest panelists that appear as the fifth panelist on the series\u2014occasionally for multiple episodes. In the first season, they were [[Joel McHale]] (episodes 3\u20134), [[J. B. Smoove]] (episode 7), and [[Kenan Thompson]](episodes 8 and 10). In the second season, they were [[Anthony Anderson]] (episode 6), [[Triumph the Insult Comic Dog]] (Robert Smigel; episode 7), McHale (episodes 8\u20139), and the winner of the first season, [[T-Pain]] (episode 10). In the third season, the guest panelists included [[Jamie Foxx]] (episode 1), [[Jason Biggs]] (episode 2), [[Leah Remini]] (episode 3), [[Gabriel Iglesias]] (episode 5), T-Pain (episode 6), McHale (episode 8), [[Will Arnett]] (episode 9), and [[Yvette Nicole Brown]] (episode 11), with [[Sharon Osbourne]] set to appear in the twelfth<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-313) \"The Mother Of All Final Face Offs, Part 2\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200402fox05/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]}}</ref> and [[Gordon Ramsay]] in the thirteenth.<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-314) \"The Battle of The Sixes: The Final 6\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200408fox06/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none; font-size:90%; width:30%;\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\"| Panelist timeline\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:15%;\"| Panelists\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"width:15%;\"| Seasons\n|-\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|1]]\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 2)|2]]\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|3]]\n|-\n| [[Ken Jeong]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Nicole Scherzinger]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Robin Thicke]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Joel McHale]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[J.B. Smoove]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Kenan Thompson]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Anthony Anderson]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Triumph the Comic Insult Dog]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[T-Pain]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jamie Foxx]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jason Biggs]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Leah Remini]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Gabriel Iglesias]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Will Arnett]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Yvette Nicole Brown]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Sharon Osbourne]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Gordon Ramsay]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|}\n\n==Production==\n===Conception and development===\n{{quote box|quote=So we're at a restaurant and my back is to the TV. My daughter said Dad, look at this, there's this crazy thing on. I turned around and all the diners were watching the TV screen. I saw a kangaroo in black pleather singing a pop song. At that moment I said, oh my gosh, I love this! It was bizarre. It was flypaper. It was in a foreign language and you didn't know what was going on, and it was still working. I found out that it was a hit format in Korea, it was a hit show in Thailand. And no one had the [U.S.] rights.|source=\u2014Plestis on the creation of ''The Masked Singer''<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\">{{cite magazine|last=Daswani|first=Mansha|title=Craig Plestis|url=https://issuu.com/worldscreen/docs/tv_formats_miptv_2019|page=38|magazine=TV Formats|date=April 2019|via=[[Issuu]]}}</ref>|align=right|width=35em}}\n\n''The Masked Singer'' is based on the South Korean series ''[[King of Mask Singer]]''. Television producer [[Craig Plestis]] explained that he first discovered the format during a visit to a small [[Los Angeles]] Thai restaurant in October 2017. While waiting for dinner, he observed the other patrons staring at a television while an episode of the [[The Mask Singer (season 3)|third season]] of the [[The Mask Singer (Thai TV series)|Thai version]] of the show was playing. Intrigued, Plestis began to research the series and secured the rights to produce an American adaptation within one week in a deal brokered by Steve Wohl of [[Paradigm Talent Agency]]. Plestis then called Fox executive Rob Wade on a Friday night telling him he needed to come in the following Monday and worked to create a showcase during the weekend. After successfully pitching the show to Wade, the series began development in November,<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\"/><ref name=\"THR Jan 2\">{{cite web|last=Bentley|first=Jean|title=''The Masked Singer'': How the Fox Reality Show Scored Top Talent (and Kept It Secret)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/masked-singer-ep-explains-how-his-insane-reality-competition-made-it-air-1171775|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713155810/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/masked-singer-ep-explains-how-his-insane-reality-competition-made-it-air-1171775|archive-date=July 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=White|first=Peter|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/fox-remaking-asian-singing-contest-the-masked-singer-1202206986/|title=Fox Developing Remake of Asian Talent Competition ''The Masked Singer''|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521062138/https://deadline.com/2017/11/fox-remaking-asian-singing-contest-the-masked-singer-1202206986/|archive-date=May 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\">{{cite web|last=Ravindran|first=Manori|title=How ''Masked Singer'' is reviving costume-led formats|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/04/05/costume-drama/|website=Television Business International|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407120916/https://tbivision.com/2019/04/05/costume-drama/|archive-date=April 7, 2019|date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and was officially ordered by Fox in August 2018.<ref name=\"VAR Aug 2\"/>\n\n[[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation]], the rightsholder of the ''Masked Singer'' format, lacked the ability to produce the series. As a result, the [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|first season]]  was produced by [[Endemol Shine North America]], then-owned partly by Fox's parent company [[21st Century Fox]] (the stake is now owned by [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]]) due to Plestis' relationship with the studio. For the [[The Masked Singer (American season 2)|second season]], production transitioned to a new in-house studio, Fox Alternative Entertainment, and the show's budget was lowered as a result.<ref>{{cite web|last=Haynes|first=Dade|title=''The Masked Singer'' Renewed For Third Season, Gets Post-Super Bowl Slot On|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/the-masked-singer-season-3-to-premiere-after-super-bowl-liv-on-fox-1202613462/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830010304/https://deadline.com/2019/05/the-masked-singer-season-3-to-premiere-after-super-bowl-liv-on-fox-1202613462/|archive-date=August 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-launching-unscripted-studio-masked-singer-1209087|title=Fox Launching Unscripted Studio With ''The Masked Singer'' (Exclusive)|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817034711/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-launching-unscripted-studio-masked-singer-1209087|archive-date=August 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Wade said this gave the network further creative control over the series and allowed it to sell merchandise, launch a national tour, and create spin-off show ''The Masked Dancer''.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 6\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nExecutive producer Izzie Pick Ibarra was ecstatic when Nick Cannon agreed to host the show, citing him as her number-one choice for the role because of his personality and experience. Regarding the panelists, she said the production team was less concerned with selecting those with an ability to critique participants' singing abilities than being able to create a comedic tone for the show as one of their goals was to reassure celebrities they would not be ridiculed for choosing to appear. Jeong was the first panelist to be signed on to the series due to his humour and pre-existing knowledge of the South Korean version, followed by McCarthy Wahlberg, Thicke, and Scherzinger.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> On March 28, 2019, Sharon Osbourne revealed on ''[[The Talk (talk show)|The Talk]]'' she was originally supposed to be signed on as a panelist for the series; those plans fell through after being contractually obligated to appear on ''[[The X Factor (British TV series)|The X Factor]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Furdyk|first=Brent|url=https://etcanada.com/news/435743/sharon-osbourne-shreds-simon-cowell-for-firing-her-from-the-x-factor-because-he-thought-i-was-too-old/|title=Sharon Osbourne Shreds Simon Cowell For Firing Her From ''The X Factor'' Because He \"Thought I Was Too Old\"|website=[[Entertainment Tonight Canada|ET Canada]]|date=March 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330152540/https://etcanada.com/news/435743/sharon-osbourne-shreds-simon-cowell-for-firing-her-from-the-x-factor-because-he-thought-i-was-too-old/|archive-date=March 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIbarra described casting for the series' first season as less difficult than she predicted due to her strategy of sending the possible participants sketches of costumes that might be featured on the series. She said many of the celebrities had emotional reactions when presented with the proposed costumes and that they were excited about using the show as a way of reinventing their [[reputation|public image]]. [[T-Pain]], the winner of the first season, said he was skeptical about the series until he saw the costume choices, citing the opportunity to wear the Monster outfit as his motivation for participating in the show.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jensen|first=Erin|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/03/22/t-pain-masked-singer-winner-pitch/3244569002/|title=''Masked Singer'' winner T-Pain first deemed show \"probably the stupidest thing\" he'd heard|website=[[USA Today]]|date=March 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111040704/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/03/22/t-pain-masked-singer-winner-pitch/3244569002/|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Conversely, [[Wayne Brady]], the winner of the second season, was approached by producers to appear in the first season but turned them down after being confused about the show's concept.<ref name=\"VAR Dec 18\">{{cite web|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-winner-interview-wayne-brady-the-fox-season-2-1203447936/|title=''The Masked Singer'' Winner Interview: \"It's the First Time in My Life I Kept a Secret Months on End\"|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110134353/https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-winner-interview-wayne-brady-the-fox-season-2-1203447936/|archive-date=January 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Those who are not professional singers send the show's production crew clips of them singing as a quasi-audition before participating in the series.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\">{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/television/8549443/masked-singer-showrunner-season-3-changes-surprises-interview|title=''Masked Singer'' Showrunner Promises Big Changes for Season 3, Says Cast is \"Unbelievably Interesting\"|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207084115/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/television/8549443/masked-singer-showrunner-season-3-changes-surprises-interview|archive-date=February 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:CBS TelevisionCity02.jpg|thumb|left|alt=refer to caption|The series is filmed at [[Television City]] studios in Los Angeles.]]\nThe series is filmed at [[Television City]] in Los Angeles, California in a studio that seats 380 people.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Keegan|first=Kayla|title=Going to a ''Masked Singer'' Taping Is Like Visiting a Top-Secret CIA Compound|url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|website=[[Good Housekeeping]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405081745/https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|archive-date=April 5, 2020|date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first season was filmed from June 4, 2018, to June 28, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|website=On Camera Audiences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526204614/http://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|archive-date=May 26, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> the second from July 1, 2019, to August 19, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|website=On Camera Audiences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714070242/http://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|archive-date=July 14, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the third from December 19, 2019, to February 28, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|website=On Camera Audiences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228120213/https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> Despite the show having a much shorter filming schedule than most television shows,<ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\">{{cite web|last=VanDerWerff|first=Todd|title=''The Masked Singer'' is one of TV's oddest shows. Here's how it was made.|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/2/27/18241269/masked-singer-interview-finale-recap-preview|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402114050/https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/2/27/18241269/masked-singer-interview-finale-recap-preview|archive-date=April 2, 2019|date=February 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> filming dates were occasionally moved to accommodate celebrities' other activities.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\">{{cite web|last=Turchiano|first=Danielle|title=''The Masked Singer'' Boss on Importance of Contestant Secrecy|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-contestant-secrecy-hippo-unmasked-1203089606/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706101843/https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-contestant-secrecy-hippo-unmasked-1203089606/|archive-date=July 6, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Plestis, the contestants sing live and their voices remain unedited in [[post-production]].<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Thicke noted that guessing is a challenge for the panelists due to sound issues in the studio often obscuring performers' voices and that it takes multiple performances for them to catch on to who the celebrity might be. Plestis said the panelists' guesses are heavily edited due to their extensiveness. They are forbidden from [[Google (verb)|googling]] possible answers to the clues presented to them between the filming of episodes.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/><ref name=\"ADW Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Jason|title=How The Masked Singer Became Broadcast's Biggest Midseason Hit|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/how-the-masked-singer-became-broadcasts-biggest-midseason-hit/|website=[[Adweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513171046/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/how-the-masked-singer-became-broadcasts-biggest-midseason-hit/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|date=February 6, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Before the participants take off their masks, the producers film the entire studio audience acting out how they would react to the moment, with only a select twenty \"extremely well-vetted\" people remaining in the audience during the actual reveal.<ref name=\"THR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/>\n\n===Security===\nBefore each of the competitors is unmasked, the show's staff undertakes significant security measures to prevent the participants' identities from leaking, many of which, according to Plestis, originate from his visits to the sets of the South Korean and Thai versions of the show.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> Everyone involved in the series signs a [[non-disclosure agreement]]; after the celebrities have been confirmed to appear on the show, they are allowed to inform a few others who also sign one.<ref name=\"VAR Dec 18\"/> They are not allowed to discuss their participation on the show until the day the episode of their reveal airs on television.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Before arriving on the show's set, the participants and their family, friends, and agents are disguised and driven from a neutral location.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> The manager of [[Joey Fatone]], the Rabbit in the first season, said he was picked up at a [[7-Eleven]] near Television City, given a disguise, and then driven inside the gate.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> Likewise, [[Adrienne Bailon]], the Flamingo in the second season, said she was taken to the set inside of an unmarked black car and only discussed her involvement on the show with producers in a \"secret warehouse.\"<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/>\n\nThe series' security team is almost as large as the production crew.<ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\"/> While on set, each participant is escorted by security guards and is disguised with a mask, visor, gloves, oversized sweatshirt, and pants to prevent their skin from showing.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\"/> Twenty-five people knew the actual identities of the contestants in advance of the first season, though they never referred to them as such on set, in emails, or during phone calls regarding the show. Ibarra said even the show's writers and director were uninformed of the participants' identities until they were unmasked. [[Margaret Cho]], the Poodle in the first season, said she never encountered another participant due to the performers' rehearsals occurring at varying times and locations.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/>\n\n===Costumes===\n[[File:Marina Toybina.png|thumb|upright=0.8|alt=refer to caption|The costumes for the series are designed by Marina Toybina.]]\nPlestis described the series' costumes as \"extremely critical\" to the show, adding \"so much money\" is invested in them.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Villareal|first=Yvonne|title=''The Masked Singer'' costume designer takes us inside TV's most colorful closet|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-masked-singer-fox-costumes-marina-toybina-20190206-story.html|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328233157/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-masked-singer-fox-costumes-marina-toybina-20190206-story.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|date=February 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  They are designed by [[Emmy Award]]-winner Marina Toybina who, using a variety of inspirations, develops the concepts herself. She begins by sketching each costume idea with a pencil and then gives the drawings to one of her friends who creates a digital version. After the costume concepts are shared with the show's producers and Fox executives who decide which designs will be featured during a season, Toybina buys all of the necessary fabrics herself and collaborates with a team of twenty to thirty people to custom-make them.<ref name=\"DH Costume\">{{cite web|last=Grobar|first=Matt|title=How ''The Masked Singer'' Costume Designer Marina Toybina Crafted 12 Full-Body Art Pieces In Under Two Months|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina-emmys-fox-interview-1202660891/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913182757/https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina-emmys-fox-interview-1202660891/|archive-date=September 13, 2019|date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nEach costume costs thousands of dollars to make over two months and the masks are designed to prevent echoes.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/><ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\"/><ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Beginning as a wire mesh; foam is gradually added around the mask, creating an easy-to-wear helmet shape for the performer.<ref name=\"TC Mar 1\">{{cite web|last=Spellings|first=Sarah|title=How Heavy Were Those ''The Masked Singer'' Masks, Anyway?|url=https://www.thecut.com/2019/03/interview-the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#The Cut|The Cut]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328233201/https://www.thecut.com/2019/03/interview-the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|date=March 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"AVC\">{{cite web|title=How The Masked Singer's costume designer dreams up the show's insane outfits|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eShX30efZd8|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=August 29, 2019|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Toybina says she purposely uses foam for the costumes instead of wood or metal as their heavy weight would make the costumes difficult to move around in.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> As \"the draping and the handwork [for the costumes are] all done the old school way,\" she cites fashion designers [[Alexander McQueen]], [[Thierry Mugler]], and [[Hussein Chalayan]] as inspirations<ref name=\"HP Costume\">{{cite web|last=Frank|first=Priscilla|title=The Maniacal Costume Designer Behind 'The Masked Singer' Speaks|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/costume-designer-masked-singer-marina-toybina_n_5c4f3992e4b0f43e41099257|url-status=live|website=[[HuffPost]]|publisher=[[Verizon Media]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915172544/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/costume-designer-masked-singer-marina-toybina_n_5c4f3992e4b0f43e41099257|archive-date=September 15, 2019|date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"VAR Jan 10\">{{cite web|last=Friedlander|first=Whitney|title=Meet the ''Masked Singer'' Costume Designer Behind Those Elaborate Looks|url=https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/masked-singer-costume-designer-1203103034/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222072254/https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/masked-singer-costume-designer-1203103034/|archive-date=December 22, 2019|date=January 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"VF Costume\">{{cite magazine|last=Bradley|first=Laura|date=January 23, 2019|title=How The Masked Singer Dreamed Up Those Delightfully Delirious Costumes|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/the-masked-singer-costumes-designer-marina-toybina|url-status=live|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915040813/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/the-masked-singer-costumes-designer-marina-toybina|archive-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> and says the majority of costumes turn out identical to her sketches.<ref name=\"VF Costume\"/> \n\nToybina meets in person with each contestant to choose which costume they want to wear on the show.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> Due to time constraints, a maximum of two fittings are conducted with each celebrity at a \"very, very private hidden-away\" location<ref name=\"VAR Jan 10\"/> (either the costume shop or Toybina's personal studio)<ref name=\"VF Costume\"/> in which the costumes are tested with a vocal coach to be sure the celebrities can sing and hear clearly.<ref name=\"TVI Sep 24\">{{cite web|last=Halterman|first=Jim|title=''The Masked Singer'' Season 2 Disguises by the Numbers|url=https://www.tvinsider.com/810949/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes-preview/|website=TV Insider|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928183052/https://www.tvinsider.com/810949/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes-preview/|archive-date=September 28, 2019|date=September 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"VUL Sep 25\">{{cite web|last=McHenry|first=Jackson|title=''The Masked Singer''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Costume Designer Breaks Down All 16 Egg-cellent New Looks|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and destination sites|Vulture]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221030001/https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> During filming, the participants are assisted by a production crew that helps them take their costumes on and off. According to Ibarra, the costumes make it difficult for the contestants to get on and off the stage and their vision is limited when performing on it.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> As there are no backup costumes, each is sanitized and repaired if needed between episodes.<ref name=\"HP Costume\"/><ref name=\"TVI Sep 24\"/>\n\nFor their work on the first season's finale, Toybina and costume supervisor Grainne O'Sullivan received a [[Creative Arts Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming|Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming]].<ref name=\"Emmy 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2019/outstanding-costumes-for-a-variety-program-or-a-special|title=Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming Nominees/Winners 2019|website=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205042123/https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2019/outstanding-costumes-for-a-variety-program-or-a-special|archive-date=December 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the second season, Toybina won a [[Costume Designers Guild#Costume Designers Guild Awards|Costume Designers Guild Award]] in the Excellence in Variety, Reality-Competition, Live Television category in recognition of her work on the final episode.<ref name=\"CAG 2020\">{{cite web|title=22nd Costume Designers Guild Awards Winners & Nominees|url=https://costumedesignersguild.com/awards/awards-2019-2020/|website=[[Costume Designers Guild]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302071147/https://costumedesignersguild.com/awards/awards-2019-2020/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Series overview==\n{{Main|List of The Masked Singer (American TV series) episodes}}\n{{Series overview\n| auxA        = Celebrities\n| infoA       = Winner\n| infoB       = Runner-up\n| infoC       = Third place\n\n| color1      = #375D71\n| link1       = The Masked Singer (American season 1)\n| auxA1       = 12\n| episodes1   = 10\n| start1      = {{Start date|2019|1|2}}\n| end1        = {{End date|2019|2|27}}\n| infoA1      = [[T-Pain]]<br /><small>as \"Monster\"</small>\n| infoB1      = [[Donny Osmond]]<br /><small>as \"Peacock\"</small>\n| infoC1      = [[Gladys Knight]]<br /><small>as \"Bee\"</small>\n\n| color2      = #A8957F\n| link2       = The Masked Singer (American season 2)\n| auxA2       = 16\n| episodes2   = 13\n| start2      = {{Start date|2019|9|25}}\n| end2        = {{End date|2019|12|18}}\n| infoA2      = [[Wayne Brady]]<br /><small>as \"Fox\"</small>\n| infoB2      = [[Chris Daughtry]]<br /><small>as \"Rottweiler\"</small>\n| infoC2      = [[Adrienne Bailon]]<br /><small>as \"Flamingo\"</small>\n\n| color3      = #453842\n| link3       = The Masked Singer (American season 3)\n| auxA3       = 18\n| episodes3   = \n| start3      = {{Start date|2020|2|2}}\n| end3        = {{End date|2020|5|27}}<ref name=\"The Futon Critic\"/>\n| infoA3      = \n| infoB3      = \n| infoC3      = \n}}\n\n==Broadcast history and release==\nThe series is broadcast by Fox in the United States and has been [[simulcast]] by [[CTV Television Network|CTV]] in Canada since the second season. The show is available for streaming in the United States on Fox's website and [[Hulu]], and in Canada on CTV's website.<ref>{{cite press release|title= CTV Unveils 2019/20 Primetime Schedule, Featuring Dynamic Dramas with Big Stars and Big Stories|url=https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/ctv-unveils-2019-20-primetime-schedule-featuring-dynamic-dramas-with-big-stars-and-big-stories/|publisher=[[Bell Media]]|date=June 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607044629/https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/ctv-unveils-2019-20-primetime-schedule-featuring-dynamic-dramas-with-big-stars-and-big-stories/|archive-date=June 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Watch The Masked Singer|url=https://www.hulu.com/series/the-masked-singer-15209f88-6004-4d73-b993-3ff1a244f494|publisher=[[Hulu]]}}</ref> [[Fox Corporation]] distributes the series in the United States and Canada while Propagate Content does so elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web|last=Otterson|first=Joe|title=Fox Partners With Propagate Content to Distribute Unscripted Programming |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/fox-propagate-content-mipcom-1203372433/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=April 7, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017154840/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/fox-propagate-content-mipcom-1203372433/|archive-date=October 17, 2019|date=October 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Aside from double-length episodes, most run for about 43 minutes and carry a TV-PG or TV-14 [[TV Parental Guidelines|parental rating]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch ''The Masked Singer'': Season 3, Episode 8 \"Old Friends, New Clues: Group C Championships\" Online|url=https://www.fox.com/watch/c2f238d84b5863a804a5455cfc687c05/|website=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Viewership and ratings===\n<noinclude>\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:7%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Season\n! style=\"width:14%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Timeslot ([[Eastern Time Zone (North America)|ET]])\n! style=\"width:7%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Episodes\n! colspan=\"2\"| First aired\n! colspan=\"2\"| Last aired\n! style=\"width:7%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| TV season\n! style=\"width:28%;\" colspan=\"4\"| Averages\n|-\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:8%;\"| Viewers<br>(millions)\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:8%;\"| Viewers<br>(millions)\n! style=\"width:7%;| Viewership<br>rank\n! style=\"width:7%;| Viewers<br>(millions)\n! style=\"width:7%;| 18\u201349<br>rank\n! style=\"width:7%;| 18\u201349<br>rating\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|1]]\n| Wednesday 9:00&nbsp;p.m.\n| 10\n| January 2, 2019\n| 9.37<ref name=\"1.01\">{{cite web|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|url=https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-on-fox-scores-tvs-highest-rated-unscripted-series-launch-in-seven-years/|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' on Fox Scores TV's Highest-Rated Unscripted Series Launch in Seven Years|work=Programming Insider|date=January 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323022456/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-on-fox-scores-tvs-highest-rated-unscripted-series-launch-in-seven-years/|archive-date=March 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| February 27, 2019\n| 11.48<ref name=\"1.09/10\">{{cite web|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403155952/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-michael-cohen-hearing-draws-significant-audience-figures-in-daytime-across-various-networks/|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: Michael Cohen Hearing Draws Significant Audience Figures in Daytime Across Various Networks|work=Programming Insider|date=February 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403155952/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-michael-cohen-hearing-draws-significant-audience-figures-in-daytime-across-various-networks/|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| [[2018\u201319 United States network television schedule|2018\u201319]]\n| 16\n| 8.17\n| 5\n| 2.6<ref name=\"S1AvgRatings\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[The Masked Singer (American season 2)|2]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Wednesday 8:00&nbsp;p.m.\n| 13\n| September 25, 2019\n| 8.03<ref name=\"2.01\">{{cite web|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' Season Premiere Helps Fox to Dominate Prime Time as it Doubled the Runner-Up Network in Adults 18-49|url=https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-season-premiere-helps-fox-to-dominate-prime-time-as-it-doubled-the-runner-up-network-in-adults-18-49/|website=Programming Insider|date=September 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005182232/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-season-premiere-helps-fox-to-dominate-prime-time-as-it-doubled-the-runner-up-network-in-adults-18-49/|archive-date=October 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| December 18, 2019\n| 8.37<ref name=\"2.12/13\">{{cite web|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: Over 12 Million Watch Impeachment Vote Coverage Across Various Cable News Stations|url=https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-over-12-million-watch-impeachment-vote-coverage-across-various-cable-news-stations/|website=Programming Insider|date=December 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328034025/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-over-12-million-watch-impeachment-vote-coverage-across-various-cable-news-stations/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[2019\u201320 United States network television schedule|2019\u201320]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|TBD}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|TBD}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|TBD}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|TBD}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|3]]\n| {{n/a|TBA}}\n| February 2, 2020\n| 23.78<ref name=\"3.01\">{{cite web|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|url=https://programminginsider.com/sunday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-third-season-premiere-on-fox-generates-second-largest-total-audience-and-adults-18-49-delivery-for-a-super-bowl-lead-out-in-five-years/|title=Sunday Final Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' Third Season Premiere on Fox Generates Second-Largest Total Audience and Adults 18-49 Delivery for a Super Bowl Lead-Out in Five Years|work=Programming Insider|date=February 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211224755/https://programminginsider.com/sunday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-third-season-premiere-on-fox-generates-second-largest-total-audience-and-adults-18-49-delivery-for-a-super-bowl-lead-out-in-five-years/|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| May 27, 2020<ref name=\"The Futon Critic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/masked-singer/listings/|title=''The Masked Singer'' Episode Listings|website=[[The Futon Critic]]|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| {{n/a|TBA}}\n|-\n|}\n</noinclude>\n''The Masked Singer'' premiered in January 2019 as the highest rated [[reality television|unscripted]] television series debut since ''[[The X Factor (American TV series)|The X Factor]]'' in 2011. Following three days of DVR viewing, the first episode's 18\u201349 rating grew by 30 percent\u2014the highest increase ever for a premiere in the show's genre.<ref>{{cite web|last=Holloway|first=Daniel|title=''The Masked Singer'' Scores Biggest Live+3 Lift Ever for Unscripted Series|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/masked-singer-ratings-1203101918/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125164644/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/masked-singer-ratings-1203101918/|archive-date=December 22, 2019|date=January 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Although initially dropping, ratings grew towards the end of the season, and the finale became the most watched episode.<ref name=\"ADW Sep 25\">{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Jason|title=How Freshman Hit ''The Masked Singer'' Will Try to Avoid a Sophomore Slump|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/masked-singer-season-2-what-to-expect/|website=[[Adweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926021058/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/masked-singer-season-2-what-to-expect/|archive-date=September 26, 2019|date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> According to [[Comscore]], the show had one of the highest viewer engagement levels of any television series during the week the finale aired.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=TV's Stickiest Shows|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A606540478/GPS|magazine=[[Broadcasting & Cable]]|via=[[Gale (publisher)|Gale In Context: Biography]]|date=March 18, 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref> It concluded the [[2018\u201319 United States network television schedule|2018\u201319 television season]] as the highest rated new series among adults 18\u201349, averaging a 2.6 rating throughout all ten episodes,<ref name=\"S1AvgRatings\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/ratings-broadcast-network-series-2018-19-1213344|title=2018-19 TV Season Ratings: 90 Percent of Veteran Broadcast Shows Fall|last=Porter|first=Rick|date=May 23, 2019|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617113702/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/ratings-broadcast-network-series-2018-19-1213344|archive-date=June 17, 2019}}</ref> and as the highest rated entertainment series among teens, men 18\u201334, adults 18\u201334, and adults 18\u201349.<ref name=\"ADW Oct 20\">{{cite web|title=The 2019 TV Hot List: The Year's Biggest and Buzziest Shows, Networks and People|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/the-2019-tv-hot-list-the-years-biggest-and-buzziest-shows-networks-and-people/4/|website=[[Adweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230042701/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/the-2019-tv-hot-list-the-years-biggest-and-buzziest-shows-networks-and-people/4/|archive-date=December 30, 2019|date=October 20, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The show was the first unscripted series to rank number-one in the genre in its first season since ''[[Joe Millionaire]]'' in 2003,<ref name=\"VAR Feb 19\">{{cite news|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=Who Is That Masked B-Lister?|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48002572/the-gazette/|work=[[Montreal Gazette]]|agency=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404200853/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48002572/the-gazette/|archive-date=April 4, 2020|date=February 19, 2019|url-status=live|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> and was one of the reasons why Fox was the only network to gain viewers compared to the previous television season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Levin|first=Gary|title=Fox plots more 'toons, a ''9-1-1'' spinoff, the end of ''Empire'' and plenty of ''Masked Singer''|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/05/13/foxs-fall-schedule-adds-new-toon-wwe-wrestling-and-masked-singer/1184733001/|work=[[USA Today]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513172632/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/05/13/foxs-fall-schedule-adds-new-toon-wwe-wrestling-and-masked-singer/1184733001/|archive-date=April 10, 2020|date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[Ad Age]]'', the series was one of two non-[[National Football League|NFL]] programs to cost at least $200,000 per thirty seconds of advertising during the [[2019\u201320 United States network television schedule|2019\u201320 television season]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Adgate|first=Brad|title=TV Ad Rates (But Not Ad Revenue) Are Dropping|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bradadgate/2019/10/15/tv-ad-rates-but-not-ad-revenue-are-dropping/|website=[[Forbes]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408171217/https://www.forbes.com/sites/bradadgate/2019/10/15/tv-ad-rates-but-not-ad-revenue-are-dropping/|archive-date=April 8, 2020|date=October 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The second season premiered 17 percent lower than the previous, though it was mostly in line with the first season's average.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thorne|first=Will|title=TV Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' Easily Wins Wednesday|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/tv-ratings-the-masked-singer-season-2-premiere-1203350350/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927145835/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/tv-ratings-the-masked-singer-season-2-premiere-1203350350/|archive-date=September 27, 2019|date=September 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The finale's ratings also dropped compared to the first season, although the broadcast was up 20 percent in viewers from the previous week.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ramos|first=Dino-Ray|title=''The Masked Singer'' & ''Survivor'' Finales, ''Live In Front Of A Studio Audience'' Ratings Dip Amid Primetime Impeachment Vote|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/the-masked-singer-finale-ratings-survivor-winner-live-in-front-of-a-studio-audience-1202813754/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304071423/https://deadline.com/2019/12/the-masked-singer-finale-ratings-survivor-winner-live-in-front-of-a-studio-audience-1202813754/|archive-date=March 4, 2020|date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Deadline Hollywood]] cited the second season as a major reason why Fox\u2014for the first time in the network's history\u2014ranked number-one in fall entertainment programming,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|title=Fox Tops Fall Demo Ratings For First Time In Decade; NBC Snaps CBS' Total Viewers Streak|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/tv-ratings-fall-2019-fox-wins-nbc-the-masked-singer-sunday-night-football-1202817673/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104191044/https://deadline.com/2019/12/tv-ratings-fall-2019-fox-wins-nbc-the-masked-singer-sunday-night-football-1202817673/|archive-date=January 4, 2020|date=December 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and ''[[Adweek]]'' named the show the \"Hottest Reality/Competition Series\" of 2019.<ref name=\"ADW Oct 20\"/> The third season, which premiered as the [[Super Bowl LIV]] [[list of Super Bowl lead-out programs|lead-out program]], was viewed by over 23.7 million people. While the episode was watched by more than the previous lead-out, ''[[The World's Best]]'' (22.2 million), and Fox's most recent lead-out, 2017's ''[[24: Legacy]]'' (17.6 million), it was lower than the viewership of ''[[This Is Us]]'' (27 million) in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last=Adalian|first=Joseph|title=23 Million People Watched a Celebrity Pretend to Be a Robot on ''The Masked Singer''|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/the-masked-singer-super-bowl-ratings.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and destination sites|Vulture]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311162320/https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/the-masked-singer-super-bowl-ratings.html|archive-date=March 11, 2020|date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> During the latter half of the season which aired during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the series\u2014like others\u2014experienced viewership and 18\u201349 rating gains of 10\u201315 percent compared to the episodes that aired before the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thorne|first=Will|title=Network TV Sees a Ratings Revival Amid Coronavirus Outbreak, but Will It Last?|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/self-isolation-ratings-network-tv-1203545128/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411070014/https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/self-isolation-ratings-network-tv-1203545128/|archive-date=April 11, 2020|date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Porter|first=Rick|title=TV Long View: The Shows With the Biggest Quarantine Viewing Gains|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/60-minutes-blacklist-lead-quarantine-viewing-gains-1288507|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413011213/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/60-minutes-blacklist-lead-quarantine-viewing-gains-1288507|archive-date=April 13, 2020|date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Excluding the third season's premiere following the Super Bowl, the show's two-hour broadcast on April 1 was the most watched since the first season's finale.<ref name=\"VAR Mar 26\">{{cite web|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=''The Masked Singer'': Gordon Ramsay Is First Confirmed Guest for Fox's ''After The Mask'' Post-Show (Exclusive)|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/the-masked-singer-gordon-ramsay-after-the-mask-1234580325/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415220047/https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/the-masked-singer-gordon-ramsay-after-the-mask-1234580325/|archive-date=April 15, 2020|date=April 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe series' concept, panelists, and production have attracted mixed reviews from critics while its costumes have been universally praised.\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Kristen Baldwin felt the show was captivating but said the panelists were unfit to be critiquing singers and that they did not pay attention to the clues or performances.<ref>{{cite web|last=Baldwin|first=Kristen|title=Fox's ''The Masked Singer'': What the holy hell is this?|url=https://ew.com/tv-reviews/2019/01/02/the-masked-singer-fox-recap/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920204236/https://ew.com/tv-reviews/2019/01/02/the-masked-singer-fox-recap/|archive-date=April 20, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Likewise, Kelly Lawler of ''[[USA Today]]'' attributed the series' success to its brilliant concept only and named the judging panel the worst in reality television history. She described Jeong as over-the-top, McCarthy Wahlberg as inexperienced, Scherzinger as boring, and Thicke as too serious.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lawler|first=Kelly|title=The 5 best (and 5 worst) reality-TV show judging panels of all time|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/02/25/reality-tv-judges-5-best-and-5-worst-panels-all-time-the-voice-american-idol-simon-cowell-rupaul/2937947002/|website=[[USA Today]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401114701/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/02/25/reality-tv-judges-5-best-and-5-worst-panels-all-time-the-voice-american-idol-simon-cowell-rupaul/2937947002/|archive-date=April 1, 2020|date=February 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Similarly, ''Variety''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Caroline Framke]] felt the panelists gave worthless insights and that the show was boring due to the caliber of celebrities competing not living up to the hype the show promotes them as when they are unmasked.<ref>{{cite web|last=Framke|first=Caroline|author-link=Caroline Framke|title=TV Review: ''The Masked Singer''|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/reviews/the-masked-singer-review-fox-korea-1203096239/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406202742/https://variety.com/2018/tv/reviews/the-masked-singer-review-fox-korea-1203096239/|archive-date=April 6, 2019|date=December 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Matt Zoller Seitz]] of ''Vulture'' lambasted the presence of McCarthy Wahlberg as a panelist (referring to her [[Jenny McCarthy#Autism activism and views on vaccines|prominent]] [[vaccine hesitancy|anti-vaccine]] views) but praised her chemistry with the rest of the panel. He criticized the way the show's producers edit their guesses, stating they should cut out repetitive comments more often.<ref>{{cite web|last=Seitz|first=Matt Zoller|author-link=Matt Zoller Seitz|title=How Is The Masked Singer Real?|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-review.html|website=Vulture|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218162823/https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-review.html|archive-date=December 18, 2019|date=September 26, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Others from ''Vulture'' also derided the editing as awkward but were impressed by the costumes, describing the Egg as timeless, the Butterfly as gorgeous, and the Rottweiler as a badass. However, they felt the panelists were mindless and unfunny, condemning them for spoiling the show's innovative concept with distracting statements.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wright|first=Megh|title=Egg Was Too Pure for This Terrible World|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/goodbye-egg.html|website=Vulture|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926201418/https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/goodbye-egg.html|archive-date=September 26, 2019|date=September 26, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=VanArendonk|first=Kathryn|title=''The Masked Singer'' Is a Reality-TV Fever Dream|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/the-masked-singer-fox-review.html|website=Vulture|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225230817/https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/the-masked-singer-fox-review.html|archive-date=December 25, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> After attended a taping of the show, Kayla Keegan of ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'' said she also appreciated the detailing of the costumes and praised Toybina's skill in designing them.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/>\n\nMalcolm Venable of ''[[TV Guide]]'' thought the costumes were fantastic but described the performers' singing abilities as lackluster and the panelists' guesses as absurd.<ref>{{cite web|last=Venable|first=Malcolm|title=Is ''The Masked Singer'' Terrible, or Am I Just Old and Cranky?|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/the-masked-singer-review/|website=[[TV Guide]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914015641/https://www.tvguide.com/news/the-masked-singer-review/|archive-date=September 14, 2019|date=December 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Megan Garber of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' compared the series' format to that of [[Police procedural|crime procedural]] ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation|CSI]]'' due to its mystery elements while [[CNN]]'s Brian Lowry felt the show's [[novelty]] would soon fade away because it is gimmicky.<ref name=\"ATL Feb 28\">{{cite web|last=Garber|first=Megan|title=''The Masked Singer'' Lets You In on the Scam|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/02/masked-singer-finale-what-show-really-reveals/583882/|website=[[The Atlantic]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308121421/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/02/masked-singer-finale-what-show-really-reveals/583882/|archive-date=March 8, 2020|date=February 28, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lowry|first=Brian|title=''Titan Games'', ''Masked Singer'' launch hunt for next reality hit|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/31/entertainment/titan-games-masked-singer-reality-tv/index.html|website=[[CNN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111064738/https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/31/entertainment/titan-games-masked-singer-reality-tv/index.html|archive-date=January 11, 2019|date=December 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>. Writing for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', Emily Yahr described the show as crazy but said Cannon was perfect as host, noting his years of experience in the same role on ''[[America's Got Talent]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Yahr|first=Emily|title=Yes, that was real life: ''The Masked Singer'' premiered and was even weirder than you imagined|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/the-masked-singer-fox-review.html|website=Vulture|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225230817/https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/the-masked-singer-fox-review.html|archive-date=December 25, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Conversely, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[John Doyle (critic)|John Doyle]] called Cannon inarticulate and described the panelists as [[Camp (style)|cheesy]] and irrelevant. He characterized the show as a wacky and dumb version of [[Charades]] but acknowledged that it is popular because of its simplicity. Doyle cited the series as an example of a cultural shift in the United States away from the competitive and often exploitative nature of shows such as ''[[American Idol]]'' towards a higher level of positivity among reality television series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Doyle|first=John|author-link=John Doyle (critic)|title=Dumb simplicity: Why The Masked Singer is a massive TV hit|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/article-dumb-simplicity-why-the-masked-singer-is-a-massive-tv-hit/|website=[[The Globe and Mail]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218163655/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/article-dumb-simplicity-why-the-masked-singer-is-a-massive-tv-hit/|archive-date=December 18, 2019|date=November 4, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Likewise, Daniel D'Addario of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described the show as relaxing and refreshing, calling it a return to form for television as the series possesses the now-rare ability to uplift and unite people. He commended the show's panelists, comparing them to the original ''American Idol'' judges as non-experts in their fields due to their common, implausible [[A-list]] celebrity guesses. He also praised the show's platform for allowing celebrities to express themselves freely even if they are not professional singers.<ref>{{cite web|last=D'Addario|first=Daniel|title=In Praise of ''The Masked Singer'', TV's Last Uniter (Column)|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/columns/masked-singer-super-bowl-1203485315/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210183913/https://variety.com/2020/tv/columns/masked-singer-super-bowl-1203485315/|archive-date=February 10, 2020|date=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Cultural impact===\nThe series is discussed on numerous [[podcast|podcasts]] and has generated its own [[Reddit#Subreddit|thread]] on [[Reddit]].<ref name=\"ATL Feb 28\"/> Fans of the show take part in guessing on [[Twitter]] each time an episode airs.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> It was the first in the [[Masked Singer|''Masked Singer'' franchise]] to air outside of Asia and its success has been attributed to subsequent local adaptations. The producers of the [[The Masked Singer (British TV series)|British series]] said they were inspired to adapt the format after watching the American version.<ref name=\"THR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> Rob Wade, the President of Fox Alternative Entertainment, has described a shift in the way new shows are [[sales presentation|pitched]] since the series premiered, noting there is an increased openness to new ideas. Wade also said the heads of almost all television networks thanked him for the series giving them a \"[[blank cheque|carte blanche]]\" to take new programming risks.<ref name=\"VAR Feb 19\"/> \n\nMichael Schneider of ''Variety'' said the show's success has revitalized reality television in the United States. The revivals of ''[[Paradise Hotel]]'' and ''[[Temptation Island (TV series)|Temptation Island]]'' by Fox and [[USA Network]], respectively, have been credited to the show's success, as have the American adaptations of ''[[Love Island (American TV series)|Love Island]]'' and ''[[I Can See Your Voice (American game show)|I Can See Your Voice]]''.<ref name=\"VAR Feb 19\"/> The show has also been credited with reinvigorating the costume genre of television. Interest in adapting other costume-centered series such as ''[[Wild Things (game show)|Wild Things]]'' and ''[[Sexy Beasts]]'' has increased around the world since the show premiered.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\"/>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:11%;\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2%;\"| Year{{efn|Indicates the year of the ceremony.}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%;\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30%;\"| Nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4%;\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2%;\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Costume Designers Guild#Costume Designers Guild Awards|Costume Designers Guild Awards]]\n| [[Costume Designers Guild Awards 2019|2020]]\n| Excellence in Variety, Reality-Competition, Live Television\n| Marina Toybina (for \"Season Finale: And The Winner Takes It All and Takes It Off\")\n| {{won}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"CAG 2020\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Creative Arts Emmy Award|Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]\n| [[71st Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|2019]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming|Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming]]\n| Marina Toybina, Grainne O'Sullivan (for \"Season Finale: The Final Mask is Lifted\")\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"Emmy 2019\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Critics' Choice Real TV Awards]]\n| [[1st Critics' Choice Real TV Awards|2019]]\n| Competition Series: Talent/Variety\n| ''The Masked Singer''\n| {{won}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|last=Montgomery|first=Daniel|title=Winners of the Inaugural Critics' Choice Real TV Awards|url=http://www.criticschoice.com/critics-choice-real-tv-awards/|publisher=[[Broadcast Film Critics Association]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918170057/http://www.criticschoice.com/critics-choice-real-tv-awards/|archive-date=September 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Gold Derby]] TV Awards\n| 2019\n| Competition Program\n| ''The Masked Singer''\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|last1=Montgomery|first1=Daniel|last2=Dixon|first2=Marcus James|last3=Beachum|first3=Chris|last4=Eng|first4=Joyce|last5=Sheehan|first5=Paul|last6=Wloszczyna|first6=Susan|title=Gold Derby TV Awards winners 2019: ''Game of Thrones'' and ''Fleabag'' rule, but voters spread the wealth|url=https://www.goldderby.com/article/2019/gold-derby-tv-awards-winners-2019-game-of-thrones-fleabag-news/|website=[[Gold Derby]]|date=September 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406001043/https://www.goldderby.com/article/2019/gold-derby-tv-awards-winners-2019-game-of-thrones-fleabag-news/|archive-date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards|Kids' Choice Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[2020 Kids' Choice Awards|TBA]]\n| Favorite Reality Show\n| ''The Masked Singer''\n| {{pending}}\n| style=text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/avengers-end-game-leads-nickelodeons-kids-choice-awards-nominations-billie-eilish-taylor-swift-chance-the-rapper-full-list-1202859259/|title=''Avengers: Endgame'' Leads Nickelodeon's Kids' Choice Awards Nominations; Chance The Rapper Set As Host|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Denise Petski|date=February 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313113934/https://deadline.com/2020/02/avengers-end-game-leads-nickelodeons-kids-choic