{"title_page": "List of Spanish flu cases", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nThe '''January 1918 \u2013 December 1920 flu pandemic''' is commonly referred to as the [[Spanish flu]].\n\nTo maintain morale, [[World War I|wartime]] censors minimized early reports of illness and mortality in Germany, the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]], the [[French Third Republic]], and the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web| last = Valentine| first = Vikki| title = Origins of the 1918 Pandemic: The Case for France| url = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5222069| publisher = [[NPR]]| access-date= 2 October 2011| date = 20 February 2006| ref = harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Anderson|first=Susan|title=Analysis of Spanish flu cases in 1918\u20131920 suggests transfusions might help in bird flu pandemic|url=http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2006-08/acop-aos082806.php|publisher=[[American College of Physicians]]|access-date=2 October 2011|date=29 August 2006}}</ref> Papers were free to report the epidemic's effects in neutral [[Restoration (Spain)|Restoration-era Spain]] (such as the grave illness of [[King Alfonso XIII]]).<ref>{{cite encyclopedia| editor1-first = Maria| editor1-last = Porras-Gallo| editor2-first = Ryan A.| editor2-last = Davis | name-list-format = vanc| title = The Spanish Influenza Pandemic of 1918\u20131919: Perspectives from the Iberian Peninsula and the Americas| publisher = University of Rochester Press| date = 2014| isbn = 978-1-58046-496-3| volume = 30| encyclopedia = Rochester Studies in Medical History| url = https://books.google.com/?id=-j53BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA51&dq=spanish+flu+davis#v=onepage&q&f=false| ref = harv}}</ref> This created a false impression of Spain as especially hard hit,<ref name=Barry_book>{{cite book| last = Barry| first = John M.| name-list-format = vanc| authorlink = John M. Barry| title = The Great Influenza: The Epic Story of the Greatest Plague in History| publisher = Viking Penguin| date = 2004| isbn = 978-0-670-89473-4| ref = harv| url = https://archive.org/details/greatinfluenzaep00john}}</ref> thereby giving rise to the pandemic's nickname, \"Spanish Flu\".<ref>{{cite web| last = Galvin| first = John | name-list-format = vanc| title = Spanish Flu Pandemic: 1918| url = http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/environment/natural-disasters/4219884| publisher = [[Popular Mechanics]]| access-date=2 October 2011| date = 31 July 2007| ref = harv}}</ref>\n\n==Fatalities==\n<!-- REAL PEOPLE ONLY --><!-- TWILIGHT FANS PLEASE NOTE -->\nListed alphabetically by surname\n* [[Johnny Aitken]], American auto racer, led first lap of the [[1911 Indianapolis 500|first Indianapolis 500]] (October 15, 1918)<ref>[https://indyracingmuseum.org/fame_inductee/johnny-aitken/ Aitken - Hall of Fame Inductees] Indianapolis Motor Speedway Museum</ref><ref>[https://www.racing-reference.info/showblog?id=3628 Historical Motorsports Stories: Johnny Aitken: Indy 500 Pioneer - Pandemic Victim] Racing-Reference</ref>\n* [[Turki I bin Abdulaziz Al Saud]], eldest son of [[Ibn Saud of Saudi Arabia]] (1919)<ref>{{cite web|last=Henderson|first=Simon|title=After King Fahd|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/uploads/Documents/pubs/PP_37_AFTERKINGFAHD.pdf|publisher=Washington Institute|accessdate=20 March 2020|format=Policy Paper|year=1994}} (Page 16)</ref>\n* [[Francisco de Paula Rodrigues Alves]], Brazilian re-elected president, died before taking office (January 16, 1919)<ref>{{Cite book | year=2004 | title=Soldiers of the P\u00e1tria: a history of the Brazilian Army, 1889\u20131937 | author=Frank D. McCann | publisher=Stanford University Press | isbn=978-0-8047-3222-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xDep7jGaHPwC&pg=RA2-PA191&dq=Francisco+influenza| author-link=Frank D. McCann }}</ref>\n* [[Robert Anderson (Scotland Yard official)|Robert Anderson]], Scotland Yard official (November 15, 1918)<ref>[https://www.casebook.org/press_reports/times/19181118.html Times (London) - 18 November 1918 - DEATH OF SIR ROBERT ANDERSON.] Casebook: Jack the Ripper</ref>\n* [[Guillaume Apollinaire]], French poet (November 9, 1918)<ref>[https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/guillaume-apollinaire Poets: Guillaume Apollinaire] Poetry Foundation</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=John Baxter|title=Carnal Knowledge: Baxter's Concise Encyclopedia of Modern Sex|url=https://archive.org/details/carnalknowledgeb00baxt|url-access=registration|accessdate=24 December 2011|date=10 February 2009|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-06-087434-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/carnalknowledgeb00baxt/page/13 13]}}</ref>\n* [[Felix Arndt]], American pianist (October 16, 1918)<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/item/n82063875/felix-arndt/ Felix Arndt] Library of Congress</ref><ref>[http://www.unconservatory.org/celam/arndtbio.html Bio: Felix Arndt] The Unconservatory</ref>\n* [[Dudley John Beaumont]], husband of the Dame of Sark (November 24, 1918)<ref name=hathway59>{{cite book |last=Hathaway |first=Sibyl |authorlink=Sibyl Hathaway |title=Dame of Sark: An Autobiography|edition=2nd|year=1962 |publisher=Coward-McCann, Inc. |location=[[New York City|New York]] |isbn= | url=https://archive.org/details/dameofsark006367mbp|page=59}}</ref>\n* [[Louis Botha]], first Prime Minister of the [[Union of South Africa]] (August 27, 1919)<ref>{{Harvnb|Duncan|2003|p=16}}{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Randolph Bourne]], American progressive writer and public intellectual, (December 22, 1918)<ref name=\"dMAC Health Digest\">[http://www.dmacdigest.com/flu1918.html dMAC Health Digest].</ref>\n* [[Ivan Cankar]], Slovenian Writer, (December 11, 1918)<ref>Historical Dictionary of Slovenia (Third edition - 2018) by Leopoldina Plut-Pregelj, Gregor Kranjc, \u017darko Lazarevi\u0107, Carole Rogel - Page 67</ref>\n* [[Bernard Capes]], British novelist (2 November 1918) <ref> Lamb, Hugh. \"Introduction\", to Capes, Bernard. ''The Black Reaper''. Ashcroft, B.C. : [[Ash-Tree Press]] 1998. {{ISBN|9781899562527}},  pg. xvii. </ref> \n* [[Amadeo de Souza Cardoso]], Portuguese painter (25 October 1918)\n* [[Kate Carmack]], founder of the [[Klondike Gold Rush]] (March 29, 1920)<ref>[https://postalmuseum.si.edu/exhibitions/as-precious-as-gold-stories-from-the-gold-rush-extraordinary-women/kate-carmack-shaaw Kate Carmack - Shaaw Tlaa] National Postal Museum</ref><ref>[http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/shaaw_tlaa_14E.html Biography - SHAAW TL\u00c1A - Volume XIV (1911-1920)] Dictionary of Canadian Biography</ref>\n* [[Larry Chappell]], American baseball player, (November 8, 1918)<ref name=\"baseballhall\">[https://baseballhall.org/discover/1918-flu-pandemic-didnt-spare-baseball 1918 FLU PANDEMIC DID NOT SPARE BASEBALL] National Baseball Hall of Fame</ref><ref>Early Exits: The Premature Endings of Baseball Careers By Brian McKenna (Page 85)</ref>\n*[[John H. Collins]], director, writer, and husband of actress [[Viola Dana]]\n* [[Rose Cleveland]], First Lady of the United States of America, sister of President [[Grover Cleveland]] (November 22, 1918)<ref>[https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/new-book-chronicles-first-lady-rose-clevelands-love-affair-evangeline-simpson-whipple-180972472/ New Book Chronicles First Lady Rose Cleveland\u2019s Love Affair With Evangeline Simpson Whipple] Smithsonian Magazine</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=vf2nAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT89&lpg=PT89&dq=rose+cleveland+influenza&source=bl&ots=eOs58V5iMW&sig=ACfU3U0bBwtPM40jZVpjyNlPcG1VPKL7XA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiT4PrKvKzoAhVJa80KHZu-CMMQ6AEwBXoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=rose%20cleveland%20influenza&f=false Rose Elizabeth Cleveland: First Lady and Literary Scholar by Sirpa Salenius]</ref>\n* [[Carrie Cornplanter]], Native American artist and descendant of diplomat [[Cornplanter]] (late 1918)<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Liberty |editor1-first=Margot |title=American Indian Intellectuals of the Nineteenth and Early Twentieth Centuries |date=July 15, 2002 |location= |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |ed