aca]], American engineer, inventor of the Ginaca machine (October 19, 1918)\n* [[Harry Glenn]], American baseball player<ref>{{cite web|title=Harry Glenn|publisher=Baseball's Greatest Sacrifice|url=http://www.baseballsgreatestsacrifice.com/biographies/glenn_harry.html}}</ref><ref name=\"baseballhall\"/><ref>Early Exits: The Premature Endings of Baseball Careers By Brian McKenna (Page 85)</ref>\n* [[Myrtle Gonzalez]], American film actress (October 22, 1918)<ref name=\"dMAC Health Digest\"/>\n* [[Edward Kidder Graham]], President of the University of North Carolina (October 26, 1918)\n* [[Charles Griffes]], American Composer, (April 8, 1920)\n* [[Wilhelm Gross]], Austrian mathematician (October 22, 1918)\n* [[Joe Hall]], [[Montreal Canadiens]] [[ice hockey defenceman]], member of the Hockey Hall of Fame (April 6, 1919)\n* [[Alfred Hindmarsh]], New Zealand Labour Party leader, lawyer and politician.\n* [[Phoebe Hearst]], mother of William Randolph Hearst, (April 13, 1919)\n* [[Shelley Hull]], American stage actor, (January 14, 1919)\n* [[Margit Kaffka]], Hungarian writer and poet, (December 1, 1918)\n* [[Joseph Kaufman]], American actor and film director, (February 1, 1918)\n* [[Lyman W.V. Kennon]], American brigadier general (September 9, 1918)\n* [[Vera Kholodnaya]], Russian actress (February 16, 1919)\n* [[Gustav Klimt]], Austrian Artist, (February 6, 1918)\n* [[Bohumil Kubi\u0161ta]], Czech painter, (November 27, 1918)\n* [[Gilda Langer]], German actress, (January 31, 1920)\n* [[Hans E. Lau]], Danish astronomer, (October 16, 1918)<ref name=\"dMAC Health Digest\"/>\n* [[Julian L'Estrange]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shakespeare.emory.edu/actordisplay.cfm?actorid%3D34 |title=Julian L'Estrange |website=Shakespeare & the Players |accessdate=2016-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424152806/http://shakespeare.emory.edu/actordisplay.cfm?actorid=34 |archivedate=2016-04-24 }}</ref> English stage and screen actor (October 22, 1918)\n* [[Ruby Lindsay]], Australian illustrator and painter, (March 12, 1919)\n* [[Harold Lockwood]], American silent film star, (October 19, 1918)<ref name=\"PBS. Influenza 1918. Victims\"/>\n* [[Rosalia Lombardo]], Italian daughter of General Lombardo (December 6, 1920)\n* [[Francisco Marto]], Portuguese F\u00e1tima child (April 4, 1919)\n* [[Jacinta Marto]], Portuguese F\u00e1tima child (February 20, 1920)\n* [[Alan Arnett McLeod]], Canadian soldier and Victoria Cross recipient, (6 November 1918)\n* [[Dan McMichael]], manager of Scottish association football club Hibernian (1919)\n* [[Robert and L\u00e9on Morane|L\u00e9on Morane]], French aircraft company founder and pre-World War I aviator (October 20, 1918)\n* [[William Francis Murray]], postmaster of Boston and former U.S. Representative (September 21, 1918)\n* [[Silk O'Loughlin]], American baseball umpire<ref name=\"baseballhall\"/>\n* [[William Osler]], Canadian physician, co founder of Johns Hopkins Hospital, (December 29, 1919)\n* [[\u014cyama Sutematsu]], first Japanese woman to receive a college degree (February, 1919)\n* [[Hubert Parry]], British composer, (October 7, 1918)\n* [[Niko Pirosmani]], Georgian na\u00efve painter (April 9, 1918)\n* [[Henry Ragas]], American pianist of the Original Dixieland Jass Band, (February 18, 1919)\n* [[Stephen Reynolds (writer)|Stephen Sydney Reynolds]], English writer, (February 14, 1919)\n* [[William Leefe Robinson]], British Victoria Cross recipient, (December 31, 1918)\n* [[Edmond Rostand]], French dramatist, best known for his play Cyrano de Bergerac, (December 2, 1918)\n* [[Morton Schamberg]], American modernist artist in 1918.\n* [[Egon Schiele]], Austrian painter (October 31, 1918, [[Vienna]])<ref name=\"whitford\">Frank Whitford, Expressionist Portraits, Abbeville Press, 1987, p. 46. {{ISBN|0-89659-780-6}}</ref>\n* [[Reggie Schwarz]], South African cricketer and rugby player (November 18, 1918)<ref name=\"dMAC Health Digest\"/>\n* [[Hamby Shore]], Canadian ice hockey player (October 13, 1918)\n* [[Robert W. Speer]], mayor of Denver (May 14, 1918)\n* [[Walter Stradling]], English born cinematographer (July 1918)\n* [[Willard Dickerman Straight]], American investment banker, publisher, reporter, Army Reserve officer and diplomat (December 1, 1918)\n* [[Yakov Sverdlov]], Bolshevik party leader and official of the Russian Republic established by the February 1917 Revolution (March 16, 1919)\n* [[Mark Sykes]], British politician and diplomat, body exhumed 2008 for scientific research (February 16, 1919)\n* [[Dark Cloud (actor)]], aka Elijah Tahamont, American Indian actor, in Los Angeles (1918)\n* [[\u02bbAnaseini Takip\u014d]], Queen Dowager of Tonga (November 26, 1918) <ref>{{cite book |last=Eustis |first=Nelson |title=The King of Tonga: A Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S151AAAAMAAJ|year=1997|publisher=Hobby Investment |location=Adelaide |isbn=978-0-646-33077-8 |oclc=38837175 |page=64}}</ref>\n* [[Frederick Trump]], grandfather of 45th President [[Donald Trump]].<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2020/03/07/flu-trump-grandfather-death-coronavirus/\n</ref>\n* [[Prince Umberto, Count of Salemi]], member of the Italian royal family, (October 19, 1918)\n* [[Prince Erik, Duke of V\u00e4stmanland]] (Erik Gustav Ludvig Albert Bernadotte), Prince of Sweden (September 20, 1918)\n* [[King Watzke]], American violinist and bandleader, (1920)<ref name=\"dMAC Health Digest\"/>\n* [[Max Weber]], German Political Sociologist and Economist, (June 14, 1920)\n* [[Pearl Webster|Pearl F. \"Specks\" Webster]], American baseball player (September 16, 1918)<ref>[https://brooklyneagle.com/articles/2014/02/17/remembering-the-royals-the-pride-of-brooklyns-african-american-baseball-community/ Remembering the Royals: The pride of Brooklyn\u2019s African-American baseball community] Brooklyn Daily Eagle</ref><ref>[http://www.baseballsgreatestsacrifice.com/biographies/webster_specks.html Specks Webster] Baseball's Greatest Sacrifice</ref>\n* [[Bill Yawkey]], Major League Baseball executive and owner of the Detroit Tigers, in Augusta, Georgia, US (March 5, 1919)\n* [[Ella Flagg Young]], American educator (October 26, 1918)\n\n==In utero effects==\nChildren of women who were pregnant during the pandemic ran the risk of lifelong effects. One in three of the more than 25 million who contracted the flu in the United States was a woman of childbearing age. A study of US census data from 1960 to 1980 found that the children born to this group of women had more physical ailments and a lower lifetime income than those born a few months earlier or later.<ref>{{cite book\n|title=Superfreakonomics: global cooling, patriotic prostitutes, and why suicide bombers should buy life insurance\n|author1=Steven D. Levitt\n|author2=Stephen J. Dubner\n|publisher=William Morrow\n|year=2009\n|isbn=978-0-06-088957-9\n|pages=[https://archive.org/details/superfreakonomic00levi/page/59 59, 230]\n|url=https://archive.org/details/superfreakonomic00levi/page/59\n}} citing \"Is the 1918 Influenza Pandemic Over? Long-Term Effects of In Utero Influenza Exposure in the Post-1940 U.S Population,\" ''Journal of Political Economy'' 114 no. 4 (2006); and Douglas Almond and Bhashkar Mazumder, \"The 1918 Influenza Pandemic and Subsequent Health Outcomes: An Analysis of SIPP Data,\" ''Recent Developments in Health Economics'' 95 no. 2 (May 2005)</ref> The study also found that persons born in states with more severe exposure to the pandemic experienced worse outcomes than persons born in states with less severe exposures.<ref>{{cite book\n|title=Innovation in Global Health Governance: Critical Cases\n|work=Global environmental governance series\n|author1=Andrew Fenton Cooper\n|author2=John J. Kirton\n|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.\n|year=2009\n|isbn=978-0-7546-4872-7\n|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=kZRaDr1VzR4C&pg=PA139 139]}}</ref>\n\n==Notable survivors==<!-- REAL PEOPLE ONLY -->\n* [[Alexandrine of Mecklenburg-Schwerin]] (1879\u20131952), Queen of Denmark<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Alfonso XIII of Spain]] (1886\u20131941), King of Spain<ref name=Barry_book/>\n* [[Walter Benjamin]] (1892\u20131940) [[German-Jewish]] philosopher and [[Marxist]] literary critic<ref name=\"Scholem, Gershom\">Sholem, Gershom. ''Walter Benjamin: The Story of a Friendship.'' Trans. The Jewish Publication Society of America. London: Faber & Faber, 1982. 76.</ref>\n* [[Raymond Chandler]] (1888\u20131959), American novelist and screenwriter<ref>[http://www.thekeptgirl.com/2017/07/the-clews-from-raymond-chandlers-war.html The clews from Raymond Chandler\u2019s war], By Kim Cooper, July 23, 2017, Kim Cooper's \"The Kept Girl\"</ref> \n* [[Walt Disney]] (1901\u20131966), cartoonist<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Peter Fraser (New Zealand politician)|Peter Fraser]] (1884\u20131950), New Zealand prime minister<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Lillian Gish]] (1893\u20131993), American early motion picture actress<ref>[[Lillian Gish]]: The Movies, Mr. Griffith, and Me, {{ISBN|0-13-536649-6}}.</ref>\n* [[Haile Selassie I]] (1892\u20131975), Emperor of [[Ethiopia]]<ref name=Marcus>Harold Marcus, ''Haile Sellassie I: The formative years, 1892\u20131936'' (Trenton: Red Sea Press, 1996), pp. 36f; Pankhurst 1990, p. 48f.</ref>\n* [[Joseph Joffre]] (1852\u20131931), French [[World War I]] general, [[First Battle of the Marne|victor of the Marne]]<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Jim Jordan (actor)|Jim Jordan]] (1896\u20131988), American actor best known as [[Fibber McGee]]<ref name=\"Radio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.niu.edu/1993/ihy930345.html|title=Jim and Marian Jordan's Contributions to Radio|publisher=www.lib.niu.edu|accessdate=January 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810024133/http://www.lib.niu.edu/1993/ihy930345.html|archive-date=August 10, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[David Lloyd George]] (1863\u20131945), British prime minister<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Franz Kafka]] (1883\u20131924), [[German language|German-speaking]] [[Jewish]] author<ref>[http://jewishnews.at/jewish-news-from-austria-21/the-impossibility-of-being-kafka.html The Impossibility of Being Kafka], December 24, 2008, Jewish News From Austria</ref>\n* [[Prince Maximilian of Baden]] (1867\u20131929), [[Chancellor of Germany (German Reich)|Chancellor of Germany]] during the [[Armistice with Germany (Compi\u00e8gne)|armistice]]<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Edvard Munch]] (1863\u20131944), [[Norwegian people|Norwegian]] painter<ref>Munch Museum, \"A timeline of Munch's life\".[http://www.munch.museum.no/content.aspx?id=14 Munch Museum] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5h5mFXCHn?url=http://www.munch.museum.no/content.aspx?id=14 |date=2009-05-27 }}. Accessed 2009-05-24. [https://www.webcitation.org/5h5mFXCHn?url=http://www.munch.museum.no/content.aspx?id=14 Archived] 2009-05-27.</ref>\n* [[Georgia O'Keeffe]] (1887\u20131986), American [[modernism|modernist]] painter<ref>[[Roxana Robinson]], Georgia O'Keeffe: A Life. University Press of New England, 1989. p. 193. {{ISBN|0-87451-906-3}}</ref>\n* [[John J. Pershing]] (1860\u20131948), American general<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Mary Pickford]] (1892\u20131979), American film actress<ref name=\"Collier\">Collier 1974{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Katherine Anne Porter]] (1890\u20131980), Pulitzer Prize-winning American writer<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] (1882\u20131945), American president<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Le\u00f3 Szil\u00e1rd]] (1898\u20131964), [[nuclear physics|nuclear physicist]], discoverer of the [[nuclear chain reaction]]<ref>[[Richard Rhodes]], The Making of the Atomic Bomb, {{ISBN|0-684-81378-5}}.</ref>\n* [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor]] (1859\u20131941)<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Woodrow Wilson]] (1856\u20131924), American president<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1918 flu pandemic}}\n[[Category:Lists of people by medical condition|Spanish flu]]\n[[Category:Spanish flu]]\n[[Category:Death-related lists]]\n[[Category:1910s-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nThe '''January 1918 \u2013 December 1920 flu pandemic''' is commonly referred to as the [[Spanish flu]].\n\nTo maintain morale, [[World War I|wartime]] censors minimized early reports of illness and mortality in Germany, the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]], the [[French Third Republic]], and the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web| last = Valentine| first = Vikki| title = Origins of the 1918 Pandemic: The Case for France| url = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5222069| publisher = [[NPR]]| access-date= 2 October 2011| date = 20 February 2006| ref = harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Anderson|first=Susan|title=Analysis of Spanish flu cases in 1918\u20131920 suggests transfusions might help in bird flu pandemic|url=http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2006-08/acop-aos082806.php|publisher=[[American College of Physicians]]|access-date=2 October 2011|date=29 August 2006}}</ref> Papers were free to report the epidemic's effects in neutral [[Restoration (Spain)|Restoration-era Spain]] (such as the grave illness of [[King Alfonso XIII]]).<ref>{{cite encyclopedia| editor1-first = Maria| editor1-last = Porras-Gallo| editor2-first = Ryan A.| editor2-last = Davis | name-list-format = vanc| title = The Spanish Influenza Pandemic of 1918\u20131919: Perspectives from the Iberian Peninsula and the Americas| publisher = University of Rochester Press| date = 2014| isbn = 978-1-58046-496-3| volume = 30| encyclopedia = Rochester Studies in Medical History| url = https://books.google.com/?id=-j53BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA51&dq=spanish+flu+davis#v=onepage&q&f=false| ref = harv}}</ref> This created a false impression of Spain as especially hard hit,<ref name=Barry_book>{{cite book| last = Barry| first = John M.| name-list-format = vanc| authorlink = John M. Barry| title = The Great Influenza: The Epic Story of the Greatest Plague in History| publisher = Viking Penguin| date = 2004| isbn = 978-0-670-89473-4| ref = harv| url = https://archive.org/details/greatinfluenzaep00john}}</ref> thereby giving rise to the pandemic's nickname, \"Spanish Flu\".<ref>{{cite web| last = Galvin| first = John | name-list-format = vanc| title = Spanish Flu Pandemic: 1918| url = http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/environment/natural-disasters/4219884| publisher = [[Popular Mechanics]]| access-date=2 October 2011| date = 31 July 2007| ref = harv}}</ref>\n\n==Fatalities==\n<!-- REAL PEOPLE ONLY --><!-- TWILIGHT FANS PLEASE NOTE -->\nListed alphabetically by surname\n* [[Johnny Aitken]], American auto racer, led first lap of the [[1911 Indianapolis 500|first Indianapolis 500]] (October 15, 1918)<ref>[https://indyracingmuseum.org/fame_inductee/johnny-aitken/ Aitken - Hall of Fame Inductees] Indianapolis Motor Speedway Museum</ref><ref>[https://www.racing-reference.info/showblog?id=3628 Historical Motorsports Stories: Johnny Aitken: Indy 500 Pioneer - Pandemic Victim] Racing-Reference</ref>\n* [[Turki I bin Abdulaziz Al Saud]], eldest son of [[Ibn Saud of Saudi Arabia]] (1919)<ref>{{cite web|last=Henderson|first=Simon|title=After King Fahd|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/uploads/Documents/pubs/PP_37_AFTERKINGFAHD.pdf|publisher=Washington Institute|accessdate=20 March 2020|format=Policy Paper|year=1994}} (Page 16)</ref>\n* [[Francisco de Paula Rodrigues Alves]], Brazilian re-elected president, died before taking office (January 16, 1919)<ref>{{Cite book | year=2004 | title=Soldiers of the P\u00e1tria: a history of the Brazilian Army, 1889\u20131937 | author=Frank D. McCann | publisher=Stanford University Press | isbn=978-0-8047-3222-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xDep7jGaHPwC&pg=RA2-PA191&dq=Francisco+influenza| author-link=Frank D. McCann }}</ref>\n* [[Robert Anderson (Scotland Yard official)|Robert Anderson]], Scotland Yard official (November 15, 1918)<ref>[https://www.casebook.org/press_reports/times/19181118.html Times (London) - 18 November 1918 - DEATH OF SIR ROBERT ANDERSON.] Casebook: Jack the Ripper</ref>\n* [[Guillaume Apollinaire]], French poet (November 9, 1918)<ref>[https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/guillaume-apollinaire Poets: Guillaume Apollinaire] Poetry Foundation</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=John Baxter|title=Carnal Knowledge: Baxter's Concise Encyclopedia of Modern Sex|url=https://archive.org/details/carnalknowledgeb00baxt|url-access=registration|accessdate=24 December 2011|date=10 February 2009|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-06-087434-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/carnalknowledgeb00baxt/page/13 13]}}</ref>\n* [[Felix Arndt]], American pianist (October 16, 1918)<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/item/n82063875/felix-arndt/ Felix Arndt] Library of Congress</ref><ref>[http://www.unconservatory.org/celam/arndtbio.html Bio: Felix Arndt] The Unconservatory</ref>\n* [[Dudley John Beaumont]], husband of the Dame of Sark (November 24, 1918)<ref name=hathway59>{{cite book |last=Hathaway |first=Sibyl |authorlink=Sibyl Hathaway |title=Dame of Sark: An Autobiography|edition=2nd|year=1962 |publisher=Coward-McCann, Inc. |location=[[New York City|New York]] |isbn= | url=https://archive.org/details/dameofsark006367mbp|page=59}}</ref>\n* [[Louis Botha]], first Prime Minister of the [[Union of South Africa]] (August 27, 1919)<ref>{{Harvnb|Duncan|2003|p=16}}{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Randolph Bourne]], American progressive writer and public intellectual, (December 22, 1918)<ref name=\"dMAC Health Digest\">[http://www.dmacdigest.com/flu1918.html dMAC Health Digest].</ref>\n* [[Ivan Cankar]], Slovenian Writer, (December 11, 1918)<ref>Historical Dictionary of Slovenia (Third edition - 2018) by Leopoldina Plut-Pregelj, Gregor Kranjc, \u017darko Lazarevi\u0107, Carole Rogel - Page 67</ref>\n* [[Bernard Capes]], British novelist (2 November 1918) <ref> Lamb, Hugh. \"Introduction\", to Capes, Bernard. ''The Black Reaper''. Ashcroft, B.C. : 