author<ref>[http://jewishnews.at/jewish-news-from-austria-21/the-impossibility-of-being-kafka.html The Impossibility of Being Kafka], December 24, 2008, Jewish News From Austria</ref>\n* [[Prince Maximilian of Baden]] (1867\u20131929), [[Chancellor of Germany (German Reich)|Chancellor of Germany]] during the [[Armistice with Germany (Compi\u00e8gne)|armistice]]<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Edvard Munch]] (1863\u20131944), [[Norwegian people|Norwegian]] painter<ref>Munch Museum, \"A timeline of Munch's life\".[http://www.munch.museum.no/content.aspx?id=14 Munch Museum] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5h5mFXCHn?url=http://www.munch.museum.no/content.aspx?id=14 |date=2009-05-27 }}. Accessed 2009-05-24. [https://www.webcitation.org/5h5mFXCHn?url=http://www.munch.museum.no/content.aspx?id=14 Archived] 2009-05-27.</ref>\n* [[Georgia O'Keeffe]] (1887\u20131986), American [[modernism|modernist]] painter<ref>[[Roxana Robinson]], Georgia O'Keeffe: A Life. University Press of New England, 1989. p. 193. {{ISBN|0-87451-906-3}}</ref>\n* [[John J. Pershing]] (1860\u20131948), American general<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Mary Pickford]] (1892\u20131979), American film actress<ref name=\"Collier\">Collier 1974{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Katherine Anne Porter]] (1890\u20131980), Pulitzer Prize-winning American writer<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] (1882\u20131945), American president<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Le\u00f3 Szil\u00e1rd]] (1898\u20131964), [[nuclear physics|nuclear physicist]], discoverer of the [[nuclear chain reaction]]<ref>[[Richard Rhodes]], The Making of the Atomic Bomb, {{ISBN|0-684-81378-5}}.</ref>\n* [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor]] (1859\u20131941)<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n* [[Woodrow Wilson]] (1856\u20131924), American president<ref name=\"Collier\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1918 flu pandemic}}\n[[Category:Lists of people by medical condition|Spanish flu]]\n[[Category:Spanish flu]]\n[[Category:Death-related lists]]\n[[Category:1910s-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "Bay o pigs", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added director John H. Collins to the list", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Spanish_flu_cases"}
{"title_page": "Helicopter money", "text_new": "{{Distinguish | People's QE | Basic income }}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n[[File:Helicopter money.png|right|200px|title=Figurative illustration of central banks making payments directly to individuals]]\n'''Helicopter money''' is a proposed [[unconventional monetary policy]], sometimes suggested as an alternative to [[quantitative easing]] (QE) when the economy is in a [[liquidity trap]] (when interest rates near zero and the economy remains in [[recession]]). Although the original idea of helicopter money describes central banks making payments directly to individuals, economists have used the term 'helicopter money' to refer to a wide range of different policy ideas, including the 'permanent' [[debt monetization|monetization of budget deficits]] \u2013 with the additional element of attempting to shock beliefs about future inflation or nominal GDP growth, in order to change expectations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worthwhile.typepad.com/worthwhile_canadian_initi/2016/04/helicopter-money-is-permanent.html |title=Worthwhile Canadian Initiative|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> A second set of policies, closer to the original description of helicopter money, and more innovative in the context of monetary history, involves the central bank making direct transfers to the private sector financed with base money, without the direct involvement of fiscal authorities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/economics-blog/2015/may/21/now-the-bank-of-england-needs-to-deliver-qe-for-the-people |title=Now the Bank of England needs to deliver QE for the people|first1=Mark|last1=Blyth |first2=Eric|last2=Lonergan |first3=Simon|last3=Wren-Lewis |date=21 May 2015|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2014/9/9/6122517/helicopter-drop-money-print-fed-blyth-lonergan |title=To fix the economy, let's print money and mail it to everyone|author=Dylan Matthews|date=15 May 2015|work=Vox|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> This has also been called a [[citizens' dividend]] or a distribution of future [[seigniorage]].<ref>{{cite web|quote=Helicopter money is giving to the people part of the net present value of your future seigniorage, the profit you make on the future banknotes. |title=Interview with Peter Praet, Member of the Executive Board of the ECB, conducted by Ferdinando Giugliano and Tonia Mastrobuoni on 15 March 2016 and published on 18 March 2016|url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/inter/date/2016/html/sp160318.en.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200216181909/https://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/inter/date/2016/html/sp160318.en.html |archivedate=16 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe name \"helicopter money\" was first coined by [[Milton Friedman]] in 1969, when he wrote a parable of dropping money from a helicopter to illustrate the effects of monetary expansion. The concept was revived by economists as a monetary policy proposal in the early 2000s following Japan's [[Lost Decade (Japan)|Lost Decade]]. In November 2002, [[Ben Bernanke]], then [[Federal Reserve]] Board governor, and later chairman suggested that helicopter money could always be used to prevent deflation.\n\n== Origins ==\nAlthough very similar concepts have been previously defended by various people including [[Major Douglas]] and the [[Social Credit Movement]], Nobel winning economist [[Milton Friedman]] is known to be the one who coined the term 'helicopter money' in the now famous paper \"[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FwA7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT14&hl=ru&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=3 The Optimum Quantity of Money]\" (1969), where he included the following parable:\n\n<blockquote>Let us suppose now that one day a helicopter flies over this community and drops an additional $1,000 in bills from the sky, which is, of course, hastily collected by members of the community. Let us suppose further that everyone is convinced that this is a unique event which will never be repeated.</blockquote>\n\nOriginally used by Friedman to illustrate the effects of monetary policy on inflation and the costs of holding money, rather than an actual policy proposal, the concept has since then been increasingly discussed by economists as a serious alternative to monetary policy instruments such as [[quantitative easing]]. According to its proponents, helicopter money would be a more efficient way to increase aggregate demand, especially in a situation of [[liquidity trap]], when central banks have reached the so-called '[[zero lower bound]]'.\n\nFriedman himself refers to financing transfer payments with base money as evidence that monetary policy still has power when conventional policies have failed, in his discussion of the [[Pigou effect]], in his 1968 AER Presidential address.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://assets.aeaweb.org/assets/production/journals/aer/top20/58.1.1-17.pdf |title=The Role of Monetary Policy|journal=American Economic Review|author=[[Milton Friedman]]|volume=58|issue=1|date=March 1968|pp=1\u201317|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160605050134/https://assets.aeaweb.org/assets/production/journals/aer/top20/58.1.1-17.pdf |archivedate=2016-06-05}}</ref> Specifically, Friedman argues that \"[the] revival of belief in the potency of money policy ... was strongly fostered among economists by the theoretical developments initiated by Haberler but named for Pigou that pointed out a channel \u2013 namely changes in wealth \u2013 whereby changes in the real quantity of money can affect aggregate demand even if they do not alter interest rates.\" Friedman is clear that money must be produced \"in other ways\" than open-market operations, which \u2013 like QE \u2013 involve \"simply substituting money for other assets without changing total wealth.\" Friedman references a paper by Gottfried Haberler written in 1952, where Haberler says, \"Suppose the quantity of money is increased by tax reductions or government transfer payments, and the resulting deficit is financed by borrowing from the central bank or simply printing money\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Haberler|first=Gottfried |date=1952-01-01|title=The Pigou Effect Once More|jstor=1826454|journal=Journal of Political Economy |volume=60|issue=3|pages=240\u2013246 |doi=10.1086/257211}}</ref>\n\nIt is noteworthy in light of more recent debates over the separation between monetary and fiscal policy, that Friedman viewed these policies as evidence of the potency of monetary policy. In the same AER address, he is highly critical of the timeliness and efficacy of fiscal measures to stabilize demand.\n\nThe idea of helicopter drops was revived as a serious policy proposal in the early 2000s by economists considering the lessons from Japan. [[Ben Bernanke]] famously delivered a speech on preventing deflation in November 2002 as a Federal Reserve Board governor, where he says that Keynes \"once semi-seriously proposed, as an anti-deflationary measure, that the government fill bottles with currency and bury them in mine shafts to be dug up by the public.\" In that speech, Bernanke himself says, \"a money-financed tax cut is essentially equivalent to Milton Friedman's famous 'helicopter drop' of money.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/boarddocs/Speeches/2002/20021121/default.htm#f8 |title=Speech, Bernanke --Deflation-- November 21, 2002|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> In a footnote to that speech, Bernanke also references an important paper by Gauti Eggertson which emphasizes the importance of a commitment from the central bank to keep the money supply at a higher level in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/wp/2003/wp0364.pdf |title=How to Fight Deflation in a Liquidity Trap: Committing to Being Irresponsible|work=IMF|type=Working Paper|author=Gauti B. Eggertsson|date=March 1, 2003}}</ref> The Irish economist, [[Eric Lonergan]], also argued in 2002 in the ''Financial Times'', that central banks consider cash transfers to households as an alternative to further reductions in interest rates, also on the grounds of financial stability.<ref>Beyond interest rates, Financial Times, Sep 09, 2002</ref> In 2003, [[Willem Buiter]], then chief economist at the [[European Bank for Reconstruction and Development]],  revived the concept of helicopter money in a theoretical paper, arguing that base money is not a liability, which provides a more rigorous case for Friedman and Haberler's Pigouvian intuitions.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.willembuiter.com/helinber.pdf | title=Helicopter Money Irredeemable fiat money and the liquidity trap Or: is money net wealth after all? | date=2003-11-06 | author=Willem H. Buiter}}</ref>\n\nStarting from 2012, economists have also called this idea \"[[quantitative easing]] for the people.\"<ref name=\"reuters.com\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/anatole-kaletsky/2012/08/01/how-about-quantitative-easing-for-the-people/ |title=How about quantitative easing for the people?|work=Reuters|accessdate=5 May 2016|date=August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"voxeu.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.voxeu.org/article/combatting-eurozone-deflation-qe-people |title=Combatting Eurozone deflation: QE for the people|publisher=[[Centre for Economic Policy Research]] |accessdate=5 May 2016|date=2014-12-23}}</ref>\n\n== Policy response to the global financial crisis ==\nIn December 2008, [[Eric Lonergan]] and [[Martin Wolf]] suggested in the ''Financial Times'' that central banks make cash transfers directly to households, financed with base money, to combat the threat of global deflation.<ref>{{cite web|quote=Central banks may soon resort to their most powerful weapons against deflation: the printing press and the \"helicopter drop\" of money. |title=Helicopter Ben confronts the challenge of a lifetime, ''Financial Times'', 16 December 2008|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/d049482c-cb8f-11dd-ba02-000077b07658.html#axzz45kZzwC6m}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|quote=The most direct and efficient solution to the economic and financial problems is for central banks to transfer cash directly to the household sector. |title=Central banks need a helicopter, ''Financial Times'', 4 December 2008|url=http://blogs.ft.com/economistsforum/2008/12/central-banks-need-a-helicopter/}}</ref>  From around 2012 onwards, some economists began advocating variants of helicopter drops, including '[[Quantitative easing|QE]] for the people', and a 'debt jubilee' financed with the monetary base.<ref name=\"reuters.com\"/> These proposals reflected a sense that conventional policies, including QE, were failing or having many adverse effects - on either financial stability or the distribution of wealth and income. In 2013, the chairman of the UK's [[Financial Services Authority]] (FCA), [[Adair Turner]], who had been considered a serious candidate to succeed [[Mervyn King, Baron King of Lothbury|Mervyn King]] as Governor of the Bank of England, argued that deficit monetization is the fastest way to recover from the financial crisis in a speech.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fca.org.uk/news/speeches/debt-money-and-mephistopheles-speech |title=Debt, Money, and Mephistopheles: How do we get out of this mess? - Speech|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Implementation ==\nAlthough the original definition of helicopter money describes a situation where central banks distribute cash directly to individuals, more modern use of the term refer to other possibilities, such as granting a universal tax rebate to all households, financed by the central bank. This is, for example, what the United States did with the [[Economic Stimulus Act of 2008]]. The use of tax rebates explains why some consider helicopter money as a fiscal stimulus as opposed to a monetary policy tool. Helicopter money, however, is not meant to be permanent, and is therefore a different policy option than universal basic income.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://basicincome.org/news/2017/03/helicopter-money-basic-income-friends-or-foes/ |title=Helicopter money and basic income: friends or foes? {{!}} Basic Income News|last=|first= |date=2017-03-25|work=Basic Income News|access-date=2017-04-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nUnder a strict definition, where helicopter drops are simply transfers from the central bank to the private sector financed with base money a number of economists have argued that they are already occurring.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/03/17/central-banks-are-already-doing-the-unthinkable---you-just-dont/ |title=Central banks are already doing the unthinkable - you just don't know it|author=Mehreen Khan|date=19 March 2016|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> In 2016, the [[European Central Bank]] (ECB) launched a [[TLTRO]] programme lending money to banks at negative interest rates, which amounts to a transfer to banks. Also, the use of differential interest rates on tiered reserves to support commercial banks' profitability in the face of negative interest rates, opens up another source of helicopter drop - albeit intermediated by banks.<ref>{{cite web|quote=Central banks have ways to drop money into ailing economies. |title=Free lunch: Helicopter engineering, published on 16 February 29 2016|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/3/914fae3e-dec6-11e5-b072-006d8d362ba3.html#axzz45kZzwC6m }}</ref>\n\nIn the case of the Eurozone, the use of [http://bruegel.org/2014/09/t-ltro-variation-on-a-ecbs-theme/ TLTROs] is believed by some economists to provide a legal and administratively tractable means of introducing transfers to households.<ref name=\"bruegel.org\">{{cite web|url=http://bruegel.org/2016/03/helicopter-drops-reloaded/ |title=Helicopter drops reloaded|publisher=breugel.org|author1=H\u00fcttl, Pia |author2=Alvaro Leandro |date=March 14, 2016|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> The economist, Eric Lonergan, argued in 2016 that legal helicopter drops in the Eurozone could be structured via zero coupon, perpetual loans, which all European adult citizens would be eligible to receive. The loans could be administered by eligible commercial banks, and under certain conditions the loans would be net interest income positive to the central bank.<ref>{{cite web|title=Legal helicopter drops in the Eurozone, published on February 24 2016|url=https://www.philosophyofmoney.net/legal-helicopter-drops-in-the-eurozone/}}</ref> This idea was revived in 2019 by [[Frances Coppola]], in her book, The Case for People\u2019s Quantitative Easing, and also by researchers at [[BlackRock]], including Stanley Fischer, and also by the French economist Jean Pisani-Ferry.\n\n== Controversies ==\n\nMany economists would argue that helicopter money, in the form of cash transfers to households, should not be seen as a substitute for fiscal policy. Given the government's borrowing costs are extremely low at close to zero interest rates, conventional fiscal stimulus through tax cuts and infrastructure spending should work. From this perspective, helicopter money is really an insurance policy against the failure of fiscal policy for political, legal or institutional reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mainlymacro.blogspot.co.uk/2016/03/two-related-confusions-about-helicopter.html |title=mainly macro|author=Mainly Macro|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016|date=March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Differences from quantitative easing===\nLike all expansionary [[monetary policy|monetary policies]] in general, [[quantitative easing]] (QE) and helicopter money involves money creation by central banks to expand the money supply. However, the effect on the central bank's balance sheet of helicopter money is different than with QE. Under QE, central banks create reserves by purchasing bonds or other financial assets, conducting an '[[asset swap]]'.<ref name=Grenville2013>{{cite web |last1=Grenville |first1=Stephen |title=Helicopter money |url=https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money |website=VoxEU.org  |publisher=[[Centre for Economic Policy Research]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190920074154/https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money |archivedate=20 September 2019 |date=24 February 2013 |url-status=live |quote=Central banks have no mandate to give money away (they can only exchange one asset for another, as they do in quantitative easing)}}</ref> The swap is reversible. By contrast, with helicopter money, central banks give away the money created, without increasing assets on their balance sheet.\n\nEconomists argue that the effect on expectations is different because helicopter money created would be perceived as 'permanent' \u2013 that is, more irreversible than QE. Economists have pointed out that the effect is not different from a combination of expansionary fiscal policy and expansionary monetary policy conducted at the same time.\n\n===Implications for central bank balance sheets===\nOne of the main concerns with transfers from the central bank directly to the private sector is that in contrast to conventional [[open-market operations]] the central bank does not have an asset corresponding to the base money created. This has implications for the measured equity of the central bank because base money is typically treated as a liability, but it could also constrain the central bank's ability to set interest rates in the future. The accounting treatment of central banks' balance sheets is controversial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.ft.com/economistsforum/2012/06/governments-can-borrow-without-increasing-their-debt/ |title=Governments can borrow without increasing their debt|work=Financial Times|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> Most economists now recognize that the 'capital' of the central bank is not really important.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/pub/pdf/scpwps/ecbwp392.pdf?e7bba27cdd7b653529fc35400ff0a3c0 | title=The Role of Central Bank Capital Revisited | publisher=European Central Bank | date=September 2004 | author=Ulrich Bindseil|author2=Andres Manzanares|author3=Benedict Weller | issn=1725-2806}}</ref> What matters is can whether expansion of base money be reversed in the future, or are there other means to raise interest rates. Various options have been proposed. Oxford professor, Simon Wren-Lewis has suggested that the government pre-commit to providing the Bank of England with bonds if needed. The European Central Bank can, in fact, mandate an increase in its capital, and the introduction of [[tiered reserves]] and [[interest on reserves]] gives central banks an array of tools to protect their own net income and the demand for reserves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philosophyofmoney.net/does-the-central-banks-balance-sheet-matter/ |title=Does the central bank's balance sheet matter?|author=Eric Lonergan|work=Philosophy of Money|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Supporters ==\nFormer chairman of the Federal Reserve [[Ben Bernanke]] is known to be one of the proponents of helicopter money when he gave a speech in November 2002 arguing, in the case of Japan, that \"a money-financed tax cut is essentially equivalent to Milton Friedman's famous 'helicopter drop' of money.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalreserve.gov/boarddocs/Speeches/2002/20021121/default.htm |title=Speech, Bernanke --Deflation-- November 21, 2002|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> In April 2016, Ben Bernanke wrote a blog post arguing that \"such programs may be the best available alternative. It would be premature to rule them out.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brookings.edu/blogs/ben-bernanke/posts/2016/04/11-helicopter-money |title=What tools does the Fed have left? Part 3: Helicopter money|author=Ben S. Bernanke|date=11 April 2016|work=The Brookings Institution|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> Fed chairwoman [[Janet Yellen]] also admitted that helicopter money could be an option in \"extreme situations\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/06/16/news/economy/federal-reserve-janet-yellen-helicopter-money/index.html |title=Janet Yellen: Helicopter money is an option in extreme situations|last=Gillespie|first=Patrick |work=CNNMoney|access-date=2017-11-17}}</ref>\n\nCitigroup Chief Economist [[Willem Buiter]] is also known to be a prominent advocate of the concept.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/business/economists-say-handing-out-cash-could-help-euro-zone-economy-a-1011352.html |title=Economists Say Handing Out Cash Could Help Euro Zone Economy|author=((SPIEGEL ONLINE, Hamburg, Germany))|date=6 January 2015|work=SPIEGEL ONLINE|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> Other proponents include Financial Times' Chief Commentator [[Martin Wolf]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/9bcf0eea-6f98-11e2-b906-00144feab49a.html#axzz2vaE3myVK |title=The case for helicopter money|work=Financial Times|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> Oxford economists [[John Muellbauer]],<ref name=\"voxeu.org\"/> and [[Simon Wren-Lewis]], Economist [[Steve Keen]], the political economist [[Mark Blyth]] of [[Brown University]], Berkeley economics professor and former Treasury advisor, [[Brad DeLong]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/helicopter-money-fiscal-stimulus-by-j--bradford-delong-2016-04 |title=Rescue Helicopters for Stranded Economies|author=J. Bradford DeLong|work=Project Syndicate|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.milkenreview.org/articles/helicopter-money-when-zero-just-isnt-low-enough |title=Helicopter Money: When Zero Just Isn't Low Enough|website=[[Milken Institute]] Review|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref> UCLA economics professor, [[Roger Farmer]], American macro hedge fund manager [[Ray Dalio]], Irish economist and Fund manager [[Eric Lonergan]],<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5EA2nKqcjtg |title=Why the ECB should give money directly to People (Eric Lonergan)|date=8 April 2016|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref> [[Anatole Kaletsky]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/onpoint/central-bankings-final-frontier-by-anatole-kaletsky-2016-05 |title=Central Banking's Final Frontier? by Anatole Kaletsky - Project Syndicate|first=Anatole|last=Kaletsky |date=6 May 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Romain Baeriswyl,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Monetary Policy, Financial Crises, and the Macroeconomy|last=Baeriswyl|first=Romain |date=2017|publisher=Springer, Cham|isbn=9783319562605 |pages=105\u2013121|language=en |doi=10.1007/978-3-319-56261-2_6 |chapter = The Case for the Separation of Money and Credit}}</ref> [[Martin Sandbu]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1dc5b4a8-57da-11e6-9f70-badea1b336d4 |title=Helicopter money: if not now, then when?|last=Sandbu|first=Martin |date=2016|work=Financial Times|access-date=}}</ref>, [[Jean Pisani-Ferry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/europe-next-recession-alternative-policies-by-jean-pisani-ferry-2019-09 |title=How to Ward Off the Next Recession |last=Pisani-Ferry|first=Jean |date=2019-09-30|website=Project Syndicate|language=en|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n\nThe idea also finds support among central bankers. For example, former governor of the Irish central bank [[Patrick Honohan]] said he believes the policy would work while the ECB's chief economist [[Peter Praet]] once said \"All central banks can do it\". The Vice-Governor of the Czech Central Bank [[Mojm\u00edr Hampl]] published a paper in which he writes that \"the idea offers many virtues and advantages compared to other forms of unconventional monetary policy, especially obliterating the need to rely on a complicated transmission mechanism, allowing much easier communication to the public, and boosting consumer confidence when most needed.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mojmir|first=Hampl |last2=Tomas|first2=Havranek |date=2018|title=Central Bank Capital as an Instrument of Monetary Policy|url=https://www.econstor.eu/handle/10419/176828 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBill Gross, Portfolio Manager of the Janus Global Unconstrained Bond Fund also argues for the implementation of a [[basic income]], funded by helicopter drops.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.janus.com/bill-gross-investment-outlook |title=Bill Gross Investment Outlook May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2016/05/04/bill-gross-what-to-do-after-the-robots-take-our-jobs |title=Bill Gross: What to Do After the Robots Take Our Jobs|author=Paul Vigna|work=WSJ|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, prominent central bankers [[Stanley Fischer]] and [[Philipp Hildebrand|Philip Hildebrand]] co-authored a paper published by BlackRock<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackrock.com/us/individual/literature/whitepaper/bii-macro-perspectives-august-2019.pdf |title=Dealing with the next downturn: From unconventional monetary policy to unprecedented policy coordination|last=Stanley Fischer, Elga Bartsch, Jean Boivin, Stanley Fischer, Philipp Hildebrand|date=August 2019|website=[[BlackRock]] Institute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> in which they propose a form of helicopter money.\n\n==Critics==\n[[File:Hyperinflation in Germany in 1923.jpg|thumb|Hyperinflation in Germany in 1923]]\n\n===Inflationary effect===\nIn the past the idea had been dismissed because it was thought that it would inevitably lead to [[hyperinflation]].{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nConsequently, a range of concerns include the fact that helicopter money would undermine trust in the currency (which ultimately would lead to hyperinflation). This concern was particularly voiced by German Economist (and former Chief Economist at the ECB) [[Otmar Issing]] in a paper written in 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://safe-frankfurt.de/fileadmin/user_upload/editor_common/Policy_Center/Issing_Helicopter-Money.pdf | title=Die letzte Waffe \u2013 Helicopter Money? | publisher=SAFE | date=7 February 2015 | author=Otmar Issing | type=Press Article}}</ref> Later in 2016, he declared in an interview: \"I think the whole idea of the helicopter money is downright devastating. For this is nothing more than a declaration of bankruptcy of the monetary policy\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/ex-ezb-chefvolkswirt-otmar-issing-warnt-vor-helikoptergeld-14141309.html#GEPC;s3 |title=Ex-EZB-Chefvolkswirt Otmar Issing warnt vor \"Helikoptergeld\"|date=23 March 2016|author=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung GmbH|work=FAZ.NET|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> [[Richard Koo]] makes a similar argument<ref>{{cite web | url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2016/07/27/2170980/koo-on-why-helicopter-money-just-wont-work/ | title=Koo on why helicopter money just won't work | work=FT Alphaville | date=27 July 2016 | author=Izabella Kaminska}}</ref> when saying \"if such envelopes arrived day after day, the entire country would quickly fall into a panic as people lose all sense of what their currency is worth.\"\n\nThis clashes with the argument that people would not spend much of the money they receive (and therefore helicopter money cannot be inflationary).\n\n=== Would helicopter money be spent? ===\nSeveral prominent economist such as central banker [[Raghuram Rajan]] are against helicopter money on the grounds that helicopter money would be ineffective because people would not spend the money.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/john-cassidy/raghuram-rajan-and-the-dangers-of-helicopter-money |title=Raghuram Rajan and the Dangers of Helicopter Money|first=John|last=Cassidy |date=13 May 2016|publisher=|via=www.newyorker.com}}</ref> In response, Lord [[Adair Turner]] argues: \"Money financed deficits will always stimulate nominal demand. By comparison debt finance deficits might do so, but might not.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.ineteconomics.org/ideas-papers/research-papers/why-a-future-tax-on-bank-credit-intermediation-does-not-offset-the-stimulative-effect-of-money-finance-deficits |title=Why a future tax on bank credit intermediation does not offset the stimulative effect of money finance deficits|website=Institute for New Economic Thinking}}</ref>\n\nContradicting this argument, several surveys conducted in the Eurozone concluded however that between 30 and 55% of the distributed money would be spent by households, in effect resulting in a boost of around 2% of GDP.<ref>[http://www.astelloncapital.com/documents/FG/astellon/news/519100_Astellon_Notes_-_Helicopter_Money.pdf Helicopter Money \u2013 Let It Rain?], Astellon Capital, June 2016</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ezonomics.com/ing_international_surveys/helicopter-money-2016/ |title=Helicopter Money 2016|last=eZonomics|first=ING|website=eZonomics by ING|language=en|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Djuric|first=Uros |last2=Neugart|first2=Michael| date=2016-12-17|title=Helicopter Money: Survey Evidence on Expectation Formation and Consumption Behavior|ssrn=2893008|location=Rochester, NY}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnb.nl/en/news/dnb-publications/dnb-working-papers-series/dnb-working-papers/working-papers-2016/dnb350283.jsp |title=Will helicopter money be spent? New evidence - De Nederlandsche Bank|author1=Maarten van Rooij | author2=Jakob de Haan|date=2017|website=www.dnb.nl|language=en|access-date=2017-04-10}}</ref>\n\n===\"There is no such thing as a free lunch\"===\n\nAnother range of critics involve the idea that there cannot be such thing as \"free money\" or as economists say \"[[there is no such thing as a free lunch]]\". This criticism was notably expressed by Bank for International Settlements researchers Claudio Borio, Piti Disyatat, Anna Zabai.,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money-illusion-free-lunch |title=Helicopter money: The illusion of a free lunch|first1=Claudio|last1=Borio |first2=Piti|last2=Disyatat |first3=Anna|last3=Zabai |date=24 May 2016|publisher=}}</ref> who claimed that helicopter drops to citizens would necessarily involve for the central bank to pay interests on the extra reserves being supplied.\n\nIn a response, the former IMF economist [[Biagio Bossone]] challenges the later assumption<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economonitor.com/blog/2016/06/why-helicopter-money-is-a-free-lunch/ |title=Why Helicopter Money is a \"Free Lunch\" - EconoMonitor|website=www.economonitor.com}}</ref> and argues that \"helicopter money is a 'free lunch' in the simple sense that, if it works and succeeds in closing the output gap, people won\u2019t have to repay it through higher taxes or undesired (above optimal) inflation.\"\n\n===Legality===\n\nOther critics claim helicopter money would be outside of the mandate of central banks, because it would \"blur the lines between fiscal policy and monetary policy\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/inter/date/2016/html/sp160926_3.en.html |title=Interview with S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung|last=Bank|first=European Central|website=European Central Bank|language=en|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref> mainly because helicopter money would involve 'fiscal effects' which is traditionally the role of governments to decide on. However advocates of helicopter money such as Eric Lonergan and Simon Wren-Lewis invalidate this argument by observing that standard monetary policy tools also have fiscal effects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mainlymacro.blogspot.be/2016/05/helicopter-money-and-fiscal-policy.html |title=Helicopter money and fiscal policy|website=mainlymacro.blogspot.be|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.philosophyofmoney.net/the-distinction-between-monetary-and-fiscal-policy/ |title=The distinction between monetary and fiscal policy - Philosophy of Money|date=2016-04-03|newspaper=Philosophy of Money|access-date=2017-02-11|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe European Central Bank explained, in a letter to MEP [[Jon\u00e1s Fern\u00e1ndez]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/pub/pdf/other/161129letter_fernandez.en_en.pdf |title=Letter from ECB President to Jon\u00e1s Fern\u00e1ndez|last=|first= |date=29 November 2016|website=European Central Bank|url-status=live|archive-url= |archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, that \"legal complexities could still arise if the scheme could be seen as the ECB financing an obligation of the public sector vis-\u00e0-vis third parties, as this would also violate the prohibition of monetary financing\". However this refers to a very unlikely and undesirable case where helicopter money payments by the central bank would substitute to welfare payments (which are a liability of governments).\n\n===Accounting issues===\n\n[[Bundesbank]] president [[Jens Weidmann]] also voiced opposition against helicopter money, arguing it would \"tear gaping holes in central bank balance sheets. Ultimately, it would be down to the euro-area countries, and thus the taxpayer, to shoulder the costs because central banks would be unprofitable for quite some time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesbank.de/Redaktion/EN/Interviews/2016_01_29_weidmann_funke_mediengruppe.html |title=Deutsche Bundesbank - Interviews - \"Helicopter money would tear gaping holes in central bank balance sheets\"|date=21 March 2016|accessdate=5 May 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160518205952/http://www.bundesbank.de/Redaktion/EN/Interviews/2016_01_29_weidmann_funke_mediengruppe.html |archivedate=18 May 2016}}</ref> The [[National Bank of Belgium|National bank of Belgium]] also released a paper making a similar argument.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbb.be/en/articles/helicopter-money-and-debt-financed-fiscal-stimulus-one-and-same-thing |title=Helicopter money and debt-financed fiscal stimulus: one and the same thing? |website=www.nbb.be |language=en|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Threat against central bank independence ===\nEndra Curren and Ben Holland of Bloomberg stated \"That type of stimulus[Helicopter Money] used to be [[taboo]], in part because it risks eroding the independence from politics that monetary policy makers prize [...] History is littered with cautionary tales in which blurring the lines between central bank and Treasury coffers led to runaway inflation.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-09-22/a-long-despised-and-risky-economic-doctrine-is-now-a-hot-idea |title=A Long-Despised and Risky Economic Doctrine Is Now a Hot Idea|date=2019-09-22 |work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-03-16|language=en}}</ref><ref name=Reichlin2019>{{cite web |last1=Reichlin |first1=Lucrezia |last2=Turner |first2=Adair |last3=Woodford |first3=Michael |title=Helicopter money as a policy option |url=https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money-policy-option |website=VoxEU.org |publisher=[[Centre for Economic Policy Research]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20191224180125/https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money-policy-option |archivedate=24 December 2019 |date=23 September 2019 |url-status=live |quote=Helicopter money is a form of fiscal policy. The question arises of whether it is the central bank, the Treasury or both in coordination that should implement it. This has the potential to threaten the principle of central bank independence or at least it may force us to reconsider the rules that govern the relation between Treasury and central banks today}}</ref>{{Empty section|date=December 2018}}\n\n==In the Eurozone==\nOn March 10, 2016, the idea became increasingly popular in Europe after [[Mario Draghi]] the President of the [[European Central Bank]], said in a press conference that he found the concept 'very interesting'.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zbb--KxTjWc |title=Mario Draghi: 'Helicopter money is a very interesting concept'|date=10 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref> This statement was followed by another statement from the ECB's [[Peter Praet]] who declared:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/inter/date/2016/html/sp160318.en.html |title=Interview with La Repubblica|author=European Central Bank|work=European Central Bank|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>\"Yes, all central banks can do it. You can issue currency and you distribute it to people. That\u2019s helicopter money. Helicopter money is giving to the people part of the net present value of your future seigniorage, the profit you make on the future banknotes. The question is, if and when is it opportune to make recourse to that sort of instrument which is really an extreme sort of instrument.\"</blockquote>\n[[File:QE_for_People_European_parliament.jpg|thumb|Conference on \"QE for People\" organised at the European parliament by [[Positive Money]] (17 February 2016)]]\nIn 2015, a European campaign called \"Quantitative Easing for People\" was launched<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fd.nl/economie-politiek/1129670/handtekeningenactie-voor-helikoptergeld |title=Cookiewall - Het Financieele Dagblad|website=fd.nl}}</ref> and is effectively promoting the concept of Helicopter Money, along with other proposals for 'Green QE' and 'Strategic QE' which are other types of monetary financing operations by central banks involving public investment programmes. The campaign was supported by 20 organisations across Europe and more than 116 economists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qe4people.eu |title=QE for People \u2022 A Rescue Plan for the Eurozone|work=Quantitative Easing for People|accessdate=5 May 2016|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180411122417/http://www.qe4people.eu/ |archive-date=11 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\nOn June 17, 2016, 18 Members of the European Parliament (including [[Philippe Lamberts]], [[Paul Tang (politician)|Paul Tang]] and [[Fabio De Masi]]) signed an open letter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qe4people.eu/open_letter_to_the_ecb |title=MEPs want the ECB to look at helicopter money|publisher=}}</ref> calling on the ECB to \"provide evidence-based analysis of the potential effects of the alternative proposals mentioned above, and to clarify under which conditions their implementation would be legal.\" If it doesn't consider alternatives to QE, MEPs fear the ECB would leave itself \u201cunprepared for a deterioration in economic conditions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/c5d08c5c-339c-11e6-bda0-04585c31b153.html |title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, a survey showed that 54% Europeans think helicopter money would be a good idea, with only 14% against.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.qe4people.eu/majority_europeans_are_in_favour_of_helicopter_money |title=54% of Europeans are in favour of 'helicopter money'|newspaper=Quantitative Easing for People|access-date=2016-10-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, politicians, civil society organisations and economists debated issuing helicopter money as a response to the [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Europe|coronavirus pandemic in Europe]].<ref name=Gali2020>{{cite web |last1=Gal\u00ed |first1=Jordi |title=Helicopter money: The time is now |url=https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money-time-now |website=VoxEU.org |publisher=[[Centre for Economic Policy Research]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200323175324/https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money-time-now |archivedate=23 March 2020 |date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stevis-Gridneff |first1=Matina |last2=Ewing |first2=Jack |title=Will \u2018Helicopter Money\u2019 and the \u2018Big Bazooka\u2019 Help Rescue Europe? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/business/EU-European-Central-Bank-economy-covid.html |website=The New York Times |date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/finanzen/geldpolitik/massnahmen-gegen-die-krise-bargeld-fuer-die-buerger-oekonomen-loben-das-helikoptergeld/25723120.html|title=Ma\u00dfnahmen gegen die Krise: Bargeld f\u00fcr die B\u00fcrger: \u00d6konomen loben das Helikoptergeld|website=www.handelsblatt.com|language=de|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.positivemoney.eu/2020/03/helicopter-money-covid19-report/|title=Report: Helicopter money as a response to the COVID-19 crisis|last=Jourdan|first=Stanislas|date=2020-03-30|website=Positive Money Europe|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== In USA ==\nIn 2020, the US legislative system debated issuing two times a $1,000 check to each eligible adult citizen, described by media as 'Helicopter Money', as a response to the [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_United_States|US coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The global markets barely budge as helicopter-money measures achieve lift-off |url=https://fortune.com/2020/03/19/global-markets-calm-helicopter-money/ |website=Fortune |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Trump seeks stimulus package potentially worth more than $1 trillion, including direct payments to Americans |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/17/mnuchin-says-trump-administration-is-looking-to-get-cash-to-americans-immediately.html |website=CNBC |language=en |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> However, this practice cannot be considered as 'Helicopter Money' as long as this money distribution is financed by the State ([[debt]]) and not by [[central bank]] money printing (monetary expansion).\n\n== In Japan ==\nIn a meeting with Japanese Prime Minister [[Shinzo Abe]] and [[Bank of Japan]]'s [[Haruhiko Kuroda]] in July 2016 it was widely reported<ref>[http://www.thefiscaltimes.com/Columns/2016/07/12/Can-Helicopter-Ben-Bernanke-Save-Japan Can 'Helicopter Ben Bernanke' Save Japan?], Retrieved July 28, 2016.</ref> that former Federal Reserve chairman Ben Bernanke advised the policy of monetizing more government debt created to fund infrastructure projects,<ref name=bl-20160727>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-27/abe-s-unusual-stimulus-announcement-may-be-directed-at-the-boj |title=Abe's Unusual Stimulus Unveiling May Be Directed at the BOJ |author=Enda Curran, Toru Fujioka |publisher=Bloomberg |date=27 July 2016 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> ostensibly as a way to drop \"Helicopter Money\" on Japan to stimulate the economy and halt deflation in Japan.  Financial markets began to front-run this stimulus effort days before it was announced when accounts of Bernanke's visit to Japan were first reported.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\nLater in the month the [[Bank of Japan]] ongoing review of its monetary stimulus program was reported to be considering policies somewhat similar to \"Helicopter Money\", such as selling 50-year or perpetual bonds.<ref name=jt-20160731>{{cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/07/31/business/economy-business/helicopter-money-talk-takes-flight-bank-japan-runs-runway/#.V55ptaIbiUk |title='Helicopter money' talk takes flight as Bank of Japan runs out of runway |author=Stanley White |newspaper=The Japan Times |agency=Reuters |date=31 July 2016 |accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref> However, even if the central bank commits to hold these 50-year government bonds for a very long time, that is not helicopter money as long as this money, financed by the State (debt) and not by central bank money printing per say, is not distributed to households directly.\n\n==Popular Culture==\nComedy heavy metal band [[Nanowar of Steel]] cited the helicopter drop monetary policy in their financial-epic-metal song \"Tooth Fairy\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CzvQxQYKO88 Nanowar of Steel Tooth Fairy - Youtube video] </ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[People's Quantitative Easing]]\n* [[Monetary policy]]\n* [[Universal Basic Income]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2016/581970/EPRS_BRI(2016)581970_EN.pdf Helicopter money: A cure for what ails the euro area?], European Parliamentary Research Service, April 2016\n* [http://willembuiter.com/helifinal.pdf Helicopter Money: Why it works - Always], Willem Buiter, 2014\n* [http://bruegel.org/2016/03/helicopter-drops-reloaded/ Helicopter Money reloaded], Bruegel, 2016\n* [http://positivemoney.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Recovery-in-the-Eurozone-FINAL-WEB-READY-2015-12-11.pdf Recovery in the Eurozone: using money creation to Stimulate the economy], Frank van Lerven, 2015\n* [http://mainlymacro.blogspot.fr/2012/10/what-do-people-mean-by-helicopter-money.html What do people mean by helicopter money?], Simon Wren-Lewis, 2012\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160804004646/http://www.fvs-ri.com/files/better_monetary_system.pdf From Zirp, Nirp, QE, and helicopter money to a better monetary system], Thomas Mayer, 2016\n* [https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/qe4people/pages/106/attachments/original/1475528559/Citizens_Monetary_Dividend.pdf?1475528559 Citizens' Monetary Dividend \u2013 Upgrading the ECB's Toolkit], Stan Jourdan and Eric Lonergan, 2016\n* [https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money-views-leading-economists Helicopter money: Views of leading economists]. [[Centre for Economic Policy Research]], April 2016\n\n{{Portal bar|Business and economics}}\n\n[[Category:Operations of central banks]]\n[[Category:Monetary policy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish | People's QE | Basic income }}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n[[File:Helicopter money.png|right|200px|title=Figurative illustration of central banks making payments directly to individuals]]\n'''Helicopter money''' is a proposed [[unconventional monetary policy]], sometimes suggested as an alternative to [[quantitative easing]] (QE) when the economy is in a [[liquidity trap]] (when interest rates near zero and the economy remains in [[recession]]). Although the original idea of helicopter money describes central banks making payments directly to individuals, economists have used the term 'helicopter money' to refer to a wide range of different policy ideas, including the 'permanent' [[debt monetization|monetization of budget deficits]] \u2013 with the additional element of attempting to shock beliefs about future inflation or nominal GDP growth, in order to change expectations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worthwhile.typepad.com/worthwhile_canadian_initi/2016/04/helicopter-money-is-permanent.html |title=Worthwhile Canadian Initiative|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> A second set of policies, closer to the original description of helicopter money, and more innovative in the context of monetary history, involves the central bank making direct transfers to the private sector financed with base money, without the direct involvement of fiscal authorities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/economics-blog/2015/may/21/now-the-bank-of-england-needs-to-deliver-qe-for-the-people |title=Now the Bank of England needs to deliver QE for the people|first1=Mark|last1=Blyth |first2=Eric|last2=Lonergan |first3=Simon|last3=Wren-Lewis |date=21 May 2015|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2014/9/9/6122517/helicopter-drop-money-print-fed-blyth-lonergan |title=To fix the economy, let's print money and mail it to everyone|author=Dylan Matthews|date=15 May 2015|work=Vox|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> This has also been called a [[citizens' dividend]] or a distribution of future [[seigniorage]].<ref>{{cite web|quote=Helicopter money is giving to the people part of the net present value of your future seigniorage, the profit you make on the future banknotes. |title=Interview with Peter Praet, Member of the Executive Board of the ECB, conducted by Ferdinando Giugliano and Tonia Mastrobuoni on 15 March 2016 and published on 18 March 2016|url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/inter/date/2016/html/sp160318.en.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200216181909/https://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/inter/date/2016/html/sp160318.en.html |archivedate=16 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe name \"helicopter money\" was first coined by [[Milton Friedman]] in 1969, when he wrote a parable of dropping money from a helicopter to illustrate the effects of monetary expansion. The concept was revived by economists as a monetary policy proposal in the early 2000s following Japan's [[Lost Decade (Japan)|Lost Decade]]. In November 2002, [[Ben Bernanke]], then [[Federal Reserve]] Board governor, and later chairman suggested that helicopter money could always be used to prevent deflation.\n\n== Origins ==\nAlthough very similar concepts have been previously defended by various people including [[Major Douglas]] and the [[Social Credit Movement]], Nobel winning economist [[Milton Friedman]] is known to be the one who coined the term 'helicopter money' in the now famous paper \"[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FwA7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT14&hl=ru&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=3 The Optimum Quantity of Money]\" (1969), where he included the following parable:\n\n<blockquote>Let us suppose now that one day a helicopter flies over this community and drops an additional $1,000 in bills from the sky, which is, of course, hastily collected by members of the community. Let us suppose further that everyone is convinced that this is a unique event which will never be repeated.</blockquote>\n\nOriginally used by Friedman to illustrate the effects of monetary policy on inflation and the costs of holding money, rather than an actual policy proposal, the concept has since then been increasingly discussed by economists as a serious alternative to monetary policy instruments such as [[quantitative easing]]. According to its proponents, helicopter money would be a more efficient way to increase aggregate demand, especially in a situation of [[liquidity trap]], when central banks have reached the so-called '[[zero lower bound]]'.\n\nFriedman himself refers to financing transfer payments with base money as evidence that monetary policy still has power when conventional policies have failed, in his discussion of the [[Pigou effect]], in his 1968 AER Presidential address.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://assets.aeaweb.org/assets/production/journals/aer/top20/58.1.1-17.pdf |title=The Role of Monetary Policy|journal=American Economic Review|author=[[Milton Friedman]]|volume=58|issue=1|date=March 1968|pp=1\u201317|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160605050134/https://assets.aeaweb.org/assets/production/journals/aer/top20/58.1.1-17.pdf |archivedate=2016-06-05}}</ref> Specifically, Friedman argues that \"[the] revival of belief in the potency of money policy ... was strongly fostered among economists by the theoretical developments initiated by Haberler but named for Pigou that pointed out a channel \u2013 namely changes in wealth \u2013 whereby changes in the real quantity of money can affect aggregate demand even if they do not alter interest rates.\" Friedman is clear that money must be produced \"in other ways\" than open-market operations, which \u2013 like QE \u2013 involve \"simply substituting money for other assets without changing total wealth.\" Friedman references a paper by Gottfried Haberler written in 1952, where Haberler says, \"Suppose the quantity of money is increased by tax reductions or government transfer payments, and the resulting deficit is financed by borrowing from the central bank or simply printing money\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Haberler|first=Gottfried |date=1952-01-01|title=The Pigou Effect Once More|jstor=1826454|journal=Journal of Political Economy |volume=60|issue=3|pages=240\u2013246 |doi=10.1086/257211}}</ref>\n\nIt is noteworthy in light of more recent debates over the separation between monetary and fiscal policy, that Friedman viewed these policies as evidence of the potency of monetary policy. In the same AER address, he is highly critical of the timeliness and efficacy of fiscal measures to stabilize demand.\n\nThe idea of helicopter drops was revived as a serious policy proposal in the early 2000s by economists considering the lessons from Japan. [[Ben Bernanke]] famously delivered a speech on preventing deflation in November 2002 as a Federal Reserve Board governor, where he says that Keynes \"once semi-seriously proposed, as an anti-deflationary measure, that the government fill bottles with currency and bury them in mine shafts to be dug up by the public.\" In that speech, Bernanke himself says, \"a money-financed tax cut is essentially equivalent to Milton Friedman's famous 'helicopter drop' of money.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/boarddocs/Speeches/2002/20021121/default.htm#f8 |title=Speech, Bernanke --Deflation-- November 21, 2002|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> In a footnote to that speech, Bernanke also references an important paper by Gauti Eggertson which emphasizes the importance of a commitment from the central bank to keep the money supply at a higher level in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/wp/2003/wp0364.pdf |title=How to Fight Deflation in a Liquidity Trap: Committing to Being Irresponsible|work=IMF|type=Working Paper|author=Gauti B. Eggertsson|date=March 1, 2003}}</ref> The Irish economist, [[Eric Lonergan]], also argued in 2002 in the ''Financial Times'', that central banks consider cash transfers to households as an alternative to further reductions in interest rates, also on the grounds of financial stability.<ref>Beyond interest rates, Financial Times, Sep 09, 2002</ref> In 2003, [[Willem Buiter]], then chief economist at the [[European Bank for Reconstruction and Development]],  revived the concept of helicopter money in a theoretical paper, arguing that base money is not a liability, which provides a more rigorous case for Friedman and Haberler's Pigouvian intuitions.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.willembuiter.com/helinber.pdf | title=Helicopter Money Irredeemable fiat money and the liquidity trap Or: is money net wealth after all? | date=2003-11-06 | author=Willem H. Buiter}}</ref>\n\nStarting from 2012, economists have also called this idea \"[[quantitative easing]] for the people.\"<ref name=\"reuters.com\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/anatole-kaletsky/2012/08/01/how-about-quantitative-easing-for-the-people/ |title=How about quantitative easing for the people?|work=Reuters|accessdate=5 May 2016|date=August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"voxeu.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.voxeu.org/article/combatting-eurozone-deflation-qe-people |title=Combatting Eurozone deflation: QE for the people|publisher=[[Centre for Economic Policy Research]] |accessdate=5 May 2016|date=2014-12-23}}</ref>\n\n== Policy response to the global financial crisis ==\nIn December 2008, [[Eric Lonergan]] and [[Martin Wolf]] suggested in the ''Financial Times'' that central banks make cash transfers directly to households, financed with base money, to combat the threat of global deflation.<ref>{{cite web|quote=Central banks may soon resort to their most powerful weapons against deflation: the printing press and the \"helicopter drop\" of money. |title=Helicopter Ben confronts the challenge of a lifetime, ''Financial Times'', 16 December 2008|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/d049482c-cb8f-11dd-ba02-000077b07658.html#axzz45kZzwC6m}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|quote=The most direct and efficient solution to the economic and financial problems is for central banks to transfer cash directly to the household sector. |title=Central banks need a helicopter, ''Financial Times'', 4 December 2008|url=http://blogs.ft.com/economistsforum/2008/12/central-banks-need-a-helicopter/}}</ref>  From around 2012 onwards, some economists began advocating variants of helicopter drops, including '[[Quantitative easing|QE]] for the people', and a 'debt jubilee' financed with the monetary base.<ref name=\"reuters.com\"/> These proposals reflected a sense that conventional policies, including QE, were failing or having many adverse effects - on either financial stability or the distribution of wealth and income. In 2013, the chairman of the UK's [[Financial Services Authority]] (FCA), [[Adair Turner]], who had been considered a serious candidate to succeed [[Mervyn King, Baron King of Lothbury|Mervyn King]] as Governor of the Bank of England, argued that deficit monetization is the fastest way to recover from the financial crisis in a speech.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fca.org.uk/news/speeches/debt-money-and-mephistopheles-speech |title=Debt, Money, and Mephistopheles: How do we get out of this mess? - Speech|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Implementation ==\nAlthough the original definition of helicopter money describes a situation where central banks distribute cash directly to individuals, more modern use of the term refer to other possibilities, such as granting a universal tax rebate to all households, financed by the central bank. This is, for example, what the United States did with the [[Economic Stimulus Act of 2008]]. The use of tax rebates explains why some consider helicopter money as a fiscal stimulus as opposed to a monetary policy tool. Helicopter money, however, is not meant to be permanent, and is therefore a different policy option than universal basic income.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://basicincome.org/news/2017/03/helicopter-money-basic-income-friends-or-foes/ |title=Helicopter money and basic income: friends or foes? {{!}} Basic Income News|last=|first= |date=2017-03-25|work=Basic Income News|access-date=2017-04-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nUnder a strict definition, where helicopter drops are simply transfers from the central bank to the private sector financed with base money a number of economists have argued that they are already occurring.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/03/17/central-banks-are-already-doing-the-unthinkable---you-just-dont/ |title=Central banks are already doing the unthinkable - you just don't know it|author=Mehreen Khan|date=19 March 2016|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> In 2016, the [[European Central Bank]] (ECB) launched a [[TLTRO]] programme lending money to banks at negative interest rates, which amounts to a transfer to banks. Also, the use of differential interest rates on tiered reserves to support commercial banks' profitability in the face of negative interest rates, opens up another source of helicopter drop - albeit intermediated by banks.<ref>{{cite web|quote=Central banks have ways to drop money into ailing economies. |title=Free lunch: Helicopter engineering, published on 16 February 29 2016|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/3/914fae3e-dec6-11e5-b072-006d8d362ba3.html#axzz45kZzwC6m }}</ref>\n\nIn the case of the Eurozone, the use of [http://bruegel.org/2014/09/t-ltro-variation-on-a-ecbs-theme/ TLTROs] is believed by some economists to provide a legal and administratively tractable means of introducing transfers to households.<ref name=\"bruegel.org\">{{cite web|url=http://bruegel.org/2016/03/helicopter-drops-reloaded/ |title=Helicopter drops reloaded|publisher=breugel.org|author1=H\u00fcttl, Pia |author2=Alvaro Leandro |date=March 14, 2016|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> The economist, Eric Lonergan, argued in 2016 that legal helicopter drops in the Eurozone could be structured via zero coupon, perpetual loans, which all European adult citizens would be eligible to receive. The loans could be administered by eligible commercial banks, and under certain conditions the loans would be net interest income positive to the central bank.<ref>{{cite web|title=Legal helicopter drops in the Eurozone, published on February 24 2016|url=https://www.philosophyofmoney.net/legal-helicopter-drops-in-the-eurozone/}}</ref> This idea was revived in 2019 by [[Frances Coppola]], in her book, The Case for People\u2019s Quantitative Easing, and also by researchers at [[BlackRock]], including Stanley Fischer, and also by the French economist Jean Pisani-Ferry.\n\n== Controversies ==\n\nMany economists would argue that helicopter money, in the form of cash transfers to households, should not be seen as a substitute for fiscal policy. Given the government's borrowing costs are extremely low at close to zero interest rates, conventional fiscal stimulus through tax cuts and infrastructure spending should work. From this perspective, helicopter money is really an insurance policy against the failure of fiscal policy for political, legal or institutional reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mainlymacro.blogspot.co.uk/2016/03/two-related-confusions-about-helicopter.html |title=mainly macro|author=Mainly Macro|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016|date=March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Differences from quantitative easing===\nLike all expansionary [[monetary policy|monetary policies]] in general, [[quantitative easing]] (QE) and helicopter money involves money creation by central banks to expand the money supply. However, the effect on the central bank's balance sheet of helicopter money is different than with QE. Under QE, central banks create reserves by purchasing bonds or other financial assets, conducting an '[[asset swap]]'.<ref name=Grenville2013>{{cite web |last1=Grenville |first1=Stephen |title=Helicopter money |url=https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money |website=VoxEU.org  |publisher=[[Centre for Economic Policy Research]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190920074154/https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money |archivedate=20 September 2019 |date=24 February 2013 |url-status=live |quote=Central banks have no mandate to give money away (they can only exchange one asset for another, as they do in quantitative easing)}}</ref> The swap is reversible. By contrast, with helicopter money, central banks give away the money created, without increasing assets on their balance sheet.\n\nEconomists argue that the effect on expectations is different because helicopter money created would be perceived as 'permanent' \u2013 that is, more irreversible than QE. Economists have pointed out that the effect is not different from a combination of expansionary fiscal policy and expansionary monetary policy conducted at the same time.\n\n===Implications for central bank balance sheets===\nOne of the main concerns with transfers from the central bank directly to the private sector is that in contrast to conventional [[open-market operations]] the central bank does not have an asset corresponding to the base money created. This has implications for the measured equity of the central bank because base money is typically treated as a liability, but it could also constrain the central bank's ability to set interest rates in the future. The accounting treatment of central banks' balance sheets is controversial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.ft.com/economistsforum/2012/06/governments-can-borrow-without-increasing-their-debt/ |title=Governments can borrow without increasing their debt|work=Financial Times|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> Most economists now recognize that the 'capital' of the central bank is not really important.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/pub/pdf/scpwps/ecbwp392.pdf?e7bba27cdd7b653529fc35400ff0a3c0 | title=The Role of Central Bank Capital Revisited | publisher=European Central Bank | date=September 2004 | author=Ulrich Bindseil|author2=Andres Manzanares|author3=Benedict Weller | issn=1725-2806}}</ref> What matters is can whether expansion of base money be reversed in the future, or are there other means to raise interest rates. Various options have been proposed. Oxford professor, Simon Wren-Lewis has suggested that the government pre-commit to providing the Bank of England with bonds if needed. The European Central Bank can, in fact, mandate an increase in its capital, and the introduction of [[tiered reserves]] and [[interest on reserves]] gives central banks an array of tools to protect their own net income and the demand for reserves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philosophyofmoney.net/does-the-central-banks-balance-sheet-matter/ |title=Does the central bank's balance sheet matter?|author=Eric Lonergan|work=Philosophy of Money|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Supporters ==\nFormer chairman of the Federal Reserve [[Ben Bernanke]] is known to be one of the proponents of helicopter money when he gave a speech in November 2002 arguing, in the case of Japan, that \"a money-financed tax cut is essentially equivalent to Milton Friedman's famous 'helicopter drop' of money.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalreserve.gov/boarddocs/Speeches/2002/20021121/default.htm |title=Speech, Bernanke --Deflation-- November 21, 2002|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> In April 2016, Ben Bernanke wrote a blog post arguing that \"such programs may be the best available alternative. It would be premature to rule them out.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brookings.edu/blogs/ben-bernanke/posts/2016/04/11-helicopter-money |title=What tools does the Fed have left? Part 3: Helicopter money|author=Ben S. Bernanke|date=11 April 2016|work=The Brookings Institution|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> Fed chairwoman [[Janet Yellen]] also admitted that helicopter money could be an option in \"extreme situations\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/06/16/news/economy/federal-reserve-janet-yellen-helicopter-money/index.html |title=Janet Yellen: Helicopter money is an option in extreme situations|last=Gillespie|first=Patrick |work=CNNMoney|access-date=2017-11-17}}</ref>\n\nCitigroup Chief Economist [[Willem Buiter]] is also known to be a prominent advocate of the concept.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/business/economists-say-handing-out-cash-could-help-euro-zone-economy-a-1011352.html |title=Economists Say Handing Out Cash Could Help Euro Zone Economy|author=((SPIEGEL ONLINE, Hamburg, Germany))|date=6 January 2015|work=SPIEGEL ONLINE|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> Other proponents include Financial Times' Chief Commentator [[Martin Wolf]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/9bcf0eea-6f98-11e2-b906-00144feab49a.html#axzz2vaE3myVK |title=The case for helicopter money|work=Financial Times|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> Oxford economists [[John Muellbauer]],<ref name=\"voxeu.org\"/> and [[Simon Wren-Lewis]], Economist [[Steve Keen]], the political economist [[Mark Blyth]] of [[Brown University]], Berkeley economics professor and former Treasury advisor, [[Brad DeLong]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/helicopter-money-fiscal-stimulus-by-j--bradford-delong-2016-04 |title=Rescue Helicopters for Stranded Economies|author=J. Bradford DeLong|work=Project Syndicate|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.milkenreview.org/articles/helicopter-money-when-zero-just-isnt-low-enough |title=Helicopter Money: When Zero Just Isn't Low Enough|website=[[Milken Institute]] Review|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref> UCLA economics professor, [[Roger Farmer]], American macro hedge fund manager [[Ray Dalio]], Irish economist and Fund manager [[Eric Lonergan]],<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5EA2nKqcjtg |title=Why the ECB should give money directly to People (Eric Lonergan)|date=8 April 2016|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref> [[Anatole Kaletsky]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/onpoint/central-bankings-final-frontier-by-anatole-kaletsky-2016-05 |title=Central Banking's Final Frontier? by Anatole Kaletsky - Project Syndicate|first=Anatole|last=Kaletsky |date=6 May 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Romain Baeriswyl,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Monetary Policy, Financial Crises, and the Macroeconomy|last=Baeriswyl|first=Romain |date=2017|publisher=Springer, Cham|isbn=9783319562605 |pages=105\u2013121|language=en |doi=10.1007/978-3-319-56261-2_6 |chapter = The Case for the Separation of Money and Credit}}</ref> [[Martin Sandbu]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1dc5b4a8-57da-11e6-9f70-badea1b336d4 |title=Helicopter money: if not now, then when?|last=Sandbu|first=Martin |date=2016|work=Financial Times|access-date=}}</ref>, [[Jean Pisani-Ferry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/europe-next-recession-alternative-policies-by-jean-pisani-ferry-2019-09 |title=How to Ward Off the Next Recession |last=Pisani-Ferry|first=Jean |date=2019-09-30|website=Project Syndicate|language=en|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n\nThe idea also finds support among central bankers. For example, former governor of the Irish central bank [[Patrick Honohan]] said he believes the policy would work while the ECB's chief economist [[Peter Praet]] once said \"All central banks can do it\". The Vice-Governor of the Czech Central Bank [[Mojm\u00edr Hampl]] published a paper in which he writes that \"the idea offers many virtues and advantages compared to other forms of unconventional monetary policy, especially obliterating the need to rely on a complicated transmission mechanism, allowing much easier communication to the public, and boosting consumer confidence when most needed.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mojmir|first=Hampl |last2=Tomas|first2=Havranek |date=2018|title=Central Bank Capital as an Instrument of Monetary Policy|url=https://www.econstor.eu/handle/10419/176828 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBill Gross, Portfolio Manager of the Janus Global Unconstrained Bond Fund also argues for the implementation of a [[basic income]], funded by helicopter drops.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.janus.com/bill-gross-investment-outlook |title=Bill Gross Investment Outlook May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2016/05/04/bill-gross-what-to-do-after-the-robots-take-our-jobs |title=Bill Gross: What to Do After the Robots Take Our Jobs|author=Paul Vigna|work=WSJ|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, prominent central bankers [[Stanley Fischer]] and [[Philipp Hildebrand|Philip Hildebrand]] co-authored a paper published by BlackRock<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackrock.com/us/individual/literature/whitepaper/bii-macro-perspectives-august-2019.pdf |title=Dealing with the next downturn: From unconventional monetary policy to unprecedented policy coordination|last=Stanley Fischer, Elga Bartsch, Jean Boivin, Stanley Fischer, Philipp Hildebrand|date=August 2019|website=[[BlackRock]] Institute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> in which they propose a form of helicopter money.\n\n==Critics==\n[[File:Hyperinflation in Germany in 1923.jpg|thumb|Hyperinflation in Germany in 1923]]\n\n===Inflationary effect===\nIn the past the idea had been dismissed because it was thought that it would inevitably lead to [[hyperinflation]].{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nConsequently, a range of concerns include the fact that helicopter money would undermine trust in the currency (which ultimately would lead to hyperinflation). This concern was particularly voiced by German Economist (and former Chief Economist at the ECB) [[Otmar Issing]] in a paper written in 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://safe-frankfurt.de/fileadmin/user_upload/editor_common/Policy_Center/Issing_Helicopter-Money.pdf | title=Die letzte Waffe \u2013 Helicopter Money? | publisher=SAFE | date=7 February 2015 | author=Otmar Issing | type=Press Article}}</ref> Later in 2016, he declared in an interview: \"I think the whole idea of the helicopter money is downright devastating. For this is nothing more than a declaration of bankruptcy of the monetary policy\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/ex-ezb-chefvolkswirt-otmar-issing-warnt-vor-helikoptergeld-14141309.html#GEPC;s3 |title=Ex-EZB-Chefvolkswirt Otmar Issing warnt vor \"Helikoptergeld\"|date=23 March 2016|author=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung GmbH|work=FAZ.NET|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> [[Richard Koo]] makes a similar argument<ref>{{cite web | url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2016/07/27/2170980/koo-on-why-helicopter-money-just-wont-work/ | title=Koo on why helicopter money just won't work | work=FT Alphaville | date=27 July 2016 | author=Izabella Kaminska}}</ref> when saying \"if such envelopes arrived day after day, the entire country would quickly fall into a panic as people lose all sense of what their currency is worth.\"\n\nThis clashes with the argument that people would not spend much of the money they receive (and therefore helicopter money cannot be inflationary).\n\n=== Would helicopter money be spent? ===\nSeveral prominent economist such as central banker [[Raghuram Rajan]] are against helicopter money on the grounds that helicopter money would be ineffective because people would not spend the money.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/john-cassidy/raghuram-rajan-and-the-dangers-of-helicopter-money |title=Raghuram Rajan and the Dangers of Helicopter Money|first=John|last=Cassidy |date=13 May 2016|publisher=|via=www.newyorker.com}}</ref> In response, Lord [[Adair Turner]] argues: \"Money financed deficits will always stimulate nominal demand. By comparison debt finance deficits might do so, but might not.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.ineteconomics.org/ideas-papers/research-papers/why-a-future-tax-on-bank-credit-intermediation-does-not-offset-the-stimulative-effect-of-money-finance-deficits |title=Why a future tax on bank credit intermediation does not offset the stimulative effect of money finance deficits|website=Institute for New Economic Thinking}}</ref>\n\nContradicting this argument, several surveys conducted in the Eurozone concluded however that between 30 and 55% of the distributed money would be spent by households, in effect resulting in a boost of around 2% of GDP.<ref>[http://www.astelloncapital.com/documents/FG/astellon/news/519100_Astellon_Notes_-_Helicopter_Money.pdf Helicopter Money \u2013 Let It Rain?], Astellon Capital, June 2016</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ezonomics.com/ing_international_surveys/helicopter-money-2016/ |title=Helicopter Money 2016|last=eZonomics|first=ING|website=eZonomics by ING|language=en|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Djuric|first=Uros |last2=Neugart|first2=Michael| date=2016-12-17|title=Helicopter Money: Survey Evidence on Expectation Formation and Consumption Behavior|ssrn=2893008|location=Rochester, NY}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnb.nl/en/news/dnb-publications/dnb-working-papers-series/dnb-working-papers/working-papers-2016/dnb350283.jsp |title=Will helicopter money be spent? New evidence - De Nederlandsche Bank|author1=Maarten van Rooij | author2=Jakob de Haan|date=2017|website=www.dnb.nl|language=en|access-date=2017-04-10}}</ref>\n\n===\"There is no such thing as a free lunch\"===\n\nAnother range of critics involve the idea that there cannot be such thing as \"free money\" or as economists say \"[[there is no such thing as a free lunch]]\". This criticism was notably expressed by Bank for International Settlements researchers Claudio Borio, Piti Disyatat, Anna Zabai.,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money-illusion-free-lunch |title=Helicopter money: The illusion of a free lunch|first1=Claudio|last1=Borio |first2=Piti|last2=Disyatat |first3=Anna|last3=Zabai |date=24 May 2016|publisher=}}</ref> who claimed that helicopter drops to citizens would necessarily involve for the central bank to pay interests on the extra reserves being supplied.\n\nIn a response, the former IMF economist [[Biagio Bossone]] challenges the later assumption<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economonitor.com/blog/2016/06/why-helicopter-money-is-a-free-lunch/ |title=Why Helicopter Money is a \"Free Lunch\" - EconoMonitor|website=www.economonitor.com}}</ref> and argues that \"helicopter money is a 'free lunch' in the simple sense that, if it works and succeeds in closing the output gap, people won\u2019t have to repay it through higher taxes or undesired (above optimal) inflation.\"\n\n===Legality===\n\nOther critics claim helicopter money would be outside of the mandate of central banks, because it would \"blur the lines between fiscal policy and monetary policy\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/inter/date/2016/html/sp160926_3.en.html |title=Interview with S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung|last=Bank|first=European Central|website=European Central Bank|language=en|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref> mainly because helicopter money would involve 'fiscal effects' which is traditionally the role of governments to decide on. However advocates of helicopter money such as Eric Lonergan and Simon Wren-Lewis invalidate this argument by observing that standard monetary policy tools also have fiscal effects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mainlymacro.blogspot.be/2016/05/helicopter-money-and-fiscal-policy.html |title=Helicopter money and fiscal policy|website=mainlymacro.blogspot.be|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.philosophyofmoney.net/the-distinction-between-monetary-and-fiscal-policy/ |title=The distinction between monetary and fiscal policy - Philosophy of Money|date=2016-04-03|newspaper=Philosophy of Money|access-date=2017-02-11|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe European Central Bank explained, in a letter to MEP [[Jon\u00e1s Fern\u00e1ndez]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/pub/pdf/other/161129letter_fernandez.en_en.pdf |title=Letter from ECB President to Jon\u00e1s Fern\u00e1ndez|last=|first= |date=29 November 2016|website=European Central Bank|url-status=live|archive-url= |archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, that \"legal complexities could still arise if the scheme could be seen as the ECB financing an obligation of the public sector vis-\u00e0-vis third parties, as this would also violate the prohibition of monetary financing\". However this refers to a very unlikely and undesirable case where helicopter money payments by the central bank would substitute to welfare payments (which are a liability of governments).\n\n===Accounting issues===\n\n[[Bundesbank]] president [[Jens Weidmann]] also voiced opposition against helicopter money, arguing it would \"tear gaping holes in central bank balance sheets. Ultimately, it would be down to the euro-area countries, and thus the taxpayer, to shoulder the costs because central banks would be unprofitable for quite some time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesbank.de/Redaktion/EN/Interviews/2016_01_29_weidmann_funke_mediengruppe.html |title=Deutsche Bundesbank - Interviews - \"Helicopter money would tear gaping holes in central bank balance sheets\"|date=21 March 2016|accessdate=5 May 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160518205952/http://www.bundesbank.de/Redaktion/EN/Interviews/2016_01_29_weidmann_funke_mediengruppe.html |archivedate=18 May 2016}}</ref> The [[National Bank of Belgium|National bank of Belgium]] also released a paper making a similar argument.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbb.be/en/articles/helicopter-money-and-debt-financed-fiscal-stimulus-one-and-same-thing |title=Helicopter money and debt-financed fiscal stimulus: one and the same thing? |website=www.nbb.be |language=en|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Threat against central bank independence ===\nEndra Curren and Ben Holland of Bloomberg stated \"That type of stimulus[Helicopter Money] used to be [[taboo]], in part because it risks eroding the independence from politics that monetary policy makers prize [...] History is littered with cautionary tales in which blurring the lines between central bank and Treasury coffers led to runaway inflation.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-09-22/a-long-despised-and-risky-economic-doctrine-is-now-a-hot-idea |title=A Long-Despised and Risky Economic Doctrine Is Now a Hot Idea|date=2019-09-22 |work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-03-16|language=en}}</ref><ref name=Reichlin2019>{{cite web |last1=Reichlin |first1=Lucrezia |last2=Turner |first2=Adair |last3=Woodford |first3=Michael |title=Helicopter money as a policy option |url=https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money-policy-option |website=VoxEU.org |publisher=[[Centre for Economic Policy Research]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20191224180125/https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money-policy-option |archivedate=24 December 2019 |date=23 September 2019 |url-status=live |quote=Helicopter money is a form of fiscal policy. The question arises of whether it is the central bank, the Treasury or both in coordination that should implement it. This has the potential to threaten the principle of central bank independence or at least it may force us to reconsider the rules that govern the relation between Treasury and central banks today}}</ref>{{Empty section|date=December 2018}}\n\n==In the Eurozone==\nOn March 10, 2016, the idea became increasingly popular in Europe after [[Mario Draghi]] the President of the [[European Central Bank]], said in a press conference that he found the concept 'very interesting'.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zbb--KxTjWc |title=Mario Draghi: 'Helicopter money is a very interesting concept'|date=10 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=5 May 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref> This statement was followed by another statement from the ECB's [[Peter Praet]] who declared:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/inter/date/2016/html/sp160318.en.html |title=Interview with La Repubblica|author=European Central Bank|work=European Central Bank|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>\"Yes, all central banks can do it. You can issue currency and you distribute it to people. That\u2019s helicopter money. Helicopter money is giving to the people part of the net present value of your future seigniorage, the profit you make on the future banknotes. The question is, if and when is it opportune to make recourse to that sort of instrument which is really an extreme sort of instrument.\"</blockquote>\n[[File:QE_for_People_European_parliament.jpg|thumb|Conference on \"QE for People\" organised at the European parliament by [[Positive Money]] (17 February 2016)]]\nIn 2015, a European campaign called \"Quantitative Easing for People\" was launched<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fd.nl/economie-politiek/1129670/handtekeningenactie-voor-helikoptergeld |title=Cookiewall - Het Financieele Dagblad|website=fd.nl}}</ref> and is effectively promoting the concept of Helicopter Money, along with other proposals for 'Green QE' and 'Strategic QE' which are other types of monetary financing operations by central banks involving public investment programmes. The campaign was supported by 20 organisations across Europe and more than 116 economists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qe4people.eu |title=QE for People \u2022 A Rescue Plan for the Eurozone|work=Quantitative Easing for People|accessdate=5 May 2016|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180411122417/http://www.qe4people.eu/ |archive-date=11 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\nOn June 17, 2016, 18 Members of the European Parliament (including [[Philippe Lamberts]], [[Paul Tang (politician)|Paul Tang]] and [[Fabio De Masi]]) signed an open letter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qe4people.eu/open_letter_to_the_ecb |title=MEPs want the ECB to look at helicopter money|publisher=}}</ref> calling on the ECB to \"provide evidence-based analysis of the potential effects of the alternative proposals mentioned above, and to clarify under which conditions their implementation would be legal.\" If it doesn't consider alternatives to QE, MEPs fear the ECB would leave itself \u201cunprepared for a deterioration in economic conditions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/c5d08c5c-339c-11e6-bda0-04585c31b153.html |title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, a survey showed that 54% Europeans think helicopter money would be a good idea, with only 14% against.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.qe4people.eu/majority_europeans_are_in_favour_of_helicopter_money |title=54% of Europeans are in favour of 'helicopter money'|newspaper=Quantitative Easing for People|access-date=2016-10-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, politicians, civil society organisations and economists debated issuing helicopter money as a response to the [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Europe|coronavirus pandemic in Europe]].<ref name=Gali2020>{{cite web |last1=Gal\u00ed |first1=Jordi |title=Helicopter money: The time is now |url=https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money-time-now |website=VoxEU.org |publisher=[[Centre for Economic Policy Research]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200323175324/https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money-time-now |archivedate=23 March 2020 |date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stevis-Gridneff |first1=Matina |last2=Ewing |first2=Jack |title=Will \u2018Helicopter Money\u2019 and the \u2018Big Bazooka\u2019 Help Rescue Europe? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/business/EU-European-Central-Bank-economy-covid.html |website=The New York Times |date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/finanzen/geldpolitik/massnahmen-gegen-die-krise-bargeld-fuer-die-buerger-oekonomen-loben-das-helikoptergeld/25723120.html|title=Ma\u00dfnahmen gegen die Krise: Bargeld f\u00fcr die B\u00fcrger: \u00d6konomen loben das Helikoptergeld|website=www.handelsblatt.com|language=de|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.positivemoney.eu/2020/03/helicopter-money-covid19-report/|title=Report: Helicopter money as a response to the COVID-19 crisis|last=Jourdan|first=Stanislas|date=2020-03-30|website=Positive Money Europe|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== In USA ==\nIn 2020, the US legislative system debated issuing two times a $1,000 check to each eligible adult citizen, described by media as 'Helicopter Money', as a response to the [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_United_States|US coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The global markets barely budge as helicopter-money measures achieve lift-off |url=https://fortune.com/2020/03/19/global-markets-calm-helicopter-money/ |website=Fortune |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Trump seeks stimulus package potentially worth more than $1 trillion, including direct payments to Americans |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/17/mnuchin-says-trump-administration-is-looking-to-get-cash-to-americans-immediately.html |website=CNBC |language=en |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> However, this practice cannot be considered as 'Helicopter Money' as long as this money distribution is financed by the State ([[debt]]) and not by [[central bank]] money printing (monetary expansion).\n\n== In Japan ==\nIn a meeting with Japanese Prime Minister [[Shinzo Abe]] and [[Bank of Japan]]'s [[Haruhiko Kuroda]] in July 2016 it was widely reported<ref>[http://www.thefiscaltimes.com/Columns/2016/07/12/Can-Helicopter-Ben-Bernanke-Save-Japan Can 'Helicopter Ben Bernanke' Save Japan?], Retrieved July 28, 2016.</ref> that former Federal Reserve chairman Ben Bernanke advised the policy of monetizing more government debt created to fund infrastructure projects,<ref name=bl-20160727>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-27/abe-s-unusual-stimulus-announcement-may-be-directed-at-the-boj |title=Abe's Unusual Stimulus Unveiling May Be Directed at the BOJ |author=Enda Curran, Toru Fujioka |publisher=Bloomberg |date=27 July 2016 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> ostensibly as a way to drop \"Helicopter Money\" on Japan to stimulate the economy and halt deflation in Japan.  Financial markets began to front-run this stimulus effort days before it was announced when accounts of Bernanke's visit to Japan were first reported.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\nLater in the month the [[Bank of Japan]] ongoing review of its monetary stimulus program was reported to be considering policies somewhat similar to \"Helicopter Money\", such as selling 50-year or perpetual bonds.<ref name=jt-20160731>{{cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/07/31/business/economy-business/helicopter-money-talk-takes-flight-bank-japan-runs-runway/#.V55ptaIbiUk |title='Helicopter money' talk takes flight as Bank of Japan runs out of runway |author=Stanley White |newspaper=The Japan Times |agency=Reuters |date=31 July 2016 |accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Popular Culture==\nComedy heavy metal band [[Nanowar of Steel]] cited the helicopter drop monetary policy in their financial-epic-metal song \"Tooth Fairy\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CzvQxQYKO88 Nanowar of Steel Tooth Fairy - Youtube video] </ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[People's Quantitative Easing]]\n* [[Monetary policy]]\n* [[Universal Basic Income]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2016/581970/EPRS_BRI(2016)581970_EN.pdf Helicopter money: A cure for what ails the euro area?], European Parliamentary Research Service, April 2016\n* [http://willembuiter.com/helifinal.pdf Helicopter Money: Why it works - Always], Willem Buiter, 2014\n* [http://bruegel.org/2016/03/helicopter-drops-reloaded/ Helicopter Money reloaded], Bruegel, 2016\n* [http://positivemoney.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Recovery-in-the-Eurozone-FINAL-WEB-READY-2015-12-11.pdf Recovery in the Eurozone: using money creation to Stimulate the economy], Frank van Lerven, 2015\n* [http://mainlymacro.blogspot.fr/2012/10/what-do-people-mean-by-helicopter-money.html What do people mean by helicopter money?], Simon Wren-Lewis, 2012\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160804004646/http://www.fvs-ri.com/files/better_monetary_system.pdf From Zirp, Nirp, QE, and helicopter money to a better monetary system], Thomas Mayer, 2016\n* [https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/qe4people/pages/106/attachments/original/1475528559/Citizens_Monetary_Dividend.pdf?1475528559 Citizens' Monetary Dividend \u2013 Upgrading the ECB's Toolkit], Stan Jourdan and Eric Lonergan, 2016\n* [https://voxeu.org/article/helicopter-money-views-leading-economists Helicopter money: Views of leading economists]. [[Centre for Economic Policy Research]], April 2016\n\n{{Portal bar|Business and economics}}\n\n[[Category:Operations of central banks]]\n[[Category:Monetary policy]]\n", "name_user": "Jojojava", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIn Japan", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helicopter_money"}
{"title_page": "Malcolm Reynolds", "text_new": "{{Infobox character\n| colour             = #fc9\n| name               = Malcolm Reynolds\n| series             = [[Firefly (TV series)|Firefly]]\n| image              = [[Image:MalReynoldsFirefly.JPG|250px|Malcolm Reynolds]]\n| caption            = Nathan Fillion as Malcolm Reynolds\n| first              = \"[[Serenity (Firefly episode)|Serenity]]\" (2002)\n| last               = ''[[Serenity (2005 film)|Serenity]]'' (2005) \n| creator            = [[Joss Whedon]]\n| portrayer          = [[Nathan Fillion]]\n| nickname           = Mal, Captain, Captain Tight Pants (Kaylee)\n| occupation         = Captain of ''[[Serenity (Firefly vessel)|Serenity]]''\n| spouse             = [[List of characters in the Firefly universe#Saffron|\"Saffron\"]]\n| gender             = Male\n| relatives          = Unnamed mother\n| lbl21               = Homeworld\n| data21              = Shadow\n}}\n'''Malcolm''' \"'''Mal'''\" '''Reynolds''' is a [[fictional character]] and the [[protagonist]] of the [[Firefly (franchise)|''Firefly'' franchise]]. Mal is played by actor [[Nathan Fillion]] in the 2002 [[TV series]] [[Firefly (TV series)|''Firefly'']] and the 2005 film ''[[Serenity (2005 film)|Serenity]]''. In the series, Mal is a former [[Browncoat]] [[sergeant]] and the captain of the [[Serenity (Firefly vessel)|\"''Firefly''-class\" spaceship ''Serenity'']]. The character was named #18 in ''[[TV Guide]]''{{'s}} Greatest Sci-Fi Legends list in 2004.<ref name=\"legend\">{{cite web |url=http://whedonesque.com/comments/4511 |title=Captain Mal Reynolds features in '25 Greatest Sci-fi legends' list |website=Whedonesque.com |date=July 27, 2004 |author=Simon |accessdate=July 16, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Production details==\nConceived by [[Joss Whedon]], the character Malcolm Reynolds was the only definite character he had in mind when formulating the ensemble cast. He wanted a hero, but not a hero in the classic sense; someone that is \"everything that a hero is not.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2010/03/the-10-greatest-anti-heroes-5-malcolm-reynolds.html |title=The 10 Greatest Anti-Heroes: #5 Malcolm Reynolds |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |date=March 17, 2010 |accessdate=October 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the proposed pilot, Mal was much darker and considerably more closed-off. Fox network executives objected, and asked that Mal be \"lightened up\". For the second episode (\"[[The Train Job]]\"), Whedon created a more \"jolly\" Mal Reynolds.<ref>Whedon, ''Train Job: Director's Commentary,'' Track 1</ref>\n\nFillion shares his view on the motivations of the character he portrayed. Mal has lost so much that each character in the crew he has gathered on ''Serenity'' represents an aspect of himself he no longer has. \"In Wash, he has a lust for life and a sense of humor he's lost. In Jayne, he has selfishness. In Book, he has spirituality. In Kaylee, he has innocence. Everybody represents a facet of himself that he has lost and that's why he keeps them close and safe, and yet at arm's length.\"<ref name=\"FFC26\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nThe role was originally written for ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (TV series)|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'' co-star [[Nicholas Brendon]] (who played [[Xander Harris]]);<ref>Q&A with Nicholas Brendan&nbsp;\u2014 Supanova Convention in Sydney, Australia - 13 October 2007, also Q&A with Nicholas Brendan - Armageddon Expo in Melbourne, Australia - 23 October 2011.{{better source|date=April 2018}}</ref> however, the shooting schedule conflicted with his commitment to ''Buffy''.\n\nWhedon approached Nathan Fillion to play the lead, and after explaining the premise and showing Fillion the treatment for the pilot, Fillion was eager for the role.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whedon.info/article.php3?id_article=1531&img= |title=Interview with Nathan Fillion&nbsp;\u2014 Dreamwatch Magazine 107 |website=Whedon.info |date=September 9, 2003 |accessdate=July 11, 2006}}</ref> Fillion was called back several times to read for the part before he was cast. He noted that \"It was really thrilling. It was my first lead and I was pretty nervous, but I really wanted that part and I wanted to tell those stories.\"<ref name=\"FFC26\">Whedon, ''Firefly Companion, Vol 1'', p.26.</ref>\n\n===Costume design===\nLos Angeles prop shop Applied Effects was approached by Randy Erikson to create Mal's main gun, a \"Moses Brothers Self-Defense Engine Frontier Model B\",<ref name=\"scifi\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.scifi.com/sfw/cool/sfw17440.html |title=Official Malcolm Reynolds Stunt Pistol |first=Sean |last=Huxter |website=[[Scifi.com]] |date=October 15, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071130182729/http://www.scifi.com/sfw/cool/sfw17440.html |archivedate=November 30, 2007}}</ref> and gave them a week and a half. Erikson provided a foamcore conceptual mockup and the base guns, one of which was a five-shot .38 [[caliber]] [[Taurus Model 85]] revolver. Erikson researched [[American Civil War]]-era revolvers for inspiration and the final mockup had a brass or bronze look, with the revolver a little elongated. The biggest challenge was masking the shape of the original revolver and still keeping it operable.<ref>Whedon, ''Firefly Companion, Vol 1'', pp.79-80.</ref>\n\nOn the TV series ''Firefly'', a cast [[bronze]] pistol was used, but for the film ''Serenity'', a more detailed replica was created which had moving [[firearm action|action]] and a [[Blank (cartridge)#Applications|blank pistol]] hidden inside, so that it could be fired in [[close-up]]s. Since this version was quite heavy, a [[resin]] replica was also constructed, which in addition to being less tiring for the actors to carry, could be thrown or dropped with less fear of injury.<ref name=\"quant\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.quantummechanix.com/IN%20THE%20WORKS/4C9CB708-01B9-4E9F-A5F7-3FCE0DED9598.html |title=The Metal Mal Hero Pistol Replica |website=Quantummechanix.com |date=September 30, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210062342/http://www.quantummechanix.com/IN%20THE%20WORKS/4C9CB708-01B9-4E9F-A5F7-3FCE0DED9598.html |archivedate=December 10, 2007}}</ref> Nonfunctional replicas of the gun are commercially available for [[fan (person)|fans]] and [[Collecting|collectors]].<ref name=\"scifi\"/><ref name=\"quant\"/>\n\nGBB Custom Gunleather was tasked with creating Mal's gun holster, which was made out of oak-tanned carving leather.<ref>Whedon, ''Firefly Companion, Vol 1'', p.81.</ref> The character's coat, a relic of his time as a [[Browncoat]], was a collaboration between ''Firefly'' costume designer [[Shawna Trpcic]] and Jonathan A. Logan, a leather artist. Trpcic sketched her idea and a cloth mockup was created before the final was made with domestic-farmed deerskin. The cuffs are actually the sleeves folded back, evoking the style of Oriental robes with their silk linings. Two coats were made for the character, one called \"Number 1\" coat and another called \"The Hero\" coat. The Number 1 coat's bullet hole is drawn in, while The Hero version has a detailed cut and sewn repair.<ref>Whedon, ''Firefly Companion, Vol 1'', p.83.</ref> As with the gun, replicas of Malcolm Reynolds' coat have also been made available commercially for fans.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://abbyshot.blogspot.com/2009/11/browncoat-launched-aim-to-misbehave.html  |title=The Malcolm Reynolds Browncoat Replica |website=AbbyShot Blog |date=November 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Character biography==\nMalcolm's main mission is to keep his crew alive and to keep his ship flying. As ''Firefly'' writer Tim Minear stated in an interview: \"It's just about getting by. That's always been the mission statement of what the show is&nbsp;\u2014 getting by.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://tv.zap2it.com/tveditorial/tve_main/1,1002,271%7c78704%7c1%7c,00.html\n |title       = Fox's 'Firefly' Keeps the Lights On\n |website     = Zap2it.com\n |first       = Kate\n |last        = O'Hare\n |date        = October 31, 2002\n |accessdate  = July 4, 2006\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070526111034/http://tv.zap2it.com/tveditorial/tve_main/1,1002,271%7C78704%7C1%7C,00.html\n |archivedate = May 26, 2007\n }}</ref>  In ''Serenity'', Mal says of himself: \"[If the] Wind blows Northerly, I go North.\"<ref name=\"Whedon, Serenity, DVD\">Whedon, ''Serenity'', DVD.</ref>\n\nMal was raised by his mother and \"about 40 hands\" on a ranch on the planet Shadow.<ref>Whedon, ''Firefly: the complete series: \"Our Mrs. Reynolds\"''</ref> Though Mal usually seems more practical than intellectual, he occasionally surprises his friends by displaying familiarity with disparate literature varying from the works of [[Xiang Yu]]<ref>Whedon, ''Firefly: the complete series: \"War Stories\"''</ref> to [[The Rime of the Ancient Mariner|poems]]<ref name=\"Whedon, Serenity, DVD\"/> by [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]], though he has no idea \"who\" [[Mona Lisa]] is.\n\nMal volunteered for the [[Browncoat|Independents]] army during the Unification War against the [[Alliance (Firefly)|Alliance]], gaining the rank of sergeant during that time. His loyal second-in-command [[Zoe Washburne|Zoe]] was by his side for most of the war, surviving many dangerous conflicts with him. The show mentions three such battles, including the Battle of Du-Khang in 2510 (featured in \"[[The Message (Firefly)|The Message]]\") and a long winter campaign in New Kashmir (as told by Zoe in \"[[War Stories (Firefly episode)|War Stories]]\") where he commanded a platoon. Mal was also involved in the ground campaign during the Battle of Sturges (as seen in the comic book ''[[Serenity: Those Left Behind]]''), which according to [[List of minor characters in Firefly#Badger|Badger]] was the \"bloodiest and shortest battle in all the war\", although Mal considers it a distant second. Mal fought in many more battles, but the turning point for him and the Independents came with their physical and emotional defeat at the ''Battle of Serenity Valley'' on the planet [[List of Firefly planets and moons#Hera|Hera]]. On-screen information in ''Serenity'' shows him to have been attached to the 57th Overlanders Brigade; in the series pilot, Badger calls it the \"Balls and Bayonets Brigade\", though it is unclear whether this was a disparaging nickname coined by Badger himself or the actual unit [[sobriquet]] (a deleted scene in ''Serenity'' marks it as the actual unit nickname.  It is unknown if the deleted scene can be considered canon or not).\n\nAfter the war, Mal acquired his own ship, a derelict 03-K64 ''Firefly''-class transport. Mal named the ship ''Serenity'' after the Battle of Serenity Valley, the decisive battle of the Unification War. Flashbacks in the episode, \"[[Out of Gas (Firefly episode)|Out of Gas]]\", indicate that Mal immediately recruited Zoe as his first mate, followed shortly by Wash and (temporary) engineer, Bester. While Wash would remain with the crew and eventually pursue Zoe romantically, Mal fires Bester for incompetence and inappropriate behavior, as he caught Bester having sex with a woman (Kaylee Frye) in the Engine room; however, after she correctly identified the problem and fixed the ship, Mal offered Bester's job to her instead. Kaylee accepted the offer and became a central member of the crew. At an unspecified time later, Mal encountered Jayne Cobb while working a job; after assessing his tracking abilities and willingness to work less-than-legal jobs (at gunpoint), Mal offers Jayne a cut of their take to switch sides, which he promptly does by betraying his former comrades. Inara Serra responds to Mal's advertisement for having an open shuttle for rent, and the two agree to a partnership, allowing Inara privacy and mobility, while Mal receives rent and some respectability from her presence.\n\n==Reception==\nFillion won the \"Cinescape Genre Face of the Future Award&nbsp;\u2014 Male\" award by the Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy & Horror Films, USA for his role as Malcolm Reynolds. Fillion also won the [[SyFy Genre Awards]] in 2006 for ''Best Actor/Television'' and was runner-up for ''Best Actor/Movie''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://syfyportal.com/news.php?id=2895 |title=SyfyPortal Awards |accessdate=October 8, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061107100529/http://www.syfyportal.com/news.php?id=2895 |archivedate=November 7, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe character was named #18 in ''[[TV Guide]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s \"Greatest Sci-fi legends\" list in 2004.<ref name=\"legend\" /> In 2008, ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' ranked Mal as #34 on their list of the 100 Greatest Movie Characters.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=51 |title=The 100 Greatest Movie Characters |magazine=Empire |accessdate=June 11, 2009}}</ref> In 2011, ''[[SFX (magazine)|SFX Magazine]]'' voted Mal Reynolds #1 on their Top 100 Sci-Fi icons of the century.\n\nIn her review of the film ''Serenity'' for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Manohla Dargis]] had this to say about the character and Nathan Fillion: \"Mal is no [[Neo (The Matrix)|Neo]] redux; he's closer to [[Indiana Jones]], if absent [[Harrison Ford]]'s rakishly handsome looks and star magnetism. Like the rest of the cast, Mr. Fillion is a charming performer, but he borrows rather than owns the screen, which dovetails with Mr. Whedon's modest aspirations for this film.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Dargis |first=Manohla |date=September 30, 2005 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/30/movies/scruffy-space-cowboys-fighting-their-failings.html |title=Scruffy Space Cowboys Fighting Their Failings |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|last=Whedon|first=Joss | title=Firefly: The Official Visual Companion, Volume 1 | publisher=Titan Books | location=UK | year=2006 | isbn=1-84576-314-9}}\n*{{cite book | last=Whedon | first=Joss | title=Serenity: The Official Visual Companion | publisher=Titan Books | location=UK | year=2005 | isbn=1-84576-082-4 | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/serenityofficial0000whed }}\n*{{cite video |date=December 9, 2003 |title=The Complete Series: Commentary for \"Serenity\" |people=Whedon, Joss |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}\n*{{cite video |date=December 9, 2003 |title=Firefly (The Series) |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}\n\n{{Firefly}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reynolds, Malcolm}}\n[[Category:Firefly (TV series) characters]]\n[[Category:Science fiction film characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional ship captains]]\n[[Category:Fictional mercenaries]]\n[[Category:Fictional sergeants]]\n[[Category:Fictional smugglers]]\n[[Category:Space pirates]]\n[[Category:Western (genre) characters]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2002]]\n[[Category:Atheism in television]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox character\n| colour             = #fc9\n| name               = Malcolm Reynolds\n| series             = [[Firefly (TV series)|Firefly]]\n| image              = [[Image:MalReynoldsFirefly.JPG|250px|Malcolm Reynolds]]\n| caption            = Nathan Fillion as Malcolm Reynolds\n| first              = \"[[Serenity (Firefly episode)|Serenity]]\" (2002)\n| last               = ''[[Serenity (2005 film)|Serenity]]'' (2005) \n| creator            = [[Joss Whedon]]\n| portrayer          = [[Nathan Fillion]]\n| nickname           = Mal, Captain, Captain Tight Pants (Kaylee)\n| occupation         = Captain of ''[[Serenity (Firefly vessel)|Serenity]]''\n| spouse             = [[List of characters in the Firefly universe#Saffron|\"Saffron\"]]\n| gender             = Male\n| relatives          = Unnamed mother\n| lbl21               = Homeworld\n| data21              = Shadow\n}}\n'''Malcolm''' \"'''Mal'''\" '''Reynolds''' is a [[fictional character]] and the [[protagonist]] of the [[Firefly (franchise)|''Firefly'' franchise]]. Mal is played by actor [[Nathan Fillion]] in the 2002 [[TV series]] [[Firefly (TV series)|''Firefly'']] and the 2005 film ''[[Serenity (2005 film)|Serenity]]''. In the series, Mal is a former [[Browncoat]] [[sergeant]] and the captain of the [[Serenity (Firefly vessel)|\"''Firefly''-class\" spaceship ''Serenity'']]. The character was named #18 in ''[[TV Guide]]''{{'s}} Greatest Sci-Fi Legends list in 2004.<ref name=\"legend\">{{cite web |url=http://whedonesque.com/comments/4511 |title=Captain Mal Reynolds features in '25 Greatest Sci-fi legends' list |website=Whedonesque.com |date=July 27, 2004 |author=Simon |accessdate=July 16, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Production details==\nConceived by [[Joss Whedon]], the character Malcolm Reynolds was the only definite character he had in mind when formulating the ensemble cast. He wanted a hero, but not a hero in the classic sense; someone that is \"everything that a hero is not.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2010/03/the-10-greatest-anti-heroes-5-malcolm-reynolds.html |title=The 10 Greatest Anti-Heroes: #5 Malcolm Reynolds |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |date=March 17, 2010 |accessdate=October 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the proposed pilot, Mal was much darker and considerably more closed-off. Fox network executives objected, and asked that Mal be \"lightened up\". For the second episode (\"[[The Train Job]]\"), Whedon created a more \"jolly\" Mal Reynolds.<ref>Whedon, ''Train Job: Director's Commentary,'' Track 1</ref>\n\nFillion shares his view on the motivations of the character he portrayed. Mal has lost so much that each character in the crew he has gathered on ''Serenity'' represents an aspect of himself he no longer has. \"In Wash, he has a lust for life and a sense of humor he's lost. In Jayne, he has selfishness. In Book, he has spirituality. In Kaylee, he has innocence. Everybody represents a facet of himself that he has lost and that's why he keeps them close and safe, and yet at arm's length.\"<ref name=\"FFC26\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nThe role was originally written for ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (TV series)|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'' co-star [[Nicholas Brendon]] (who played [[Xander Harris]]);<ref>Q&A with Nicholas Brendan&nbsp;\u2014 Supanova Convention in Sydney, Australia - 13 October 2007, also Q&A with Nicholas Brendan - Armageddon Expo in Melbourne, Australia - 23 October 2011.{{better source|date=April 2018}}</ref> however, the shooting schedule conflicted with his commitment to ''Buffy''.\n\nWhedon approached Nathan Fillion to play the lead, and after explaining the premise and showing Fillion the treatment for the pilot, Fillion was eager for the role.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whedon.info/article.php3?id_article=1531&img= |title=Interview with Nathan Fillion&nbsp;\u2014 Dreamwatch Magazine 107 |website=Whedon.info |date=September 9, 2003 |accessdate=July 11, 2006}}</ref> Fillion was called back several times to read for the part before he was cast. He noted that \"It was really thrilling. It was my first lead and I was pretty nervous, but I really wanted that part and I wanted to tell those stories.\"<ref name=\"FFC26\">Whedon, ''Firefly Companion, Vol 1'', p.26.</ref>\n\n===Costume design===\nLos Angeles prop shop Applied Effects was approached by Randy Erikson to create Mal's main gun, a \"Moses Brothers Self-Defense Engine Frontier Model B\",<ref name=\"scifi\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.scifi.com/sfw/cool/sfw17440.html |title=Official Malcolm Reynolds Stunt Pistol |first=Sean |last=Huxter |website=[[Scifi.com]] |date=October 15, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071130182729/http://www.scifi.com/sfw/cool/sfw17440.html |archivedate=November 30, 2007}}</ref> and gave them a week and a half. Erikson provided a foamcore conceptual mockup and the base guns, one of which was a five-shot .38 [[caliber]] [[Taurus Model 85]] revolver. Erikson researched [[American Civil War]]-era revolvers for inspiration and the final mockup had a brass or bronze look, with the revolver a little elongated. The biggest challenge was masking the shape of the original revolver and still keeping it operable.<ref>Whedon, ''Firefly Companion, Vol 1'', pp.79-80.</ref>\n\nOn the TV series ''Firefly'', a cast [[bronze]] pistol was used, but for the film ''Serenity'', a more detailed replica was created which had moving [[firearm action|action]] and a [[Blank (cartridge)#Applications|blank pistol]] hidden inside, so that it could be fired in [[close-up]]s. Since this version was quite heavy, a [[resin]] replica was also constructed, which in addition to being less tiring for the actors to carry, could be thrown or dropped with less fear of injury.<ref name=\"quant\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.quantummechanix.com/IN%20THE%20WORKS/4C9CB708-01B9-4E9F-A5F7-3FCE0DED9598.html |title=The Metal Mal Hero Pistol Replica |website=Quantummechanix.com |date=September 30, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210062342/http://www.quantummechanix.com/IN%20THE%20WORKS/4C9CB708-01B9-4E9F-A5F7-3FCE0DED9598.html |archivedate=December 10, 2007}}</ref> Nonfunctional replicas of the gun are commercially available for [[fan (person)|fans]] and [[Collecting|collectors]].<ref name=\"scifi\"/><ref name=\"quant\"/>\n\nGBB Custom Gunleather was tasked with creating Mal's gun holster, which was made out of oak-tanned carving leather.<ref>Whedon, ''Firefly Companion, Vol 1'', p.81.</ref> The character's coat, a relic of his time as a [[Browncoat]], was a collaboration between ''Firefly'' costume designer [[Shawna Trpcic]] and Jonathan A. Logan, a leather artist. Trpcic sketched her idea and a cloth mockup was created before the final was made with domestic-farmed deerskin. The cuffs are actually the sleeves folded back, evoking the style of Oriental robes with their silk linings. Two coats were made for the character, one called \"Number 1\" coat and another called \"The Hero\" coat. The Number 1 coat's bullet hole is drawn in, while The Hero version has a detailed cut and sewn repair.<ref>Whedon, ''Firefly Companion, Vol 1'', p.83.</ref> As with the gun, replicas of Malcolm Reynolds' coat have also been made available commercially for fans.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://abbyshot.blogspot.com/2009/11/browncoat-launched-aim-to-misbehave.html  |title=The Malcolm Reynolds Browncoat Replica |website=AbbyShot Blog |date=November 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Character biography==\nMalcolm's main mission is to keep his crew alive and to keep his ship flying. As ''Firefly'' writer Tim Minear stated in an interview: \"It's just about getting by. That's always been the mission statement of what the show is&nbsp;\u2014 getting by.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://tv.zap2it.com/tveditorial/tve_main/1,1002,271%7c78704%7c1%7c,00.html\n |title       = Fox's 'Firefly' Keeps the Lights On\n |website     = Zap2it.com\n |first       = Kate\n |last        = O'Hare\n |date        = October 31, 2002\n |accessdate  = July 4, 2006\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070526111034/http://tv.zap2it.com/tveditorial/tve_main/1,1002,271%7C78704%7C1%7C,00.html\n |archivedate = May 26, 2007\n }}</ref>  In ''Serenity'', Mal says of himself: \"[If the] Wind blows Northerly, I go North.\"<ref name=\"Whedon, Serenity, DVD\">Whedon, ''Serenity'', DVD.</ref>\n\nMal was raised by his mother and \"about 40 hands\" on a ranch on the planet Shadow.<ref>Whedon, ''Firefly: the complete series: \"Our Mrs. Reynolds\"''</ref> Though Mal usually seems more practical than intellectual, he occasionally surprises his friends by displaying familiarity with disparate literature varying from the works of [[Xiang Yu]]<ref>Whedon, ''Firefly: the complete series: \"War Stories\"''</ref> to [[The Rime of the Ancient Mariner|poems]]<ref name=\"Whedon, Serenity, DVD\"/> by [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]], though he has no idea \"who\" [[Mona Lisa]] is.\n\nMal volunteered for the [[Browncoat|Independents]] army during the Unification War against the [[Alliance (Firefly)|Alliance]], gaining the rank of sergeant during that time. His loyal second-in-command [[Zoe Washburne|Zoe]] was by his side for most of the war, surviving many dangerous conflicts with him. The show mentions three such battles, including the Battle of Du-Khang in 2510 (featured in \"[[The Message (Firefly)|The Message]]\") and a long winter campaign in New Kashmir (as told by Zoe in \"[[War Stories (Firefly episode)|War Stories]]\") where he commanded a platoon. Mal was also involved in the ground campaign during the Battle of Sturges (as seen in the comic book ''[[Serenity: Those Left Behind]]''), which according to [[List of minor characters in Firefly#Badger|Badger]] was the \"bloodiest and shortest battle in all the war\", although Mal considers it a distant second. Mal fought in many more battles, but the turning point for him and the Independents came with their physical and emotional defeat at the ''Battle of Serenity Valley'' on the planet [[List of Firefly planets and moons#Hera|Hera]]. On-screen information in ''Serenity'' shows him to have been attached to the 57th Overlanders Brigade; in the series pilot, Badger calls it the \"Balls and Bayonets Brigade\", though it is unclear whether this was a disparaging nickname coined by Badger himself or the actual unit [[sobriquet]] (a deleted scene in ''Serenity'' marks it as the actual unit nickname.  It is unknown if the deleted scene can be considered canon or not).\n\nAfter the war, Mal acquired his own ship, a derelict 03-K64 ''Firefly''-class transport. Mal named the ship ''Serenity'' after the Battle of Serenity Valley, the decisive battle of the Unification War.\n\n==Reception==\nFillion won the \"Cinescape Genre Face of the Future Award&nbsp;\u2014 Male\" award by the Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy & Horror Films, USA for his role as Malcolm Reynolds. Fillion also won the [[SyFy Genre Awards]] in 2006 for ''Best Actor/Television'' and was runner-up for ''Best Actor/Movie''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://syfyportal.com/news.php?id=2895 |title=SyfyPortal Awards |accessdate=October 8, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061107100529/http://www.syfyportal.com/news.php?id=2895 |archivedate=November 7, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe character was named #18 in ''[[TV Guide]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s \"Greatest Sci-fi legends\" list in 2004.<ref name=\"legend\" /> In 2008, ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' ranked Mal as #34 on their list of the 100 Greatest Movie Characters.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=51 |title=The 100 Greatest Movie Characters |magazine=Empire |accessdate=June 11, 2009}}</ref> In 2011, ''[[SFX (magazine)|SFX Magazine]]'' voted Mal Reynolds #1 on their Top 100 Sci-Fi icons of the century.\n\nIn her review of the film ''Serenity'' for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Manohla Dargis]] had this to say about the character and Nathan Fillion: \"Mal is no [[Neo (The Matrix)|Neo]] redux; he's closer to [[Indiana Jones]], if absent [[Harrison Ford]]'s rakishly handsome looks and star magnetism. Like the rest of the cast, Mr. Fillion is a charming performer, but he borrows rather than owns the screen, which dovetails with Mr. Whedon's modest aspirations for this film.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Dargis |first=Manohla |date=September 30, 2005 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/30/movies/scruffy-space-cowboys-fighting-their-failings.html |title=Scruffy Space Cowboys Fighting Their Failings |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|last=Whedon|first=Joss | title=Firefly: The Official Visual Companion, Volume 1 | publisher=Titan Books | location=UK | year=2006 | isbn=1-84576-314-9}}\n*{{cite book | last=Whedon | first=Joss | title=Serenity: The Official Visual Companion | publisher=Titan Books | location=UK | year=2005 | isbn=1-84576-082-4 | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/serenityofficial0000whed }}\n*{{cite video |date=December 9, 2003 |title=The Complete Series: Commentary for \"Serenity\" |people=Whedon, Joss |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}\n*{{cite video |date=December 9, 2003 |title=Firefly (The Series) |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}\n\n{{Firefly}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reynolds, Malcolm}}\n[[Category:Firefly (TV series) characters]]\n[[Category:Science fiction film characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional ship captains]]\n[[Category:Fictional mercenaries]]\n[[Category:Fictional sergeants]]\n[[Category:Fictional smugglers]]\n[[Category:Space pirates]]\n[[Category:Western (genre) characters]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2002]]\n[[Category:Atheism in television]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "name_user": "199.46.251.140", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCharacter biography)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malcolm_Reynolds"}
{"title_page": "Bars and Melody", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Bars and Melody\n| background       = group_or_band\n| caption          = \n| image            = Bars and Melody 2018.jpg\n| alias            = BAM\n| origin           = [[United Kingdom]]\n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| years_active     = 2014\u2013present\n| label            = [[Syco Music]], Zeneration Records, BetterNow Records, Universal Music\n| website          = {{URL|http://barsandmelody.tv/}}\n| current_members  = [[#Members|Leondre Devries <br/>Charlie Lenehan]]\n| past_members     = \n}}\n\n'''Bars and Melody''' (B.A.M.) are a British [[Pop music|pop]] duo consisting of rapper '''Leondre \"Bars\" Devries''' and singer '''Charlie \"Melody\" Lenehan'''<ref name=\"Billboard\" /> who took part in the [[Britain's Got Talent (series 8)|eighth series]] of ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]'' in 2014. During their audition, they were automatically sent into the semifinals of the competition after the head judge, [[Simon Cowell]], pressed the \"golden buzzer.\"<ref name=\"WO Cardiff app\" /> They ultimately finished in third place in the series.<ref name=\"SS Jamie's a Winner\" /><ref name=\"OC Hopeful\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2014-08-09/|title=2014-08-09 Top 40 Official Singles Chart UK Archive|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]}}</ref><ref name=\"PT heartthrobs\" /> They brought out a new song, \"Shining Star\", on 30 July 2014; this was an extra to their acoustic version of the song \"Hopeful\".<ref name=\"LE Bambinos queue\">{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/whats-on/bambinos-queue-hours-outside-hmv-8993843 |title=Bambinos queue for hours outside HMV Liverpool One to meet Bars and Melody | author=Jade Wright |date=7 April 2015 |website=Liverpool Echo |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> Bars and Melody released their debut studio album ''[[143 (album)|143]]'' on 21 August 2015.<ref name=\"CL 143\">{{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/britains-talents-bars--melody-9834520|title=Britain's Got Talent's Bars & Melody line-up two Newcastle dates|website=ChronicleLive|author=Gordon Barr|date=12 August 2015|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> It debuted at number four in the UK.<ref name=\"WO Cardiff app\" /> Two years later, their EP ''[[Teen Spirit (EP)|Teen Spirit]]'' was released.<ref name=\"WO Cardiff app\">{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/britains-talents-bars-melody-coming-11810803 |title=Britain's Got Talent's Bars and Melody are coming to Cardiff and here's how you can meet them | author=Rachel Mainwaring |date=28 August 2016 |website=Wales Online |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> They refer to their fans as \u201cbambinos\" or may refer to them generally as \"bamfam\"\n\nThey have appeared in the UK, the United States, Japan, mainland Europe, and Australia.<ref name=\"PT heartthrobs\">{{cite news|url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/whats-on/bgt-heartthrobs-bars-and-melody-at-the-met-1-7573620 |title=BGT heartthrobs Bars and Melody at The Met  |date=12 September 2016 |website=Peterborough Today |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref>.\n\n==History==\n===2013\u201314: Formation and ''Britain's Got Talent''===\nDevries and Lenehan first met on [[Facebook]]<ref name=\"Billboard\" /> in September 2013, after Devries had seen Lenehan's videos. They first met in person in January 2014 and decided to form a music duo as Bars and Melody.<ref name=\"BP Jones\" />\n\nOn 8 February 2014, Bars and Melody auditioned in [[Manchester]] for the eighth series of ''Britain's Got Talent''. They performed a song based on [[Twista]] and [[Faith Evans]]' \"[[Hope (Twista song)|Hope]]\", with Devries replacing the original verses with ones protesting against [[bullying]]. After the performance, Simon Cowell pressed the golden buzzer, sending them through straight through to the live semifinals.<ref name=\"Billboard\" /><ref name=\"SWEP Leondre\" />\n\nBefore the semifinals, the boys appeared and performed on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-thursdays-tv-highlights-labyrinth-on-ktla-20140521-story.html |title=Thursday's (May 22) TV Highlights: 'Labyrinth' on KTLA | author= |date=21 May 2014 |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> In the ''BGT'' semi-final on 29 May, they performed [[Puff Daddy]] and Faith Evans' \"[[I'll Be Missing You]]\", coupled with new verses about someone who had recently lost a friend; audience members were given candles to wave during the performance. They won their semi-final and progressed through to the final,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/showbiz/479142/Britain-s-Got-Talent-2014-Bars-Melody-and-Lettice-Rowbotham-reach-final|title=Britain's Got Talent: Bars & Melody and Lettice Rowbotham book final spots|last=Dassanayake|first=Dion|date=29 May 2014|work=[[Daily Express]]|publisher=[[Northern & Shell]]|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref> where they performed the song they sang in their audition and ultimately finished third behind Lucy Kay and [[Collabro]].<ref name=\"SS Jamie's a Winner\" >{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-36140438.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226212829/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-36140438.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 February 2017|title=Jamie's a Winner as Collabro Get a Huge Thumbs Up|location=Newcastle-upon-Tyne|author=Alex Finnis|date=8 June 2014|work=[[Sunday Sun]]|accessdate=25 February 2017 |via=HighBeam Research|url-access=subscription }}</ref> According to [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] magazine, the video of their audition was number six in the top ten trending videos for 2014 and it is still the most viewed out of all the auditions of BGT with more than 200 million views.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6397791/watch-youtubes-2014-rewind-video-with-music-from-dj-earworm |title=Watch YouTube's 2014 Rewind Video, With Music From DJ Earworm | author=Elias Leight |date=9 December 2014 |website=Billboard |accessdate=February 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u201315: ''143''===\n{{Main|143 (album)}}\nDespite not  winning, Bars and Melody signed a \u00a3500,000 record deal with Simon Cowell's record label,<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/6207987/bars-and-melody/biography |title=Biography | author=John D. Buchanan, Rovi |website= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> [[Syco Music|Syco]], which released \"Hopeful\" in July 2014.<ref name=\"Billboard\" /> Their debut single went straight to number five on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"OC Hopeful\" /> The music video of their song \"Hopeful\" was released on YouTube on 7 July 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.reveal.co.uk/lifestyle/news/a582910/britains-got-talent-stars-bars-and-melody-unveil-hopeful-music-video.html|title=Britain's Got Talent stars Bars and Melody unveil 'Hopeful' music video|last=Heath|first=Olivia|date=8 July 2014|work=Reveal|publisher=[[Nat Mags]]|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://imvdb.com/video/bars-and-melody/hopeful |title=Hopeful (2014) | author=\nMax & Dania (director) |date= |website=IMVdB |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> To promote the song, they appeared on television shows such as ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/goodmorningbritain/entertainment/bars-and-melody-are-number-two |title='Our parents didn't speak for at least three days!' | author= |date=1 August 2014 |website=Good Morning Britain |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/thismorning/showbiz/bars-and-melody-britains-got-talent-hopeful |title=Bars and Melody make Hopeful debut | author= |date=27 July 2014 |website=This Morning |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> and ''[[The Official Chart]]'' on [[BBC Radio 1]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01pq7sq/p02453tp |title=Bars and Melody pop in to see Jameela!  |website=BBC |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> By late September, the song \"Hopeful\" was number 33 on the [[Twitter Top Tracks]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6266489/social-charts-kendrick-lamar-one-direction |title=Kendrick Lamar, One Direction Highlight Social Chart Action | author=William Gruger |date=26 September 2014 |website=Billboard |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nBars and Melody also participated in their first [[HMV]] signing tour to promote ''Hopeful''. They released the song \"Shining Star\", which came out as part of ''Hopeful Acoustic''.<ref name=\"LE Bambinos queue\" /> Their second single, \"[[Keep Smiling (Bars and Melody song)|Keep Smiling]]\", was released on 28 February 2015,<ref name=\"UK\" /> with a music video filmed in [[Plymouth]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/bars-melody-prepare-release-second-8589201 |title=Bars and Melody prepare for release of second single after BGT success | author=Emma Sisk |date=7 February 2015 |website=Wales Online |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"WO Easter egg\">{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/bars-melody-prepare-release-second-8589201 |title=BGT's Bars and Melody release their very own Easter egg | author=Kate Rees |date=17 March 2015 |website=Wales Online |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> It peaked at 52 in the [[Official Charts Company]].<ref name=\"UK\" /> Their third official single, \"[[Stay Strong (song)|Stay Strong]]\", was released on 18 April 2015 and peaked at 53 in the Official Charts Company.<ref name=\"UK\" /> Two physical editions of the CD could be purchased with each one containing an image of either Lenehan or Devries, promoted through a second HMV signing tour.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/bars-melody-meet-adoring-bambinos-city-s-hmv/story-26314321-detail/story.html |title=Bars and Melody meet their adoring 'Bambinos' in city's hmv |author=David W Owen |date=10 April 2015 |website=Leicester Mercury |accessdate=25 February 2017 |quote=See photograph showing Lenehan and Devries each holding their versions of the single with their photographs on the cover. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813143106/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Bars-Melody-meet-adoring-Bambinos-city-s-hmv/story-26314321-detail/story.html |archive-date=13 August 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> They released their fourth single \"Beautiful\" in June 2015 alongside a music video.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bars-and-melody-mn0003282589/biography|title=Bars and Melody biography|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe boys released their debut album, ''[[143 (album)|143]]'', on 21 August 2015,<ref name=\"CL 143\" /> which peaked at number four on the [[UK Albums Chart]] on 28 August 2015.<ref name=\"WO Cardiff app\" /> The album included their previously recorded singles and additional songs. To promote the album, they toured across the United Kingdom in the summer and had a winter tour in the United Kingdom, the Netherlands and Poland,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-39654928.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226212741/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-39654928.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 February 2017 |title=BGT Duo's Gig at Slade Rooms |date=19 May 2016 |newspaper=The Tamworth Herald |accessdate=25 February 2017 |via=HighBeam Research|url-access=subscription }}</ref> where the album went [[Platinum album|platinum]].<ref name=\"WM duo sign\">{{cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-461838674.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226212633/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-461838674.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 February 2017 |title=Pop Rap Duo in Signing Appearance |date=29 August 2016 |newspaper=Western Mail |location=Cardiff, Wales |accessdate=25 February 2017 |via=HighBeam Research|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nFollowing a guest presenting stint in 2014,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-29062673 |title=CBBC's Friday Download heads to the big screen | author=Entertainment & Arts |date=4 September 2014 |website= BBC|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> Bars and Melody made a red carpet appearance at the premiere of [[CBBC]] show ''[[Friday Download]]'' in May 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/entertainment/up-all-night-stars-dionne-bromfield-and-tyger-drew-honey-reveal-their-holiday-nightmares-676502.html |title=Up All Night stars Dionne Bromfield and Tyger Drew-Honey reveal their holiday nightmares | author= |date=10 May 2015 |website=Irish Examiner |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> They also participated in the ''Friday Download'' movie called ''Up All Night''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.j-14.com/posts/the-vamps-friday-download-the-movie-up-all-night-75913 |title=The Vamps 'Friday Download, The Movie (Up All Night)' | author=Heather Thompson |date=31 October 2015 |website=J-14 |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> They performed the third ending theme \"Unite (Live Forever)\" for the anime series ''[[Future Card Buddyfight|Future Card Buddyfight Triple D]]''.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}} They appeared on [[BBC]]'s ''[[Newsround]]'' during a week-long series about bullying in February 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsround/30122787 |title=Greg James, Niki and Sammy, Bars and Melody on bullying | author= |date=20 February 2015 |website=BBC's Newsround |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\n{{Main|Teen Spirit (EP)}}\nIn 2016, they toured five cities with [[Kiera Weathers]], a contestant on ''[[The X Factor]]'', in February and April of that year. The cities included [[London]], [[Birmingham]], [[Bristol]], [[Glasgow]], and [[Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/the-x-factor/news/a779432/x-factors-kiera-weathers-to-join-britains-got-talents-bars-and-melody-on-uk-tour/ |title=X Factor's Kiera Weathers to join Britain's Got Talent's Bars and Melody on UK Tour | author=Ian Sandwell |date=10 January 2016 |website= Digital Spy|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> They also became ambassadors for the Anti Bullying Charity campaign that year.<ref name=\"WO Cardiff app\" /> In August 2016, their album ''[[Teen Spirit (EP)|Teen Spirit]]'' was released by Syco.<ref name=\"WO Cardiff app\" /> They toured Australia and Japan by August 2016.<ref name=\"WM duo sign\" />\n\nIn August 2016 they released their first Japanese album, titled Hopeful by [[Avex Music Creative]], including fourteen tracks from the UK albums 143 and Teen Spirit as well as UK and Japanese versions of Hopeful.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Bars-And-Melody-Hopeful/release/9328834|title=Bars And Melody - Hopeful|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2017-05-03}}</ref>\n\nThey toured thirteen cities in Austria, Germany and Switzerland in November and December, opening for German teen singer [[Lukas Rieger]] .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juiceorcider.com/2016/11/13/bars-melody-tour-german-speaking-countries/|title=Bars and Melody to tour German-speaking countries \u2013 Juice or Cider|access-date=2017-05-03}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017 - \"Generation Z\" ===\nOn 15 February 2017 they released their second Japanese Album, titled Never Give Up, for distribution in Asia, by Rhythm Sound, a division of [[Avex Music Creative]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Bars-And-Melody-Never-Give-Up/release/9835988|title=Bars And Melody - Never Give Up|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2017-05-03}}</ref> In April they announced the future release of a new album, titled ''Generation Z'', scheduled for September 2017 as well as the immediate digital release of new song Faded on 14 April.<ref name=\"News - BarsandMelody.tv\">{{cite web|url=http://barsandmelody.tv/news/|title=News - BarsandMelody.tv|website=BarsandMelody.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420030456/http://barsandmelody.tv/news/|archive-date=20 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> In April they toured ten cities in the UK opening for the dance troupe [[Diversity (dance troupe)|Diversity]].<ref name=\"News - BarsandMelody.tv\"/> On 27 May they released a song from Generation Z called \"Thousand Years,\" which has a music video with over 28 million views on Youtube as of 14 November 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/BarsAndMelody/status/868100169853800449|title=Bars and Melody on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2017-05-28|language=en}}</ref> On 1 September they released Generation Z, featuring the said songs along with Not A Love Song, Fast Car, and others. The album has 13 songs in total.\n\n=== 2018 ===\nIn early 2018, Bars and Melody went on their ''Generation Z'' Tour around Europe. On 12 October 2018, they released a single called Put \u00dc First. They also announced and had shows in Tokyo, Nagoya and Osaka, Japan in December.\n\n=== 2019 ===\nIn early 2019, Bars and Melody released a single from their upcoming album called \"Love To See Me Fail.\" Just a few weeks after that, Bars and Melody embarked on their ''Choke Tour'' from late March to mid-May. On 26 July, they released their long-awaited single \"Waiting for the Sun\" on Youtube, Apple Music, and Spotify. In late August, they competed on ''[[Britain's Got Talent: The Champions|Britain's Got Talent The Champions]]'' where they sang ''Waiting for the Sun'' in week 5, getting through the audience vote to the final the following week, where they sang their then-newest song ''Lighthouse''. On 13 September, a German/English song they had a feature on from [https://de.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Die_Lochis Die Lochis] called [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=It-XUxZ-aSk Killa] released. On 4 October, they released their single ''Lighthouse,'' which would be on their new album releasing in 2020. They also set to embark on their primarily-UK tour ''Lighthouse'' from October until early November, along with 3 shows in Japan in mid-January 2020. On 6 December, Bars and Melody released a teaser of an upcoming single via Instagram and a week later on 13 December, they released the single (and their first feature ever) from the album called Teenage Romance, featuring [[Mike Singer]]. On 7 December, they announced their album ''Sadboi'' would be released in 2020. To finish off the year, on 20 December, they announced ''Sadboi Tour,'' which would be set across Europe, with Charlie hinting it'd be a \"world tour.\"\n\n=== 2020 - \"Sadboi Era\" ===\n\nOn 29 January, Bars and Melody took it to Instagram to announce the track list for their upcoming album ''Sadboi''. The album would consist of 12 tracks which included previous singles \"Love to See Me Fail, \"Waiting For The Sun\", \"Lighthouse\" and \"Teenage Romance\". It was originally set for release on 6 March, however, it had to be delayed due to problems with the album shipment. On 6 March, their new single \"Ain\u2019t Got You\" was released. On 13 March, they made a surprise drop with their new song \u2018Invisible\u2019. On 27 March 2020, their album was finally released. In late March, they had to postpone their ''Sadboi'' tour due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 outbreak.]] Some concerts were cancelled and others were postponed.\n\n==Members==\n===Leondre Devries (Bars)===\nLeondre Antonio Devries was born on 6 October  2000<ref name=\"Billboard\" /> to stonemason Antonio and personal trainer Victoria Lee.<ref name=\"WO open up\" /><ref name=\"SWEP video\">{{cite video|author=G Roberts|url=http://www.southwales-eveningpost.co.uk/Britain-s-Got-Talent-2014-Leondre-Devries-Bars/story-21199672-detail/story.html |title=Britain's Got Talent 2014: Leondre Devries from Bars and Melody tells all |publisher=South Wales Evening Post |date=7 June 2014|accessdate=25 February 2017|time=0:34}}</ref> From [[Port Talbot]], [[Neath Port Talbot]], Wales, he has three older brothers\u2014Jacob Lee, Joseph Devries (Joey), the eldest is Ben Lee \u2014and a younger sister, Matilda Devries (Tilly).<ref name=\"WO open up\" /> Joey was part of the boy band [[Overload Generation]] who participated in the [[The X Factor (UK series 11)|eleventh series]] of ''The X Factor''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/x-factor-overload-generation-second-7920625?pageNumber=17 |title=X Factor: Overload Generation is second Welsh act to make it through to live stages of talent show | author=Sandra Loy |date=11 October 2014 |website=Wales Online |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> Leondre Devries has spoken openly about his experiences of bullying for four years before he switched schools.<ref name=\"WO open up\" /> He attended the Glan Afan Comprehensive School at the time of the ''Britain's Got Talent'' competition.<ref name=\"SWEP Leondre\">{{cite news|author=G Roberts|url=http://www.southwales-eveningpost.co.uk/Britain-s-Got-Talent-2014-Leondre-Devries-Bars/story-21199672-detail/story.html |title=Britain's Got Talent 2014: Leondre from Bars and Melody tells all |newspaper=South Wales Evening Post |date=7 June 2014|accessdate=15 June 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714193439/http://www.southwales-eveningpost.co.uk/Britain-s-Got-Talent-2014-Leondre-Devries-Bars/story-21199672-detail/story.html|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref> Previously he rapped solo under the stage name 'Little Dre'.<ref name=\"WO open up\">{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/britains-talent-2014-bars-melody-7184915 |title=Britain's Got Talent 2014: Bars and Melody open up on their meteoric rise to fame|date=29 May 2014|work=Wales Online|accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> His father said that Leondre lived with him until he appeared on ''Britain's Got Talent'', and after that has lived with his mother.<ref name=\"YN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/britains-got-talent-stars-bars-and-melody-being-115755985.html |title=Britain\u2019s Got Talent Stars Bars And Melody Being Sued By Member\u2019s Own DAD | author=Adele Ankers |date=25 March 2016 |website=Yahoo News |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> Although Leondre said that his father was a stonemason during the contest,<ref name=\"SWEP video\" /> his father now says he is a music promoter.<ref name=\"YN\" />\n\n===Charlie Lenehan (Melody)===\nCharlie Lenehan was born 27 October 1998 in [[Frampton Cotterell]].<ref name=\"Billboard\" /> He lives in [[Cologne, Germany]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/barsandmelody/status/1083478258119860224?lang=en-gb |title=Twitter |publisher=Mobile.twitter.com |date=2019-01-10 |accessdate=2019-06-03}}</ref> He has a family that consists of his mother, a school cook; his step-father, a businessman;<ref>{{cite video|author=G Roberts|url=http://www.southwales-eveningpost.co.uk/Britain-s-Got-Talent-2014-Leondre-Devries-Bars/story-21199672-detail/story.html |title=Britain's Got Talent 2014: Leondre Devries from Bars and Melody tells all |publisher=South Wales Evening Post |date=7 June 2014|accessdate=25 February 2017|time=0:42}}</ref> he has a younger sister, Brooke. His mother, Karen James, is a cook in [[Thornbury, Gloucestershire|Thornbury]] at [[Thornbury, Gloucestershire#Schools|Gillingstool and New Siblands schools]].<ref name=\"Gazette\">{{cite news|url= http://www.gazetteseries.co.uk/NEWS/11267350.Mum_tells_of_pride_at_son_s_third_place_on_Britain_s_Got_Talent/|title=Mum of Bars and Melody singer Charlie Lineman is 'over the moon' after 15-year-old comes third on Britain's Got Talent | author=Alexandra Womack |date=10 June 2014 |website=Gazette|publisher=Newsquest Media |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> Charlie took up singing at the age of 11 when his schoolmates invited him to join a band.<ref name=\"Billboard\" /> He has been attending the [[The Ridings' Federation Winterbourne International Academy|Winterbourne International Academy]]<ref name=\"BP Jones\" /> since he was 11, and was interested in drama, music, and engineering at the time of the competition. He returned to school the first day after the ''Britain's Got Talent'' finale.<ref name=\"Gazette\" />\n\n==Lawsuit==\nAntonio Devries, Leondre's father, threatened to file a suit against the group in March 2016, saying that he wrote ''Hopeful'' due to troubles that he was having in his life.<ref name=\"YN\" /> He claims that he helped promote the boys until their ''Britain's Got Talent'' contest, is unhappy that the boys are moving away from the anti-bullying theme, and claims that their management overworks them. He says that he does not have any issues with Bars and Melody,<ref name=\"YN\" /><ref name=\"Metro dad\" /> but he took over the boy's social media accounts and posted music from his son Joey and other artists he represents until the management team regained control of the accounts.<ref name=\"BP Jones\">{{cite news |url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/exclusive-britain-s-got-talent-favourites-bars/story-28987126-detail/story.html#oCOYkLrl7wu42B5l.99 |title=Exclusive: Britain's Got Talent stars Bars and Melody sued by dad |author=Craig Jones |date=24 March 2016 |website=Bristol Post |accessdate=25 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326165339/http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Exclusive-Britain-s-Got-Talent-favourites-Bars/story-28987126-detail/story.html#oCOYkLrl7wu42B5l.99 |archive-date=26 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The management team, who Devries says is the root of the problem, have stated that the boys wrote \"Hopeful\". A spokesperson for the boys says that they are happy with their career and management team and do not feel exploited or overworked.<ref name=\"YN\" /><ref name=\"Metro dad\">{{cite news|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/03/25/britains-got-talents-bars-and-melody-are-being-sued-by-one-of-their-dads-5776219/#ixzz4ZiGQZMcA |title=Britain's Got Talent's Bars And Melody are being sued by one of their dads | author=Katie Baillie |date=25 March 2016 |website=Metro |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> They also said, \"Bars and Melody are sorry to hear that legal action is being threatened and they hope it will [be] resolved quickly and amicably.\"<ref name=\"YN\" />\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"5\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Certification\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br/><ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/32739/bars-and-melody/|title=Bars & Melody|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|work=Officialcharts.com}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[GfK Entertainment Charts|GER]]<br/><ref name=\"GER\">{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/suche?artist_search=Bars+and+Melody&do_search=do|title=Discographie Bars and Melody|publisher=[[GfK Entertainment Charts]]|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Irish Albums Chart|IRE]]<br/><ref name=\"IRE\">{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Bars+And+Melody|title=Discography Bars and Melody|work=Irish Charts Portal